{"title_page": "Nova Scotia killings", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of shootings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, Nova Scotia\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = Portapique, NS\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n|      label2      = Enfield, Nova Scotia\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title2       = Enfield, NS\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree shooting]], [[arson]], [[mass murder]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 20 (including the perpetrator)\n| injuries         = At least 2\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nThe '''Nova Scotia killings''' took place between April 18 and April 19, 2020 in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] when Gabriel Wortman raped, shot and killed (not necessarily in that order) at least 191 people and set fire to at least five buildings before being killed by the police following a car chase.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among 17 confirmed dead in Nova Scotia killing spree|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/canada/rcmp-say-in-excess-of-19-victims-in-n-s-rampage-1.4903398|title=RCMP say 'in excess of 19 victims' in N.S. rampage|date=2020-04-20|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The attack took place from the late hours of April 18 to the morning of April 19 and ended when Wortman was shot dead by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=At Least 16 Killed in Nova Scotia Shooting, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. (UTC-3) on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\" /> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1|911]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.\n\nThen, at around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately 37 kilometres (23 mi) north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of Wentworth Valley, on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the RCMP to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was sighted in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 17 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer]] and operating a replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 16 in rural Canada|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later stated that this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly twelve hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside a gas station restaurant at the [[Irving Oil]] Big Stop in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /> The [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, and at least two other police use-of-force incidents.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather stated that there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said that he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n== Victims ==\nAt least 19 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them Constable Stevenson, a 23-year veteran of the police force. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims, who included an elementary school teacher and a nurse,<ref name=\"BBC-52346447\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Gunman kills at least 16 in rural Canada|date=20 April 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420075915/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52346447\" /> The RCMP expects to find more victims within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|author=Meredith MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Perpetrator ==\nThe RCMP identified Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19th after he was pronounced dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=2020-04-19|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called Wortman's home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two police cruisers he bought near his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by authorities to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> However, neighbours said that Wortman struggled with alcoholism, and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/20/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=After Nova Scotia Shooting, Families Mourn as Police Seek a Motive|first=Iliana|last=Magra|date=April 20, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=2020 Nova Scotia attacks|2=Talk:Nova Scotia killings#Requested move 20 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{pp-move-dispute|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Series of shootings in Nova Scotia, Canada}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Current|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title            = Nova Scotia killings\n{{OSM Location map\n| coord            = {{coord|45.1965|-63.3377}}\n|  zoom            = 7\n| float            = center\n| width            = 300\n| height           = 206\n| caption          =\n|   title          =\n|    minimap       = file\n|  mini-file       = Canada location map.svg\n| mini-width       = 120\n|mini-height       = 64\n|  minipog-x       = 105\n|  minipog-y       = 48\n|  scalemark       = 120 <!-- shifts the scalemark further to the left -->\n|      shape1      = image\n|       mark1      = Red pog.svg\n|      label1      = Portapique, Nova Scotia\n| mark-coord1      = {{coord|45.4015|-63.6977}}\n|  label-pos1      = bottom\n| label-size1      = 10\n|label-color1      = black\n| label-offset-x1  =\n| label-offset-y1  =\n|mark-title1       = Portapique, NS\n|mark-image1       =\n|mark-description1 =\n|      label2      = Enfield, Nova Scotia\n|       mark2      = Red pog.svg\n| mark-size2       = 8\n|  label-pos2      = left\n| label-size2      = 10\n|label-color2      = black\n| mark-coord2      = {{coord|44.9274|-63.5366}}\n|mark-title2       = Enfield, NS\n}}\n| partof           = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| map              = \n| map_size         = \n| map_alt          = \n| map_caption      = Portapique in Nova Scotia\n| susperp          = \n| location         = [[Nova Scotia]], Canada\n| target           = \n| date             = {{start date|2020|4|18}}\u2013{{end date|2020|4|19}}\n| time             = \n| timezone         = [[UTC\u221203:00]]\n| coordinates      = \n| type             = [[Spree shooting]], [[arson]], [[mass murder]]\n| weapons          = Firearm(s)\n| fatalities       = At least 20 (including the perpetrator)\n| injuries         = At least 2\n| victim           = \n| perp             = Gabriel Wortman\n| numparts         = \n| numpart          = \n| dfens            = \n| dfen             = \n| footage          = \n| motive           = Under investigation\n}}\n\nThe '''Nova Scotia killings''' took place between April 18 and April 19, 2020 in the [[Canadian province]] of [[Nova Scotia]] when Gabriel Wortman shot and killed at least 19 people and set fire to at least five buildings before being killed by the police following a car chase.<ref name=\"CBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among 17 confirmed dead in Nova Scotia killing spree|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419130936/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/mobile/canada/rcmp-say-in-excess-of-19-victims-in-n-s-rampage-1.4903398|title=RCMP say 'in excess of 19 victims' in N.S. rampage|date=2020-04-20|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> The attack took place from the late hours of April 18 to the morning of April 19 and ended when Wortman was shot dead by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIt is the deadliest attack involving the use of firearms in Canadian history, surpassing the 1989 [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]], during which 15 people were killed.<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|title=16 killed in shooting rampage, deadliest in Canadian history|last=Gillies|first=Rob|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202425/https://apnews.com/7c9a33ae52420e0ddbfb5275898a7e79|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Police say the motive has not yet been established.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\">{{Cite news|last=Diaz|first=Johnny|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=At Least 16 Killed in Nova Scotia Shooting, Police Say|date=April 19, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419142013/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|archive-date=April 19, 2020|last2=Bilefsky|first2=Dan}}</ref><ref name=\"Politico\">{{cite news|last=Blatchford|first=Andy|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/19/at-least-10-dead-in-canadian-shooting-rampage-195506|title=Gunman kills at least 16, including officer, in Nova Scotia|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\nAt 11:32 p.m. (UTC-3) on April 18,<ref name=\"CBC\" /> police responded to multiple [[9-1-1|911]] calls regarding a gun-related incident in the community of [[Portapique]], {{convert|130|km|mi}} north of [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\"/><ref name=\"CBC2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|title=Timeline: How an active-shooter situation unfolded in Nova Scotia|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420001136/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/nova-scotia-timeline-active-shooter-portapique-1.5537756|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/canadian-authorities-say-mass-shooting-suspect-may-have-been-disguised-n1187381|title=16 dead, including officer, in shooting, Canadian authorities say|last1=Madani|first1=Doha|last2=Stelloh|first2=Tim|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|title=Nova Scotia mass killings: What we know and what we don't know|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420034520/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-what-we-know-what-we-don-t-1.5537918|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They found several dead and injured inside and outside of a home, but no suspect.<ref name=\"ABC\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/multiple-victims-canada-shooting-suspect-dressed-police-officer/story?id=70232582|title=16 dead, including police officer, in deadliest shooting in Canadian history|last=Deliso|first=Meredith|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> The investigation overnight led police to multiple separate crime scenes that were scattered over a distance of at least {{convert|50|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /> By the morning of April 19, police announced that they were dealing with an [[active shooter]] situation.\n\nThen, at around 8:00 a.m., a 9-1-1 caller reported \"an explosion and gunfire\" at a house on Hunter Road in [[Wentworth, Nova Scotia|Wentworth]], approximately 37 kilometres (23 mi) north of Portapique. Two residents and a neighbour were later confirmed to be victims. Another victim was then allegedly shot and killed while walking in the community of Wentworth Valley, on the road between Wentworth and Portapique.<ref name=\"CBC4\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killing-shooting-victims-remembered-1.5538032|title=Teacher, family of 3 and RCMP officer among victims of N.S. shooting rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nResidents were advised by the RCMP to stay indoors, while a portion of Portapique was evacuated.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /><ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"MassLive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.masslive.com/news/2020/04/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman-kills-16-including-police-officer-in-canadas-deadliest-shooting-attack.html|title=Nova Scotia shooting: Gabriel Wortman kills 16 including police officer in Canada's deadliest shooting attack|publisher=MassLive|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was identified as the shooter at 8:54 a.m.<ref name=\"CBC\" /> Between 10:04 and 11:24, he was sighted in or near [[Glenholme]], [[Debert]], [[Brookfield, Nova Scotia|Brookfield]], and [[Milford (Halifax), Nova Scotia|Milford]].<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CTV\">{{cite news|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shot-and-killed-by-police-1.4902687|title=At least 17 people killed in N.S. shooting; deadliest such attack in Canada: police|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|publisher=CTV News}}</ref> During this time, police warned that he was [[police impersonation|dressed as an RCMP officer]] and operating a replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6840120/nova-scotia-shooting-timeline/|title=Timeline of what we know about Nova Scotia killing spree that left RCMP officer, 16 others dead|publisher=Global News|last=Shah|first=Maryam|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|title=A timeline of the deadly shooting incident in Nova Scotia|last=Lopez-Martinez|first=Melissa|date=April 19, 2020|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420053707/https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/a-timeline-of-the-deadly-shooting-incident-in-nova-scotia-1.4902954|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The public was urged to avoid these areas,<ref name=global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s>{{Cite news|title=17 dead, including one RCMP officer, after shooting spree in Portapique, N.S.|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|last=Quon|first=Alexander|date=April 19, 2020|access-date=April 19, 2020|publisher=[[Global News]]|last2=Stephenson|first2=Mercedes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419202613/https://globalnews.ca/news/6838880/rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s/|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and to call 9-1-1 immediately if they spotted the fake RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"ABC\" /> An hour later, officials said that Wortman had switched to a silver [[Chevrolet Tracker (Americas)|Chevrolet Tracker]] [[sports utility vehicle]] (SUV).<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Canada shooting: Gunman kills at least 16 in rural Canada|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200419211041/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 19, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAround this time, the community of [[Shubenacadie, Nova Scotia|Shubenacadie]] was named as the site of a \"serious criminal event.\"<ref name=\"CBC\" /> A resident of the community reported that they saw two burning vehicles along [[Nova Scotia Trunk 2]], including at least one police car, and that they heard an exchange of gunfire between an RCMP officer and a man who ran toward them.<ref name=\"CBC5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/rcmp-weapon-lockdown-portapique-1.5537598|title=RCMP officer among the dead after Nova Scotia gunman's rampage|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Officials later stated that this was where Wortman shot and killed RCMP Constable Heidi Stevenson, and that one of the burning cars was Wortman's replica RCMP vehicle.<ref name=\"CBC6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/mass-killings-shooting-community-reaction-1.5538181|title=Death toll from Nova Scotia gunman's rampage climbs to 19|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=April 20, 2020|date=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNearly twelve hours after police first received the firearms complaint,<ref name=\"Vox\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2020/4/19/21227349/mass-shooting-nova-scotia-canada-enfield-portapique|title=What we know about a mass shooting in Nova Scotia, Canada|publisher=Vox|last=Collins|first=Sean|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Wortman was killed by police outside a gas station restaurant at the [[Irving Oil]] Big Stop in [[Enfield, Nova Scotia|Enfield]], about {{convert|92|km|mi}} south of Portapique and about {{convert|40|km|mi}} north of Halifax.<ref name=\"CBC2\" /><ref name=\"CTV\" /> The [[Serious Incident Response Team]] announced it would be conducting an investigation into the officer-involved shooting, and at least two other police use-of-force incidents.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\nBy the afternoon of April 20, RCMP Chief Superintendent Chris Leather stated that there were 16 crime scenes in total, including five structure fires. He said that he expected the death toll to continue to rise as these were investigated further.<ref name=\"CBC6\" />\n\n== Victims ==\nAt least 19 people were killed (excluding Wortman), one of them Constable Stevenson, a 23-year veteran of the police force. A second RCMP officer was injured and is in stable condition.<ref name=\"CBC\" /><ref name=\"global-news-rcmp-active-shooter-portapique-n-s\" /> According to Commissioner [[Brenda Lucki]], some of the first victims had connections to Wortman, but as the killings continued, the targets became more random.<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> The victims, who included an elementary school teacher and a nurse,<ref name=\"BBC-52346447\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52346447|title=Gunman kills at least 16 in rural Canada|date=20 April 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420075915/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-52346447|archive-date=April 20, 2020|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref> are believed to have died from gunshot wounds, but other causes are also being investigated.<ref name=\"CBC3\" /><ref name=\"BBC-52346447\" /> The RCMP expects to find more victims within the remnants of five structure fires.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/canada/nova-scotia-rampage-results-in-18-victims-16-crime-scenes-1.4903398|title=Nova Scotia rampage results in 18 victims, 16 crime scenes|date=April 20, 2020|work=[[CTV News]]|author=Meredith MacLeod|accessdate=April 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Perpetrator ==\nThe RCMP identified Wortman, a [[denturist]] working in the Halifax area, on April 19th after he was pronounced dead. He owned real estate in Portapique and [[Dartmouth, Nova Scotia|Dartmouth]].<ref name=\"CBC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/20/nova-scotia-shooting-gunman-profile-quiet-gentle-denturist|title=Nova Scotia shooting: shock and surprise at killings by denturist|first=Leyland|last=Cecco|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 19, 2020|website=The Guardian}}</ref> He attended [[Riverview High School (New Brunswick)|Riverview High School]] in New Brunswick and aspired to be a police officer.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/just-unbelievable-neighbours-of-nova-scotia-shooting-suspect-shocked-by-news-1.4903021|title='Just unbelievable': Neighbours of Nova Scotia shooting suspect shocked by news|date=2020-04-19|website=CTV News|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\nWortman was shown to have had a degree of obsession for policing, with a hobby of buying law enforcement memorabilia and refurbishing old police cruisers. One person called Wortman's home a \"shrine\" for the RCMP.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|title=Nova Scotia mass shooter was a denturist with an obsession for policing|publisher=The Globe and Mail|last1=Woo|first1=Andrew|last2=Mercer|first2=Greg|date=April 19, 2020|accessdate=April 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420055810/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/article-nova-scotia-mass-shooter-was-a-denturist-with-an-obsession-for/|archive-date=April 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He stored the two police cruisers he bought near his dental clinic.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nNo motive has been established for the killings, and it is not considered by authorities to be an act of [[terrorism in Canada|terrorism]].<ref name=\"nyt-nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman\" /> However, neighbours said that Wortman struggled with alcoholism, and his profitable business was impacted by the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nova Scotia|coronavirus pandemic]], which forced all non-essential dental services to cease.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/20/world/canada/nova-scotia-shooting-gabriel-wortman.html|title=After Nova Scotia Shooting, Families Mourn as Police Seek a Motive|first=Iliana|last=Magra|date=April 20, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n[[Nova Scotia Premier]] [[Stephen McNeil]] told reporters, \"This is one of the most senseless acts of violence in our province's history.\" He expressed his condolences to the residents affected and the families of the victims.<ref name=\"CTV2\">{{cite news|url=https://atlantic.ctvnews.ca/shooting-one-of-the-most-senseless-acts-of-violence-in-nova-scotia-s-history-premier-1.4902917|title=Shooting 'one of the most senseless acts of violence' in Nova Scotia's history: premier|last=Jerrett|first=Andrea|publisher=CTV News|accessdate=April 19, 2020|date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] also expressed his condolences.<ref name=\"CBC\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]\n* [[Moncton shooting]]\n* [[List of massacres in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2020 crimes in Canada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings]]\n[[Category:2020 mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:2020 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2020s mass shootings in North America]]\n[[Category:21st-century mass murder in North America]]\n[[Category:April 2020 crimes]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in Canada]]\n[[Category:Arson in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2020]]\n[[Category:Crime in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Death in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass shootings in Canada]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in Canada]]\n[[Category:Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "85.221.156.88", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nova_Scotia_killings"}
{"title_page": "R. Carey Davis", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = R. Carey Davis\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| order = \n| office = [[List of mayors of San Bernardino, California|Mayor of San Bernardino]]\n| term_start = March 3, 2014\n| term_end = December 19, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Pat Morris (politician)|Pat Morris]]\n| successor = [[John Valdivia]]\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[San Bernardino, California]], U.S.\n| citizenship = United States\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| children = 4\n| spouse = Johnetta Davis\n| residence = San Bernardino, California\n| profession = [[Certified Public Accountant|CPA]]\n| alma_mater = [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]] <small>([[bachelor's degree]])</small><ref name=\"OfficialBio\"/><br>[[California State University, San Bernardino]]<small>([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])</small>\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Learish|first1=Jessica|title=Who Is R. Carey Davis, San Bernardino's Mayor? People Will Be Looking To Him For Leadership|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/127277-who-is-r-carey-davis-san-bernardinos-mayor-people-will-be-looking-to-him-for-leadership|website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|accessdate=8 December 2015|date=2 December 2015|quote=Davis, a Republican and political newcomer, was elected mayor of San Bernardino in 2014 in the wake of the city declaring bankruptcy.}}</ref>\n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Richard Carey Davis''' formerly served as the mayor of San Bernardino,California. He served as the 28th mayor of the city. Davis was elected mayor [[2014 San Bernardino mayoral election|in 2014]]. He lost [[2018 San Bernardino mayoral election|the general election]] on November 6, 2018, after advancing from the primary on June 5, 2018.\n\n==Early life and education==\nDavis was born in [[San Bernardino, California|San Bernardino]] and graduated from [[Pacific High School (San Bernardino, California)|Pacific High School]] there.<ref name=\"Professionalism\"/> He received his bachelor's degree from [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]]<ref name=\"OfficialBio\">[http://www.sbcity.org/cityhall/mayor/about_the_mayor/default.asp About the Mayor: Mayor R. Carey Davis], City of San Bernardino (accessed December 3, 2015).</ref> and his [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[California State University, San Bernardino]].<ref name=\"OfficialBio\"/><ref name=\"Professionalism\"/>\n\n==Career==\nDavis is a [[certified public accountant]].<ref name=\"YarbroughHagen\">Beau Yarbrough & Ryan Hagen, [http://www.sbsun.com/government-and-politics/20140204/carey-davis-elected-san-bernardino-mayor Carey Davis elected San Bernardino mayor], ''The Sun'' (February 5, 2014).</ref>  who works as a controller in Los Angeles for Hehr International, a manufacturer of [[Recreational vehicle|RV]] doors and windows.<ref name=\"Professionalism\">Ryan Hagen, [http://www.sbsun.com/government-and-politics/20140202/carey-davis-vote-for-professionalism-in-san-bernardino-mayor Carey Davis: Vote for professionalism in San Bernardino mayor], ''The Sun'' (February 2, 2014).</ref>\n\nHe became involved in city politics in spring 2013.<ref name=\"YarbroughHagen\"/> He ran for mayor in a ten-candidate field and in the November 5, 2013, election gained second place, being narrowly edged for first place by 7th Ward city council member Wendy McCammack.<ref name=\"YarbroughHagen\"/><ref name=\"Runoff\">Ryan Hagen, [http://www.sbsun.com/government-and-politics/20131105/wendy-mccammack-carey-davis-headed-for-runoff-in-san-bernardino-mayoral-race Wendy McCammack, Carey Davis headed for runoff in San Bernardino mayoral race] (November 5, 2013).</ref> Davis and McCammack then proceeded to a February 4, 2014, [[runoff election]], in which Davis defeated Wendy McCammack; turnout was low.<ref name=\"YarbroughHagen\"/> He was sworn in on March 3, 2014.<ref name=\"SwornIn\">{{cite news|last=Hagen|first=Ryan|url=http://www.redlandsdailyfacts.com/government-and-politics/20140303/new-san-bernardino-mayor-sworn-in|title=New San Bernardino mayor sworn in|newspaper=Redlands Daily Facts|date=March 3, 2014|access-date=November 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{California cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, R. Carey}}\n[[Category:American accountants]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California Polytechnic State University alumni]]\n[[Category:California State University, San Bernardino alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mayors of San Bernardino, California]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = R. Carey Davis\n| image = \n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| order = \n| office = [[List of mayors of San Bernardino, California|Mayor of San Bernardino]]\n| term_start = March 3, 2014\n| term_end = December 19, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Pat Morris (politician)|Pat Morris]]\n| successor = [[John Valdivia]]\n| birth_date = \n| birth_place = [[San Bernardino, California]], U.S.\n| citizenship = United States\n| nationality = [[Americans|American]]\n| children = 4\n| spouse = Johnetta Davis\n| residence = San Bernardino, California\n| profession = [[Certified Public Accountant|CPA]]\n| alma_mater = [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]] <small>([[bachelor's degree]])</small><ref name=\"OfficialBio\"/><br>[[California State University, San Bernardino]]<small>([[Masters of Business Administration|MBA]])</small>\n| party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Learish|first1=Jessica|title=Who Is R. Carey Davis, San Bernardino's Mayor? People Will Be Looking To Him For Leadership|url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/127277-who-is-r-carey-davis-san-bernardinos-mayor-people-will-be-looking-to-him-for-leadership|website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]]|accessdate=8 December 2015|date=2 December 2015|quote=Davis, a Republican and political newcomer, was elected mayor of San Bernardino in 2014 in the wake of the city declaring bankruptcy.}}</ref>\n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website = \n}}\n'''Richard Carey Davis''' formerly served as the mayor of San Bernardino,California. He served as the 28th mayor of the city. Davis was elected mayor [[2014 San Bernardino mayoral election|in 2014]]. He lost [[2018 San Bernardino mayoral election|the general election]] on November 6, 2018, after advancing from the primary on June 5, 2018.\n\n==Early life and education==\nDavis was born in [[San Bernardino, California|San Bernardino]] and graduated from [[Pacific High School (San Bernardino, California)|Pacific High School]] there.<ref name=\"Professionalism\"/> He received his bachelor's degree from [[California Polytechnic State University|Cal Poly San Luis Obispo]]<ref name=\"OfficialBio\">[http://www.sbcity.org/cityhall/mayor/about_the_mayor/default.asp About the Mayor: Mayor R. Carey Davis], City of San Bernardino (accessed December 3, 2015).</ref> and his [[master's in business administration]] from [[California State University, San Bernardino]].<ref name=\"OfficialBio\"/><ref name=\"Professionalism\"/>\n\n==Career==\nDavis is a [[certified public accountant]].<ref name=\"YarbroughHagen\">Beau Yarbrough & Ryan Hagen, [http://www.sbsun.com/government-and-politics/20140204/carey-davis-elected-san-bernardino-mayor Carey Davis elected San Bernardino mayor], ''The Sun'' (February 5, 2014).</ref>  who works as a controller in Los Angeles for Hehr International, a manufacturer of [[Recreational vehicle|RV]] doors and windows.<ref name=\"Professionalism\">Ryan Hagen, [http://www.sbsun.com/government-and-politics/20140202/carey-davis-vote-for-professionalism-in-san-bernardino-mayor Carey Davis: Vote for professionalism in San Bernardino mayor], ''The Sun'' (February 2, 2014).</ref>\n\nHe became involved in city politics in spring 2013.<ref name=\"YarbroughHagen\"/> He ran for mayor in a ten-candidate field and in the November 5, 2013, election gained second place, being narrowly edged for first place by 7th Ward city council member Wendy McCammack.<ref name=\"YarbroughHagen\"/><ref name=\"Runoff\">Ryan Hagen, [http://www.sbsun.com/government-and-politics/20131105/wendy-mccammack-carey-davis-headed-for-runoff-in-san-bernardino-mayoral-race Wendy McCammack, Carey Davis headed for runoff in San Bernardino mayoral race] (November 5, 2013).</ref> Davis and McCammack then proceeded to a February 4, 2014, [[runoff election]], in which Davis defeated Wendy McCammack; turnout was low.<ref name=\"YarbroughHagen\"/> He was sworn in on March 3, 2014.<ref name=\"SwornIn\">{{cite news|last=Hagen|first=Ryan|url=http://www.redlandsdailyfacts.com/government-and-politics/20140303/new-san-bernardino-mayor-sworn-in|title=New San Bernardino mayor sworn in|newspaper=Redlands Daily Facts|date=March 3, 2014|access-date=November 30, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{California cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, R. Carey}}\n[[Category:American accountants]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California Polytechnic State University alumni]]\n[[Category:California State University, San Bernardino alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mayors of San Bernardino, California]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R._Carey_Davis"}
{"title_page": "Halloway (EP)", "text_new": "{{Infobox EP|\n| name         = Halloway\n| type         = EP\n| artist       = [[Tessa Violet]]\n| cover        = Halloway_EP_cover.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = September 16, 2016\n| recorded     = \n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Pop music|Pop]]\n| length       = 16:51<ref name=\"Amazon.com staff 2020\" />\n| label        = \n| producer     = Seth Earnest<ref name=\"Cline 2019\" /><ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /><ref name=\"Discogs staff 2020\" /><ref name=\"Malach 2019\" />\n| prev_title   = [[Maybe Trapped Mostly Troubled]]\n| prev_year    = 2014\n| next_title   = Bad Ideas\n| next_year    = 2019\n}}\n\n'''''Halloway''''' is a 2016 [[Extended play|EP]] by American musician [[Tessa Violet]]. It was released on September 16, 2016 on [[Compact disc|CD]].<ref name=\"Discogs staff 2020\" />\n\n== Background ==\nThe title of ''Halloway'' was inspired by the character Will Halloway from the novel ''[[Something Wicked This Way Comes (novel)|Something Wicked This Way Comes]]'' by [[Ray Bradbury]]. Violet listened to [[audiobook]] version while on [[concert tour|tour]] after her mom said it was \"one of the scariest books she\u2019s read, and one of the most well-written.\"<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /> Violet described the album as \"dark pop\".<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" />\n\n''Halloway'' was released in 2016.<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /><ref name=\"Hull 2019\" /> Seth Earnest, who has worked with Tessa Violet since 2013, produced the album.<ref name=\"Cline 2019\" /><ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /><ref name=\"Malach 2019\" />\n\n== Production ==\nDuring ''Halloway''{{'}}s production, Violet listened to [[Taylor Swift]]'s ''[[1989 (Taylor Swift album)|1989]]'', [[Troye Sivan]]'s ''[[Blue Neighbourhood]]'', and [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]]'s ''[[Badlands (Halsey album)|Badlands]]''; as well as [[pop music|pop]] [[playlist]]s on [[Spotify]].<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" />\n\n== Alternate versions ==\nViolet released a [[royalty-free]] [[A-side and B-side|B-Side]]s version through her second reward tier of her [[Patreon]].<ref name=\"Aikins 2018\" />\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing     = \n| headline        = \n| title1          = Dream\n| length1         = 3:26\n| title2          = Not over You\n| length2         = 3:13\n| title3          = Haze\n| length3         = 3:46\n| title4          = On My Own\n| length4         = 2:56\n| title5          = I Don't Get to Say I Love You Anymore\n| length5         = 3:30\n}}\n\n== Reception ==\n''CelebMix.com''{{'}}s Annemarie Cutruzula favoured ''Halloway'' with \"a collection of five fresh pop songs, inspired by the likes of [[Halsey (singer)|Halsey]] and [[Taylor Swift]].\"<ref name=\"Cutruzzula 2016\" /> ''We The Unicorns''{{'}}s Liam Dryden praised the music video for \"Dream\": \"If we weren't hyped for Tessa's upcoming EP \"Halloway\" before now, this video is the ultimate sell.\"<ref name=\"Dryden 2016\" /> Reviewing ''Bad Ideas'' in 2019, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''{{'}}s Hannah Malach described ''Halloway'' as \"dark pop.\"<ref name=\"Malach 2019\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em\n|refs=\n<ref name=\"Aikins 2018\">{{cite web|first1=Gabriel|last1=Aikins|title=Tessa Violet is personally inviting you into her world|work=[[Substream Magazine]]|publisher=Substream Magazine|date=16 August 2018|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://substreammagazine.com/2018/08/tessa-violet-interview/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Amazon.com staff 2020\">{{cite web|author=Amazon.com staff|title=Halloway by Tessa Violet on Amazon Music - Amazon.com|work=[[Amazon (company)]]|publisher=amazon.com|date=|accessdate=19 April 2020|url=https://www.amazon.com/Halloway-Tessa-Violet/dp/B01LD13U74}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Cline 2019\">{{cite web|first1=Jesse|last1=Cline|title=PREMIERE: Tessa Violet Knows \u201cWords Ain\u2019t Enough\u201d on Her Second Album\u2019s Lead Single|work=[[Flood Magazine]]|publ