.wikipedia.org/wiki/%27Allo_%27Allo!_(series_9)"}
{"title_page": "National Labor Relations Board", "text_new": "{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name     = National Labor Relations Board\n|nativename      = NLRB\n|seal            = National Labor Relations Board logo - color.jpg\n|seal_width      = 140px\n|formed          = {{Start date and age|1935|7|5}}\n|jurisdiction    = [[Federal government of the United States]]\n|headquarters    = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|employees       = 1,628 (2008)\n|preceding1      = [[National Labor Board]]{{sfn|Morris|2005|p=25}}\n|preceding2      = \"First\" '''National Labor Relations Board'''{{sfn|Vittoz|1987|p=145}}\n|preceding3      = [[National War Labor Board (1942\u20131945)|National War Labor Board (World War II)]]\n|preceding4      = [[Council on Wage and Price Stability|Council on Wage and Price Stability (Carter-era)]]<ref name=wagecontrolenc>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Wage_and_Price_Controls.aspx|title=Wage and Price Controls facts, information, pictures - Encyclopedia.com articles about Wage and Price Controls|website=www.encyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n|parent_agency   = [[Executive Office of the President of the United States]]\n|budget          =\n|chief1_name     = [[John F. Ring]]\n|chief1_position = [[List of Chairmen of the National Labor Relations Board|Chairman]]\n|chief2_name     = [[Peter B. Robb]]\n|chief2_position = General Counsel\n|website         = {{url|http://www.nlrb.gov|nlrb.gov}}\n}}\nThe '''National Labor Relations Board''' ('''NLRB''') is an [[Independent agencies of the United States government|independent agency]] of the [[federal government of the United States]] with responsibilities for enforcing [[United States labor law|U.S. labor law]] in relation to [[collective bargaining]] and [[unfair labor practices]]. Under the [[National Labor Relations Act of 1935]] it supervises [[election]]s for [[trade union|labor union]] representation and can investigate and remedy [[unfair labor practice]]s. Unfair labor practices may involve union-related situations or instances of [[protected concerted activity]]. The NLRB is governed by a five-person board and a [[General Counsel]], all of whom are appointed by the [[President of the United States|President]] with the [[Advice and consent|consent]] of the [[United States Senate|Senate]]. Board members are appointed to five-year terms and the General Counsel is appointed to a four-year term. The General Counsel acts as a prosecutor and the Board acts as an [[appellate]] [[quasi-judicial body]] from decisions of [[administrative law judge]]s.\n\nThe NLRB is headquartered at 1015 Half St. SE, Washington, D.C., with over 30 regional, sub-regional and residential offices throughout the United States.\n\n==History==\n\n===1933\u20131935: First collective bargaining organization 'National Labor Board'===\nThe history of the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) can be traced to enactment of the [[National Industrial Recovery Act]] in 1933. Section 7(a) of the act protected collective bargaining rights for unions,{{sfn|Morris|2005|p=8}} but was difficult to enforce. A massive wave of union organizing was punctuated by employer and [[union violence]], [[general strike]]s, and [[recognition strike]]s.{{sfn|Dubofsky|Dulles|2004|pp=252\u201354}}{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=217\u201318}}{{sfn|Rayback|pp=328\u201329}} The National Industrial Recovery Act was administered by the [[National Recovery Administration]] (NRA). At the outset, NRA Administrator [[Hugh S. Johnson]] believed that Section 7(a) would be self-enforcing, but the tremendous labor unrest proved him wrong. On August 5, 1933, President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] announced the establishment of the [[National Labor Board]], under the auspices of the NRA, to implement the collective bargaining provisions of Section 7(a).{{sfn|Morris|2005|p=25}}\n\nThe National Labor Board (NLB) established a system of 20 regional boards to handle the immense caseload. Each regional board had a representative designated by local labor unions, local employers, and a \"public\" representative. All were unpaid. The public representative acted as the chair. The regional boards could hold hearings and propose settlements to disputes. Initially, they lacked authority to order representation elections, but this changed after Roosevelt issued additional executive orders on February 1 and February 23, 1934.\n\nThe NLB, too, proved ineffective. Congress passed Public Resolution No. 44 on June 19, 1934, which empowered the president to appoint a new labor board with authority to issue subpoenas, hold elections, and mediate labor disputes.{{sfn|Morris|2005|p=47}}{{sfn|Schlesinger|2003|p=151}} On June 29, President Roosevelt abolished the NLB and in [[Executive order (United States)|Executive Order]] 6763 established a new, three-member National Labor Relations Board.{{sfn|Vittoz|1987|p= 144}}{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=71\u201372}}\n\n[[Lloyd K. Garrison]] was the first Chairman of the National Labor Relations Board (often referred to by scholars the \"First NLRB\" or \"Old NLRB\").{{sfn|Vittoz|1987|p=145}} The \"First NLRB\" established organizational structures which continue at the NLRB in the 21st century. This includes the regional structure of the board; the use of [[administrative law judge]]s and regional hearing officers to initially rule on cases; an appeal process to the national board; and the use of expert staff, organized into various divisions, at the national level.{{sfn|Gross|1974|p=156}} Formally, Garrison established the:{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=79\u201380}}\n* Executive Office, which handled administrative activities of the national and regionalsit boards, field staff, and Legal Division. It was overseen by an Executive Secretary.\n* Examining Division, national staff which conducted field investigations and assisted the regional boards with adjudications, hearings, and representative elections.\n* Information Division, which provided the press and public with news.\n* Legal Division, which assisted the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] in seeking compliance with board decisions in the courts, or in responding to suits brought about by board decisions.<ref>The \"first NLRB\" was barred from initiating or responding to lawsuits itself. It could only ask the Department of Justice to act on its behalf.</ref>\n* Research Division, which studied decisions of the regional boards so that a comprehensive labor law might be developed, and studied the economics of each case.\n\nWithin a year, however, most of the jurisdiction of the \"First NLRB\" was stripped away. Its decisions in the automobile, newspaper, textile, and steel industries proved so volatile that Roosevelt himself often removed these cases from the board's jurisdiction. Several federal court decisions further limited the board's power. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Robert F. Wagner]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]] \u2013 [[New York (state)|NY]]) subsequently pushed legislation through Congress to give a statutory basis to federal labor policy that survived court scrutiny. On July 5, 1935, a new law\u2014the [[National Labor Relations Act]] (NLRA, also known as the Wagner Act)\u2014superseded the NIRA and established a new, long-lasting federal labor policy.{{sfn|Schlesinger|2003|pp=400\u201306}} The NLRA designated the National Labor Relations Board as the implementing agency.\n\n===1935\u20131939: Constitutionality, communism, and organizational changes===\n[[File:Madden witt fahy.jpg|thumb|[[J. Warren Madden]] (left), [[Nathan Witt]], and [[Charles Fahy]] (right) reviewing documents before a congressional hearing on December 13, 1937.]]\nThe first Chairman of the \"new\" NLRB was [[J. Warren Madden]], professor of the [[University of Pittsburgh School of Law]].<ref>\"President Names New Labor Board.\" ''New York Times.'' August 24, 1935.</ref> Madden largely confirmed the previous structure of the \"first NLRB\" by formally establishing five divisions within the agency:\n* '''Administrative Division:'''  Oversaw all administrative activities of national and regional boards and their finances; led by Secretary\n* '''Economic Division:'''  Analyzed economic evidence in cases; made studies of economics of labor relations for use by board and  courts; supervised by Chief Industrial Economist; also known as the Technical Service Division{{sfn|Gross|1974|p=219}}\n* '''Legal Division:'''  Handled NLRB either decisions appealed to courts or cases in which NLRB sought enforcement of its decisions; overseen by General Counsel (hired by NLRB board); comprised two subdivisions: \n** Litigation Section:  Advised national and regional boards, prepared briefs, worked with Justice Department\n** Review Section:  Analyzed regional hearings and decisions; issued interpretations of law; prepared forms; drafted regulations\n* '''Publications Division:'''  Handled all press and public inquiries; published decisions of national and regional boards and their rules and regulations; overseen by Director of Publications\n* '''Trial Examining Division:'''  Held hearings before the national board; overseen by Chief Trial Examiner\nBenedict Wolf served as first Secretary of the NLRB, [[Charles H. Fahy]] the first General Counsel, and [[David J. Saposs]] the first Chief Industrial Economist.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=79, 170, 174\u201375}} Wolf resigned in mid-1937, and [[Nathan Witt]], an attorney in the Legal Division, was named Secretary in October.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=111, 143}}\n\nThe Economic Division was a critical one for the NLRB. Cause-and-effect was one of the fundamental assumptions of the National Labor Relations Act, and for the causes of labor unrest to be understood economic analysis was needed.{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=344}} From the start, the Economic Division undertook three important tasks: 1) Gather economic data in support of cases before the courts; 2) Conduct general studies of labor relations to guide the board in formulating decisions and policies; and 3) Research the history of labor relations (the history of written agreements, whether certain issues were historically part of collective bargaining, how unions functioned internally, trends in employer activities, trends in collective bargaining, whether certain employer actions led to labor disputes, etc.) so that the board could educate itself, the courts, Congress, and the public about labor relations.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=176\u201379}} The first function proved critical to the survival of the NLRB. It was the Economic Division's data and analysis, more than then NLRB's legal reasoning, which proved critical in persuading the Supreme Court to sustain the Wagner Act in ''NLRB v. Jones & Laughlin Steel''.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=176\u201379, 191}}{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=347}} The Court even cited several Economic Division studies in its decision.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=228\u201329}} In the wake of ''Jones & Laughlin Steel'', many labor relations experts outside the agency concluded that economic analysis was \"an accepted fact\" essential to the proper functioning of the agency.{{sfn|Gross|1974|p=233}} The Economic Division did, too.  It asked Madden to pair an economist with an attorney in every important case,{{sfn|Eisner|2000|p=101}} and prepared outline of the economic data needed to support each case in case it went before the courts.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=182\u201383}}\n\nDuring his time on the NLRB, Madden was often opposed by the [[American Federation of Labor]] (AFL), which believed that Madden was using the NLRA and the procedures and staff of the NLRB to favor the AFL's primary competitor, the [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] (CIO).<ref>Stark, Louis. \"Both A.F.L. and C.I.O. Hit at National Labor Board.\" ''New York Times.'' October 14, 1937.</ref>{{sfn|Gall|1999|pp=83\u201384, 97\u201398}} The NLRB and NLRA were also under intense pressure from employers, the press, congressional [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]], and conservative [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]].{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=171\u201373}}{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=2}}\n\nThe NLRB's Economic Division proved critical in pushing for a congressional investigation into employer anti-union activities, and ensuring that investigation was a success. The Economic Division was deeply aware of employer use of [[Labor spy|labor spies]], violence, and [[company union]]s to thwart union organizing, and quietly pressed for a congressional investigation into these and other tactics. Senator [[Robert M. La Follette, Jr.]] took up the suggestion, on June 6, 1936, the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Senate Committee on Education and Labor]] established a Subcommittee Investigating Violations of Free Speech and the Rights of Labor chaired by La Follette.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=214\u201323}} Better known as the \"[[La Follette Committee]]\", the subcommittee held extensive hearings for five years and published numerous reports.  The committee uncovered extensive evidence of millions of company dollars used to pay for spies and [[fifth column]]ists within unions, exposed the culpability of local law enforcement in acts of violence and murder against union supporters (particularly in the [[Harlan County War]]),{{sfn|Baker|Stack|2006|pp=56\u201357}} revealed the wide extent of illegal [[blacklisting]] of union members, and exposed the use of armed [[strikebreaker]]s and widespread stockpiling of tear gas, vomit gas, machine guns, mortars, and armor by corporations to use against [[Strike action|strikers]].{{sfn|Luff|2007|p=774}} Some of the evidence the committee used was provided by the Economic Division,{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=90}} and the investigation proved critical for a time in defending the agency from business and congressional attack.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=214\u201323}}\n\nThe biggest issue the NLRB faced was constitutional. The [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] and NLRB legal staff wanted the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] to rule as quickly as possible on the constitutionality of the NLRA. But the Board and Justice Department also realized that the Court's [[Lochner era|''Lochner'' era]] legal philosophy made it unlikely for the Court to uphold the Act. Subsequently, Madden strove to resolve minor cases before they could become court challenges, and worked to delay appeals as long as possible until the best possible case could be brought to the Court.{{sfn|Chasse|2011|p=57}} This legal strategy paid off. The Supreme Court upheld the NLRA in ''[[National Labor Relations Board v. Jones & Laughlin Steel Corporation]]'', 301 U.S. 1 (1937).{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=643\u201346}} Afterward, Madden continued to strategically guide the NLRB's legal efforts to strengthen the federal courts' view of the NLRA and the board's actions.{{sfn|Chasse|2011|p=57}} Because of the efforts of Madden and NLRB General Counsel Charles H. Fahy, the Supreme Court reviewed only 27 cases between August 1935 and March 1941, even though the board had processed nearly 5,000 cases since its inception. The Supreme Court enforced the NLRB's rulings in 19 cases without modifying them, enforced them with modification in six more, and denied enforcement in two cases. Additionally, the Board won all 30 [[injunction]] and all 16 representation cases before the lower courts, a rate of success unequalled by any other federal agency.{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=662\u201363}}\n\nAFL opposition to the \"Madden Board\" grew after decisions in ''Shipowners' Ass'n of the Pacific Coast'', 7 NLRB 1002 (1938), ''enf'd'' ''[[American Federation of Labor v. National Labor Relations Board]]'', 308 U.S. 401 (1940) (awarding a longshoremen's unit to the CIO rather than the AFL), and ''American Can Co.'', 13 NLRB 1252 (1939) (unit's history of collective bargaining outweighs desire of workers to form craft-only unit).<ref>{{harvnb|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=654\u201355}} The AFL held to a philosophy of [[craft unionism]], while the CIO believed in [[industrial unionism]]. According to the AFL, ''American Can'' decisively tipped NLRB policy in favor of the CIO.</ref>\n\nThe AFL began pushing for an investigation into the NLRB, and this investigation led to allegations of communist influence within the agency. In June 1938, the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (led by Chairman [[Martin Dies, Jr.]] [D-[[Texas|TX]]]) heard testimony from AFL leader [[John P. Frey]], who accused Madden of staffing the NLRB with [[Communism|communists]].<ref>\"Reds Start Count of Allies in Federal Jobs and Push Participation in C.I.O., Frey Says.\" ''New York Times.'' January 10, 1938; \"Communists Rule the C.I.O., Frey of A.F.L. Testifies.\" ''New York Times.'' August 14, 1938; \"High Federal Aides Are Linked to Reds at House Hearing.\" ''New York Times.'' August 18, 1938; \"Green Pushes Fight on 2 NLRB Members.\" ''New York Times.'' August 24, 1938; \"Council of A.F.L. Backs Dies Inquiry.\" ''New York Times.'' September 2, 1938; Stark, Louis. \"A.F.L. Report Asks NLRB Power Be Cut.\" ''New York Times.'' October 10, 1938.</ref> The allegations were true, in at least one case: [[Nathan Witt]], the NLRB's executive secretary and the man to whom Madden had delegated most administrative functions, was a member of the [[Communist Party of the United States]].{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|p=667}}{{sfn|Storrs|2013|p=65}} These allegations and discoveries significantly damaged the agency's support in Congress and with the public.\n\nA second investigation into the [[NLRB]] led to organizational changes at the board. On July 20, 1939, Republicans and conservative Democrats formed a coalition to push through the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] a resolution establishing a Special Committee to Investigate the National Labor Relations Board (the \"[[J. Warren Madden#The Smith Committee|Smith Committee]]\"), chaired by conservative, anti-labor Rep. [[Howard W. Smith]] (D-[[Virginia|VA]]).{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=151\u201354}}{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|p=668}} On March 7, 1940, the Smith Committee proposed legislation to abolish the NLRB, reconstitute it, and radically amend the NLRA.{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=194\u201399}}<ref>Among the changes proposed:  Removing of many of the guarantees of collective bargaining from the Wagner Act's preamble, denying legal protection to [[sitdown strike]]rs and agricultural workers, removing the requirement that employers must bargain with unions, making the General Counsel independent from the Board, abolishing the board's economic research unit, enhancing employer free speech rights, introducing the right of employers to seek an election among their workers, and removing the board's authority to engage in bargaining unit determination. See: {{harvnb|Bernstein|Piven|1969|p=670}}</ref><ref>\"Ramspeck Attacks NLRB to Roosevelt.\" ''New York Times.'' December 30, 1939; \"Republicans Urge Abolition of NLRB.\" ''New York Times.'' March 3, 1940; Dorris, Henry N. \"Smith Committee Asks End of NLRB, Revised Labor Law.\" ''New York Times.'' March 8, 1940; Stark, Louis. \"House Quickens Labor Act Battle.\" ''New York Times.'' March 17, 1940; \"Jackson Is Urged to Prosecute NLRB.\" ''New York Times.'' March 19, 1940.</ref> President Roosevelt opposed the bill, although he conceded that perhaps the Board's membership should be expanded to five from three.<ref>\"President Opposes Smith NLRB Changes.\" ''New York Times.'' March 13, 1940.</ref> The Smith bill won several early tests in the House, which also voted to substantially cut the NLRB's budget.<ref>\"NLRB of Five Men Again Wins in Test.\" ''New York Times.'' March 21, 1940; Dorris, Henry N. \"House Votes Rises for NYA and CCC, NLRB Cut Is Upheld.\" ''New York Times.'' March 29, 1940; Stark, Louis. \"House Unit Gets NLRB Bill Dissent.\" ''New York Times.'' April 10, 1940.</ref> Smith won a vote in the [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]] permitting him to bring his bill to the floor for a vote.<ref>\"Smith Moves to Get NLRB Bills to Floor.\" ''New York Times.'' April 14, 1940; \"Rival Labor Bills Put Before House.\" ''New York Times.'' April 20, 1940.</ref> In an attempt to defuse the legislative crisis, Madden fired 53 staff and forced another five to resign, and decentralized the NLRB's trial process to give regional directors and field agents more authority.<ref>\"NLRB Dismisses 53, 5 Quit, in Fund Cut.\" ''New York Times.'' May 25, 1940; \"Field Men to Rule for Labor Board.\" ''New York Times.'' May 26, 1940.</ref> But the House still passed the Smith bill by a vote of 258 to 129 on June 7, 1940.<ref>Dorris, Henry N. \"Sweeping Changes in Labor Act Voted by House, 258\u2013129.\" ''New York Times.'' June 8, 1940.</ref> To protect the NLRB, Roosevelt convinced Senator [[Elbert D. Thomas]], Chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions#Education and Labor, 1884\u20131947|Senate Committee on Education and Labor]], to hold no hearings or votes on the bill, and the legislation died.{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=670\u201371}}{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=209\u201311}}\n\nThe Smith Committee investigation had a lasting effect on labor law in the U.S., and was the basis for the [[Taft-Hartley Act]] of 1947.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=225}}{{sfn|Atleson|1998|p=11}} Madden's term on the NLRB came to an end after just four years. On November 15, 1940, President Roosevelt nominated [[Harry A. Millis]] to the NLRB and named him Chairman, and nominated Madden to a seat on the U.S. Court of Claims.<ref>\"Dr. Millis Slated to Head the NLRB.\" ''New York Times.'' November 7, 1940; Hurd, Charles. \"Roosevelt Names Dr. Millis to NLRB, Replacing Madden.\" ''New York Times.'' November 16, 1940.</ref>\n\n===1940\u20131945: The Economics Division and World War II===\nAnother major structural change occurred at the same time that Madden left the NLRB. The Smith committee's anti-communist drive also targeted David J. Saposs, the NLRB Chief Industrial Economist. Saposs had been surreptitiously assessed by members of the Communist Party USA for membership, and rejected as a prospect.{{sfn|Gross|1974|p=220}} But Smith and others attacked Saposs as a communist, and Congress defunded his division and his job on October 11, 1940.{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=199, 202}}{{sfn|Jacobs|2007|pp=171\u201372}}{{sfn|Chasse|2011|p=58}} Although the Smith committee's investigation proved critical, the disestablishment of the Economic Division was due to many reasons\u2014both internal and external to the NLRB, and only some of which involved allegations of communist infiltration. As historian James A. Gross observed:.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}}\n<blockquote>The Division was eliminated for all kinds of reasons which had nothing to do with the merits and importance of its work:  political pressures and maneuverings, jealousy and empire building between and among lawyers and economists inside the Board, opposition to leftist ideologies, a personal attack on the Chief Economist, David Saposs, and a mighty hostility to the administrative process.</blockquote>\n\nThe loss of the Economic Division was a major blow to the NLRB.  It had a major tactical impact: Economic data helped the NLRB fulfill its adjudicatorial and prosecutorial work in areas such as [[unfair labor practice]]s (ULPs), representation elections, and in determining remedial actions (such as reinstatement, back pay awards, and fines).{{sfn|Stryker|1989|pp=346\u201347}} Economic data also undermined employer resistance to the agency by linking that opposition to employer ULPs.{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=349}} The loss also left the board dependent on the biased information offered by the parties in dispute before it, leading to poor decision-making and far less success in the courts.{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=266\u201367}} It also had a major strategic impact: It left the board unable to determine whether its administration of the law was effective or not.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=265}} Nor could the board determine whether labor unrest was a serious threat to the economy or not. As [[Labor history (discipline)|labor historian]] Josiah Bartlett Lambert put it: \"Without the Economic Research Division, the NLRB could not undertake empirical studies to determine the actual impact of [[Secondary action|secondary boycotts]], [[jurisdictional strike]]s, national emergency strikes, and the like.\"{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=104}} The Economic Division was critical to a long-range NLRB process to lead to the long-term evolution of industrial labor relations in the U.S., but that goal had to be abandoned.{{sfn|Eisner|2000|p=101}}{{sfn|Eisner|2010|pp=336\u201337}} Most importantly, however, the evisceration of the Economic Division struck at the fundamental purpose of federal labor law, which was to allow experts to adjudicate labor disputes rather than use a legal process. With this data and analysis, widespread skepticism about the board's expertise quickly spread through Congress and the courts.  It also left the board largely unable to engage in rule-making, forcing it to make labor law on an inefficient, time-consuming case-by-case basis.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=266}} As of 1981, NLRB was still the only federal agency forbidden to seek economic information about the impact of its activities.{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=264\u201365}}\n\nThe second Chairman of the NLRB, [[Harry A. Millis]], led the board in a much more moderate direction.{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=104}} Lacking an economic division to give it ammunition to fight with Millis deliberately made the NLRB dependent on Congress and the executive branch for its survival.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=261}} Millis made a large number of organizational changes. He stripped the office of Secretary of its power, set up an Administrative Division to supervise the 22 regional offices, initiated a study of the Board's administrative procedures, and genuinely delegated power to the regional offices.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=229}} He removed casehandling and regional office communication from the jurisdiction of the Office of the Secretary and created a Field Division.{{sfn|Tomlins|1985|p=225}}<ref>Stark, Louis. \"Methods of NLRB Indicated in Study Made By Own Men.\" New York Times. March 22, 1940.</ref> He also adopted procedures requiring the board made its decisions based solely on the trial examiner's report, authorized NLRB review attorneys to review trial examiner report, required decisions to be drafted ahead of time and distributed for review, authorized review attorneys to revise drafts before a final decision was issued, required trial examiners to emphasize findings of fact and to address points of law, and began holding board meetings when there were differences of opinion over decisions.{{sfn|Tomlins|1985|p=225}}\n\nMillis eliminated the Review Division's decisive role in cases, which had been established under Madden and Witt.{{sfn|Tomlins|1985|p=226}} Madden and Witt had adopted a highly centralized Board structure so that (generally speaking) only the cases most favorable to the board made it to the courts. The centralized structure meant that only the strongest cases made it to national board, so that the board could apply all its economic and legal powers to crafting the best decision possible. This strategy enabled the NLRB to defend itself very well before the Supreme Court. But Madden and Witt had held on to the centralized strategy too long, and made political enemies in the process. Millis substituted a decentralized process in which the board was less a decision-maker and more a provider of services to the regions.{{sfn|Tomlins|1985|p=226}} Many of the changes Millis instituted were designed to mimic requirements placed on other agencies by the [[Administrative Procedure Act (United States)|Administrative Procedure Act]].{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}}\n\nAmerican entry into World War II on December 8, 1941, significantly changed the NLRB. On January 12, 1942, President Roosevelt created the [[National War Labor Board (1942\u20131945)|National War Labor Board]] (NWLB), which displaced the NLRB as the main focus of federal labor relations for the duration of the war. The NWLB was given the authority to \"finally determine\" any labor dispute which threatened to interrupt war production, and to stabilize union wages and benefits during the war. Although Roosevelt instructed the NWLB not to intrude on jurisdiction exercised by the NLRB, the War Labor Board refused to honor this request. From 1942 to 1945, Millis tried to secure a jurisdictional agreement with NWLB Chairman George W. Taylor. But these discussions proved fruitless, and Millis broke them off in June 1945. The NWLB also heavily raided the NLRB for staff, significantly hindering NLRB operations.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=243}}\n\nAdditional changes came with the passage of the [[War Labor Disputes Act]] (WLDA) on June 25, 1943. Enacted over Roosevelt's veto after 400,000 coal miners, their wages significantly lower due to high wartime inflation, struck for a $2-a-day wage increase,{{sfn|Malsberger|2000|p=104}}{{sfn|Karatnycky|2000|p=115}} the legislation (in part) required the NLRB to issue a ballot outlining all the collective bargaining proposals and counter-proposals, wait 30 days, and then hold a strike vote.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=244}} The War Labor Disputes Act proved very burdensome.  The NLRB processed 2,000 WLDA cases from 1943 to the end of 1945, of which 500 were strike votes. The act's strike vote procedures did little to stop strikes, however, and Millis feared unions were using the referendums to whip up pro-strike feelings among their members. Millis also believed the law's strike vote process permitted more strikes to occur than the NLRB would have allowed under its old procedures. There were so many strike vote filings in the six months after the war ended that NLRB actually shut down its long distance telephone lines, cancelled all out of town travel, suspended all public hearings, and suspended all other business to accommodate the workload.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=245}} By early 1945, Millis was in ill health.<ref>\"Dr. H.A. Millis Dies.\" ''New York Times.'' June 26, 1948.</ref>  He resigned from the NLRB on June 7, 1945,<ref>\"In Administration Shake-Up\", ''Associated Press,'' June 8, 1945.</ref> and [[Paul M. Herzog]] was named his successor.\n\n===1947\u20131965: Taft-Hartley===\nA major turning point in the history of the NLRB came in 1947 with passage of the [[Taft-Hartley Act]]. Disruptions caused by strikes during World War II as well as the huge wave of strikes that followed the end of the war fueled a growing movement in 1946 and 1947 to amend the NLRA to correct what critics saw as a pro-labor tilt in federal law.<ref>Stark, Louis. \"Save Bargaining, Keep Peace In Industry, Says NLRB Head.\" ''New York Times.'' March 7, 1947.</ref>{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=251\u201352}} Drafted by the powerful Republican Senator [[Robert A. Taft]] and the strongly anti-union Representative [[Fred A. Hartley, Jr.]], the Taft-Hartley Act banned jurisdictional strikes, [[Wildcat strike action|wildcat strikes]], political strikes, [[Secondary action|secondary boycotts]], secondary picketing, mass picketing, union campaign donations made from dues money, the [[closed shop]], and unions of supervisors. The act also enumerated new employer rights, defined union-committed ULPs, gave states the right to opt out of federal labor law through [[right-to-work law]]s, required unions to give an 80-days' strike notice in all cases, established procedures for the President to end a strike in a national emergency, and required all union officials to sign an anti-Communist oath. Organizationally, the act made the General Counsel a presidential appointee, independent of the board itself, and gave the General Counsel limited powers to seek injunctions without referring to the Justice Department. It also banned the NLRB from engaging in any mediation or conciliation, and formally enshrined in law the ban on hiring personnel to do economic data collection or analysis.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}}\n\nIn August 1947, [[Robert N. Denham]] became the NRLB's [[general counsel]]. He held \"conservative views\" and wielded \"considerable influence\" on labor-management relations and interpretations of the newly passed [[Taft-Hartley Act]]. In 1950, US President [[Harry S. Truman]] fired Denham (''New York Times'':  \"left at the behest of the President\").<ref name=DenhamPapers>\n{{cite web\n| title = Denham, Robert N. (1885-1954), Papers, 1919-1954\n| publisher = State Historical Society of Missouri\n| url = https://collections.shsmo.org/manuscripts/columbia/c0012.pdf\n| date = \n| accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=NYT-Denham>\n{{cite news\n| title = Robert N. Denham Dies; N.L.R.B. Ex-General Counsel Victim of Heart Attack\n| publisher = State Historical Society of Missouri\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1954/06/19/archives/robert-n-denham-dies-n-l-r-b-exgeneral-counsel-victim-of-heart.html\n| pages = \n| date = 19 June 1954\n| accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref> While NLRB general counsel, Denham received considerable news coverage as a \"quasi-Republican.\"  Nominated by US President [[Harry S. Truman]],<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = The President's News Conference: July 17, 1947 \n| publisher = Harry S. Truman Library & Museum\n| url = https://www.trumanlibrary.gov/library/public-papers/145/presidents-news-conference-0\n| date = 17 July 1947\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref> Denham received unanimous approval by the US Senate Labor Committee. He received \"full and independent powers to investigate violations, file complaints and prosecute offenders before the board.\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Labor: Fair Target\n| publisher = TIME\n| url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,855805,00.html\n| date = 4 August 1947\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref> In August 1947, he supported an \"Anti-Red Affidavit Rule\" and so sided with US Senator [[Robert A. Taft]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Denham Is Reported Determined To Keep Anti-Red Affidavit Rule\n| first = Louis \n| last = Starkspecial\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1947/08/30/archives/denham-is-reported-determined-to-keep-antired-affidavit-rule.html\n| page = 28\n| date = 30 August 1947\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>  In October 1947, the NRLB overruled him, which meant that top officers of the [[American Federation of Labor]] (AFL) and [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] (CIO) would not have to sign an anti-Communist oath per the Taft-Hartley Act.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = National Affairs: Reversal\n| publisher = TIME\n| url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,804309,00.html\n| date = 20 October 1947\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHerzog publicly admitted the need for some change in the NLRA, but privately he opposed the proposed Taft-Hartley amendments. He felt the communist oath provisions were unconstitutional, that the amendments would turn the NLRA into a management weapon, that creation of an independent General Counsel would weaken the NLRB, and that the law's dismantling of the agency's economic analysis unit deprived the NLRB of essential expertise.{{sfn|Gross|2010|pp=11\u201313}} Nonetheless, Congress overrode Truman's veto of the Taft-Hartley Act on June 23, 1947, and the bill became law.{{sfn|Lee|1980|pp=101\u201303}}\n\nThe Taft-Hartley Act fundamentally changed the nature of federal labor law, but it also seriously hindered the NLRB's ability to enforce the law. The loss of the mediation function left the NLRB unable to become involved in labor disputes, a function it had engaged in since its inception as the National Labor Board in 1933. This hindered the agency's efforts to study, analyze, and create bulwarks against [[Good faith|bad-faith]] [[collective bargaining]]; reduced its ability to formulate national labor policy in this area; and left the agency making labor law on an ineffective, time-consuming case-by-case basis.{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=104}} The separation of the General Counsel from supervision by the national board also had significant impact on the agency. This separation was enacted against the advice of the Justice Department, contradicted the policy Congress had enacted in the Administrative Procedure Act of 1946, and ignored Millis' extensive internal reforms. The change left the NLRB as the only federal agency unable to coordinate its decision-making and legal activities, and the only agency exempted in this manner under the Administrative Procedure Act. The separation of the General Counsel was not discussed by the committee or by any witnesses during the legislation's mark-up. Indeed, there was no basis for it at all in the public record.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}} It was, in the words of sociologist Robin Stryker, \"little-noted\" and \"unprecedented\".{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=344}}\n\nThe anti-communist oath provisions generated extensive public debate, and generated disputes before the Supreme Court several times. The Taft-Hartley oath first reached the court in [[American Communications Ass'n v. Douds]], {{Ussc|339|382|1950|el=no}}, in which the court held 5-to-1 that the oath did not violate the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]], was not an ''[[ex post facto]]'' law or [[bill of attainder]] in violation of [[Article One of the United States Constitution#Section 10: Limits on the States|Article One, Section 10]], and was not a \"test oath\" in violation of [[Article Six of the United States Constitution#Oaths|Article Six]]. The issue again came before the court in [[Garner v. Board of Public Works]], {{Ussc|341|716|1951|el=no}}, in which the court unanimously held that a municipal [[loyalty oath]] was not an ''ex post facto law'' or bill of attainder. It came before the court yet a third time in ''Wieman v. Updegraff'', {{Ussc|344|183|1952|el=no}}. This time, the outcome was radically different. The Supreme Court unanimously ruled that state loyalty oath legislation violated the [[due process]] clause of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]]. In 1965, the Supreme Court held 5-to-4 that the anti-communist oath was a bill of attainder in ''[[United States v. Brown (1965)|United States v. Brown]]'', {{Ussc|381|437|1965|el=no}}.<ref>\"Beyond Process: A Substantive Rationale for the Bill of Attainder Clause.\" ''Virginia Law Review.'' April 1984, p. 485.</ref> The Supreme Court essentially overturned ''Douds'', but did not formally do so.{{sfn|Rabinowitz|1996|p=56}}\n\n===1966\u20132007===\n\nThe board itself (as an adjudicating body distinct from the functions separated as a result of Taft-Harley) has a fixed seating which is assigned based on the names of<ref>[https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/members-nlrb-1935 names of the original board members] The complete personnel list of the board since its inception at nlrb.gov</ref> 5 original members.\n\n===2007\u20132013: Lack of quorum===\nFrom December 2007 until June 2010, the five-person Board had only two members, creating a legal controversy. Three members' terms expired in December 2007, leaving the NLRB with just two members\u2014Chairman [[Wilma B. Liebman]] and Member Peter Schaumber.<ref name=\"Hananel\">Hananel, Sam. [http://www.boston.com/news/nation/washington/articles/2009/09/07/on_labor_day_us_labor_board_remains_in_gridlock \"On Labor Day, Labor Board Still in Gridlock\"], ''Boston Globe'', September 7, 2009.</ref> President [[George W. Bush]] refused to make some nominations to the Board and Senate [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] refused to confirm those which he did make.<ref name=\"Hananel\"/><ref name=\"Hananel2\">Hananel, Sam. \"Justice Asks High Court to OK Labor Board Rulings\", ''Associated Press'', September 29, 2009.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name=\"Greenhouse\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/15/us/politics/15nlrb.html Greenhouse, Steven. \"Labor Panel Is Stalled by Dispute on Nominee\"], ''[[The New York Times]].'' January 14, 2010.</ref>\n\nOn December 28, 2007, just before the Board lost its quorum, the four members agreed to delegate their authority to a three-person panel per the [[National Labor Relations Act]].<ref name=\"Greenhouse\"/><ref name=\"CCHLabor\">[http://hr.cch.com/news/employment/011008a.asp \"NLRB Temporarily Delegates Litigation Authority to General Counsel\"], ''CCH/Aspen Labor & Employment Law.'' January 10, 2008.</ref> Only Liebman and Schaumber remained on the Board, but the Board concluded that the two constituted a [[quorum]] of the three-person panel and thus could make decisions on behalf of the Board.<ref name=\"Greenhouse\"/><ref name=\"CCHLabor\"/> Liebman and Schaumber informally agreed to decide only those cases which were in their view noncontroversial and on which they could agree, and issued almost 400 decisions between January 2008 and September 2009.<ref name=\"Hananel\"/><ref name=\"Hananel2\"/><ref name=\"Greenhouse\"/><ref name=\"InsideCounsel\">\"Court Invalidates Two-Member NLRB Decision\", ''Inside Counsel'', July 2009.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name=\"Pickler\">Pickler, Nedra. \"NLRB Decisions Cause Conflicting Court Opinions.\" ''Associated Press'', May 1, 2009.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nThe U.S. Courts of Appeals for the [[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|First]], [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second]], and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|Seventh]] Circuits upheld the two-member NLRB's authority to decide cases, while the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|D.C. Circuit Court of Appeals]] did not.<ref name=\"Hananel\"/><ref name=\"Hananel2\"/>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name=\"InsideCounsel\" />{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name=\"Pickler\"/>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}} In September 2009, the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] asked the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] to immediately hear arguments concerning the dispute, given the high stakes involved.<ref name=\"Hananel2\"/> The Supreme Court granted [[certiorari]] in October and agreed to decide the issue.<ref>\"U.S. Supreme Court to Rule on National Labor Relations Board Issue\", ''Lawyers USA'', November 2, 2009; [https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8786398 \"Court to Decide If Two-Person Labor Board Legal\"], ''Associated Press.'' November 2, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, the Supreme Court ruled in ''[[New Process Steel, L. P. v. NLRB]]'' that the two-member Board had no authority to issue decisions, invalidating all rulings made by Liebman and Schaumber.<ref>130 S. Ct. 2635, 2638 (2010).</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}} In 2013, the question of a legitimate quorum on the NLRB surfaced again, when the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] ruled that President Obama had \"violated the Constitution when he bypassed the Senate to fill three board vacancies\".{{sfn|Trottman|Maher|2013}}{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Structure==\n{{refimprove section|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:1099 14th Street \u2013 National Labor Relations Board - sign.JPG|thumb|right|Plaque on the exterior of [[1099 14th Street]] NW in Washington, D.C., the NLRB headquarters as of 2013.]]\n[[File:NLRB picketing 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Union members picketing NLRB rulings outside the agency's [[Washington, D.C.]], headquarters in November 2007.]]\nIn 1947, the [[Taft\u2013Hartley Act]] created a formal administrative distinction between the Board and the General Counsel of the NLRB. In broad terms, the General Counsel is responsible for investigating and prosecuting [[unfair labor practice]] claims and for the general supervision of the NLRB field offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/general-counsel|title=The General Counsel - NLRB|website=www.nlrb.gov}}</ref> The General Counsel is appointed by the President to a four-year term and independent from the Board; it has limited independence to argue for a change in the law in presenting cases to the Board. The General Counsel oversees four divisions: the Division of Operations Management, the Division of Administration, the Division of Advice, and the Division of Enforcement Litigation.\n\nThe Board, on the other hand, is the adjudicative body that decides the unfair labor practice cases brought to it. Once the Board has decided the issue, it is the General Counsel's responsibility to uphold the Board's decision, even if it is contrary to the position it advocated when presenting the case to the Board. The Board is also responsible for the administration of the Act's provisions governing the holding of elections and resolution of jurisdictional disputes.\n\nThe Board has more than thirty regional offices. The regional offices conduct elections, investigate unfair labor practice charges, and make the initial determination on those charges (whether to dismiss, settle, or issue complaints). The Board has jurisdiction to hold elections and prosecute violations of the Act in [[Puerto Rico]] and [[American Samoa]].\n\n===Jurisdiction===\nThe Board's [[jurisdiction]] is limited to [[private sector]] employees and the [[United States Postal Service]]; other than Postal Service employees, it has no authority over labor relations disputes involving governmental, [[railroad]] and [[airline]] employees covered by the [[Adamson Railway Labor Act]], or agricultural employees. On the other hand, in those parts of the private sector its jurisdictional standards are low enough to reach almost all employers whose business has any appreciable impact on [[interstate commerce]].\n\n===Processing of charges===\nCharges are filed by parties against unions or employers with the appropriate regional office. The regional office will investigate the complaint. If a violation is believed to exist, the region will take the case before an [[Administrative Law Judge]] who will conduct a hearing. The decision of the Administrative Law Judge may be reviewed by the five member Board. Board decisions are reviewable by [[United States Courts of Appeals]]. The Board's decisions are not self-executing: it must seek court enforcement in order to force a recalcitrant party to comply with its orders. (For greater detail on this process see the entry for [[unfair labor practice]]).\n\n==General Counsel==\n[[Lafe Solomon]] was named Acting General Counsel on June 21, 2010. His nomination was sent to the U.S. Senate on January 5, 2011. Solomon's authority came into question on August 13, 2013 when Judge [[Benjamin Settle]] for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Washington]] denied a petition for [[Temporary restraining order#Injunctions in US labor law context|injunctive]] relief, ruling that Solomon had not been properly appointed under the [[Federal Vacancies Reform Act of 1998]] (FVRA).<ref>{{citation |last=Trottman |first=Melanie |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2013/08/22/ruling-on-top-lawyer-adds-to-nlrb-questions |title=Ruling on Top Lawyer Adds to NLRB Questions |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=August 22, 2013 |accessdate= August 22, 2013}}</ref> Although other [[United States district court|district courts]] had enforced Solomon's requests, Judge Settle's decision called into question all of Solomon's activity since June 21, 2010, focusing on subsections (a)(1) and (2) of the FVRA; some pundits claimed that Solomon's appointment was allowed under subsection (a)(3).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.laborrelationstoday.com/2013/08/articles/presidential-appointments/another-setback-for-the-nlrb-federal-district-court-invalidates-the-acting-general-counsels-appointment |title=Another Setback for the NLRB: Federal District Court Invalidates the Acting General Counsel's Appointment |work=Labor Relations Today |date=August 22, 2013 |accessdate= August 22, 2013}}</ref> President Obama withdrew Solomon's nomination.\n\nOn July 31, 2013, President Obama nominated former NLRB nominee Richard Griffin as General Counsel\u2014\"a kind of prosecutor at the board\" and \"one of the most critical roles at the agency.\"<ref name=\"huffingtonpost_2013\">{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/17/richard-griffin-nlrb_n_3611585.html | title=Richard Griffin, Former NLRB Nominee, To Be Offered General Counsel Slot After Filibuster Deal | publisher=Huffington Post | date=July 18, 2013 | accessdate=April 4, 2016 |first1=Dave |last1=Jamieson |first2=Ryan |last2=Grim}}</ref> Solomon's nomination was withdrawn.<ref name=vail>{{citation |url=http://inthesetimes.com/working/entry/15380/senate_approves_new_members_for_national_labor_board |last=Vail |first=Bruce |title=National Labor Board Shutdown Averted as Senate Approves New Members |work=In These Times |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}</ref> The Senate approved Griffin's nomination on October 29, 2013, by a vote of 55 to 44.<ref>{{cite news|last=Devaney|first=Tim|title=Rejected NLRB pick wins vote to serve as board counsel|work=The Washington Times|date=October 29, 2013|accessdate=April 26, 2016|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/oct/29/obama-nlrb-counsel-pick-wins-key-vote/?page=all}}</ref>\n\n==Board members==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Seat<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/members-nlrb-1935|title=Members of the NLRB since 1935|author=nlrb.gov}}</ref>\n! Member\n! Entered office\n! Term expires\n|-\n| Carmody<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 8 and 3)</div>\n| ''Vacant'' \n| \n| August 27, 2023<!--Mark Gaston Pearce (D)\n| April 7, 2010<ref>https://www.law360.com/articles/1077826/trump-taps-nlrb-s-pearce-for-3rd-term</ref>-->\n|-\n| Gray<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 9 and 4)</div>\n| ''Vacant'' \n| \n| December 16, 2024\n|-\n| Smith<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 6 and 1)</div>\n| [[William Emanuel]] (R)\n|September 28, 2017\n| August 27, 2021\n|-\n| [[Orrice Abram Murdock Jr.|Murdock]]<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 7 and 2)</div>\n| [[John F. Ring]] (R)\n| April 16, 2018\n| December 16, 2022\n|-\n| [[J. Warren Madden|Madden]]<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 5 and 0)</div>\n| [[Marvin Kaplan (lawyer)|Marvin Kaplan]] (R) \n| August 10, 2017<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nlrb.gov/news-outreach/news-story/marvin-e-kaplan-sworn-nlrb-member |title=Marvin E. Kaplan Sworn in as NLRB Member|date=10 August 2017|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n| August 27, 2020\n|}\n\n===2007\u20132013: Unoccupied board seats===\nIn April 2009, President Obama nominated Craig Becker (Associate General Counsel of the [[Service Employees International Union]]), Mark Gaston Pearce (a member on the Industrial Board of Appeals, an agency of the New York State Department of Labor), and Brian Hayes (Republican Labor Policy Director for the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions]]) to fill the three empty seats on the NLRB.<ref name=\"Hananel\"/>\n\nBecker's nomination appeared to fail on February 8, 2010, after Republican Senators (led by [[John McCain]]) threatened to filibuster his nomination.<ref name=\"Greenhouse\" /><ref name=\"Failed\">[http://voices.washingtonpost.com/federal-eye/2010/02/nlrb_nominee_craig_becker_fail.html O'Keefe, Ed. \"Craig Becker, nominated for NLRB, rejected by Senate\"], ''Washington Post''. February 9, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/12/us/politics/12confirm.html \"Senate Confirms 2 Dozen Obama Nominees\"], ''New York Times.'' February 11, 2010.</ref> President Obama said he would consider making [[recess appointment]]s to the NLRB due to the Senate's failure to move on any of the three nominations.<ref name=\"Failed\"/> On March 27, 2010, Obama recess appointed Becker and Pearce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-positions|date=March 27, 2010|title=President Obama Announces Recess Appointments to Key Administration Positions|author=The White House, Office of the Press Secretary|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022015004/http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-positions|archivedate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2010, a [[voice vote]] in the Senate confirmed Pearce to a full term, allowing him to serve until August 27, 2013. The same day, the Senate confirmed Republican nominee Brian Hayes of Massachusetts by voice vote. Hayes' term ended on December 16, 2012.<ref>Trottman, Melanie. [https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2012/12/17/labor-relations-board-loses-voice-of-dissent \"Labor Board Loses Voice of Dissent\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', December 17, 2012; accessed 2013-01-27.</ref> Becker's term, as a recess appointee, ended on December 31, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newmediajournal.us/indx.php/item/1450|title=Media Journal coverage of the NLRB appointments|publisher=}}</ref> Effective August 28, 2011, Pearce was named Chairman to replace Democrat Wilma Liebman, whose term had expired.<ref>Geman, B.[http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/178489-labor-board-chief-departs-as-uncertainty-for-panel-looms \"NLRB chairwoman departs; political fights loom for labor panel\"], ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' Briefing Room, August 27, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2012, Obama announced [[recess appointment]]s to three seats on the board: Sharon Block, Terence F. Flynn, and Richard Griffin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2012/01/04/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-posts|title=President Obama Announces Recess Appointments to Key Administration Posts|author=The White House, Office of the Press Secretary|date=January 4, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2012}}</ref> The appointments were criticized by Republicans, including the House Speaker [[John Boehner]], as unconstitutional and \"a brazen attempt to undercut the role of the Senate to advise and consent the executive branch on appointments\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Bucking Senate, Obama Appoints Consumer Chief|author=Helene Cooper|author2=Jennifer Steinhauer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/05/us/politics/richard-cordray-named-consumer-chief-in-recess-appointment.html?pagewanted=all|work=The New York Times|date=January 4, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> Although made as recess appointments, critics questioned their legality, arguing that Congress had not officially been in recess as pro forma sessions had been held.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/04/obama-tempts-fight-over-recess-appointments|title=Obama tempts fight over recess appointments|author=Charlie Savage|date=January 4, 2012|work=The Caucus|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> Former U.S. attorney general [[Edwin Meese]] stated that in his opinion, since the appointments were made when the Senate was \"demonstrably not in recess\" they represented \"a constitutional abuse of a high order\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama's recess appointments are unconstitutional|author=Edwin Meese|author2=Todd Gaziano|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/obamas-recess-appointments-are-unconstitutional/2012/01/05/gIQAnWRfdP_story.html|work=The Washington Post|date=January 5, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> On January 12, 2012 the U.S. Justice Department released a memo stating that appointments made during pro forma sessions are supported by the Constitution and precedent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama Has Recess Appointment Power, Justice Department Says|author=Seth Stern|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/01/12/bloomberg_articlesLXP7PE6K50XW.DTL|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=January 12, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 25, 2013, in ''Noel Canning v. NLRB'', a panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit ruled that President Obama's recess appointments were invalid as they were not made during an intersession recess of the Senate, and the President moved to fill them during the same recess.<ref>Greenhouse, Steven. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/26/us/labor-relations-board-rulings-could-be-undone.html \"More Than 300 Labor Board Decisions Could Be Nullified\"], ''New York Times'', January 25, 2013; accessed 2013-01-26.</ref> On May 16, 2013, in ''National Labor Relations Board v. New Vista Nursing and Rehabilitation'', the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit became the second federal appellate court to rule that the recess appointments to the NLRB were unconstitutional. In a split decision, it also found that the March 27, 2010 recess appointment of Craig Becker was unconstitutional.<ref>Allenson, Sheryl C. and Milam-Perez, Lisa. [http://www.employmentlawdaily.com/index.php/2013/05/16/former-board-member-craig-becker-invalidly-recess-appointed/#sthash.ScW6uRak.dpuf \"Former Board member Craig Becker invalidly recess-appointed; clause refers to 'intrasession break'\"], ''Employment Law Daily'', May 16, 2013; accessed February 1, 2014.</ref> On January 14, 2014, the U.S. Supreme Court heard the case in ''[[National Labor Relations Board v. Noel Canning]]''.<ref>Liptak, Adam. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/25/us/justices-agree-to-hear-case-on-presidents-recess-appointments.html \"Justices to Hear Case on Obama's Recess Appointments\"], ''New York Times'', June 24, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref><ref>Williams, Victor. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/victor-williams/the-supreme-court-should-_2_b_4586974.html \"The Supreme Court Should Stay Out of the Noel Canning Recess Fight\"], ''Huffington Post'', January 14, 2014; accessed February 1, 2014.</ref>\n\nBetween January 2008 and mid-July 2013 the agency never had all five members, and not once did it operate with three confirmed members.<ref>Landler, Mark and Greenhouse, Steven. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/16/us/politics/vacancies-and-partisan-fighting-put-labor-relations-agency-in-legal-limbo.html \"Vacancies and Partisan Fighting Put Labor Relations Agency in Legal Limbo\"], ''New York Times'', July 15, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref> On July 14, 2013, Senate Majority Leader [[Harry Reid]] threatened to exercise the \"[[nuclear option]]\" and allow a simple majority (rather than a [[supermajority]]) of the Senate to end a [[filibuster]]. This threat to end the filibuster's privileged position in the Senate was intended to end Republican filibustering of NLRB nominees.<ref>Weisman, Jonathan and Parker, Ashley. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/16/us/politics/democrats-seeing-precedent-press-on-to-curb-filibuster.html \"Senate's Leader Sets Showdown Over Changes to Filibuster\"], ''New York Times'', July 15, 2013; accessed 2013-07-16.</ref> On July 16, 2013, President Obama and Senate Republicans reached an agreement to end the impasse over NLRB appointees. Obama withdrew the pending nominations of Block and Griffin, and submit two new nominees: Nancy Schiffer, associate general counsel at the AFL-CIO, and Kent Hirozawa, chief counsel to NLRB Chairman Mark Gaston Pearce. Republicans agreed not to oppose a fourth nominee, to be submitted in 2014.<ref>[http://www.politico.com/story/2013/07/white-house-consults-with-afl-cio-head-on-nlrb-picks-94280.html Everett, Burgess and Bresnahan, John. \"Obama Selects NLRB Replacement Picks\"], ''Politico'', July 16, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn July 30, 2013, the Senate confirmed all five of Obama's nominees for the NLRB: Kent Hirozawa, Harry I. Johnson III, [[Philip A. Miscimarra]], Mark Gaston Pearce and Nancy Schiffer. Johnson and Miscimarra represented the Republican nominees for the board.<ref>Cox, Ramsey.[http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/314503-senate-votes-to-confirm-all-five-nlrb-members#ixzz2aemFMR3p \"Senate Confirms All Five NLRB Members\"], ''The Hill'', July 30, 2013; accessed 2013-07-31.</ref> Pearce was confirmed for a second five-year term.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20130731/NEWS04/130739947/chicago-attorney-tapped-for-national-labor-relations-board \"Chicago Attorney Tapped for National Labor Relations Board\"], ''Chicago Business Journal'', July 31, 2013; accessed July 31, 2013.</ref>  Nancy Schiffer's term ended on December 15, 2014. She was succeeded by Lauren McFerran on December 16, 2014. Harry I. Johnson III's term ended on August 27, 2015.<ref>[https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/board-members-1935 NLRB official website], nlrb.gov; accessed February 4, 2016.</ref>\n\n===2017 appointments===\nOn January 25, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] appointed Philip Miscimarra the acting Chairman of the NLRB.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wiessner|first=Daniel|title=Trump taps Republican EEOC, NLRB members as acting chairs|work=Reuters|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=January 26, 2017|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/trump-appointments-idUSL1N1FF20G}}</ref> Miscimarra's term expired on December 16, 2017. [[Marvin Kaplan (lawyer)|Marvin Kaplan]] succeeded him as NLRB Chairman on December 21, 2017.<ref name=nlrb_chair_confirm_vote>{{cite web|author=United States Senate|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00184|title=Confirmation Marvin Kaplan, of Kansas, to be a Member of the National Labor Relations Board|date=September 25, 2017|accessdate=December 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=trump_named_kaplan_chairman>{{cite web|author=National Labor Relations Board|url=https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/marvin-e-kaplan|title=Marvin E. Kaplan|date=|accessdate=December 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Organized labour}}\n* [[US labor law]]\n* [[Federal Labor Relations Authority]]\n* [[Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service (United States)]]\n* [[List of Chairmen of the National Labor Relations Board]]\n* [[NLRB election procedures]]\n* [[Subpoena ad testificandum]]\n* [[Subpoena duces tecum]]\n* [[Title 29 of the Code of Federal Regulations]]\n* [[Union organizer]]\n* [[USA.gov]]\n* [[USAFacts]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|first=James B.|last=Atleson|title=Labor and the Wartime State: Labor Relations and Law During World War II|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=fZ7wf-45KPcC}}|date=January 1, 1998|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-06674-0|ref=harv |oclc=605496878}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Thomas E.|last1=Baker|authorlink1=Thomas E. Baker|first2=John F.|last2=Stack|title=At War with Civil Rights and Civil Liberties|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=svxzgTPwG1wC}}|year=2006|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-0-7425-3599-2|ref=harv |oclc=646057221}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Irving|last1=Bernstein|authorlink=Irving Bernstein|first2=Frances Fox|last2=Piven|authorlink2=Frances Fox Piven|title=The Turbulent Years: A History of the American Worker, 1933-1941|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=aaHaroUImGIC}}|year=1969|publisher=Haymarket Books|isbn=978-1-60846-064-9|ref=harv |oclc=776982985}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Malcolm|editor-last1=Rutherford|title=The Institutionalist Movement in American Economics, 1918\u20131947: Science and Social Control|chapter-url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=XfX72hARkpsC|page=361}}|date=February 21, 2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-49756-5|last=Chasse|first=J. Dennis|chapter=John R. Commons and His Students: The View From the End of the Twentieth Century|ref=harv |oclc=474282342}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Melvyn|last1=Dubofsky|authorlink=Melvyn Dubofsky|first2=Foster Rhea|last2=Dulles|title=Labor in America: A History|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=gIZDPwAACAAJ}}|date=January 2004|publisher=Harlan Davidson|isbn=978-0-88295-998-6|ref=harv |oclc=300754496}}\n* {{cite book|first=Marc Allen|last=Eisner|title=From Warfare State to Welfare State: World War I, Compensatory State-Building, and the Limits of the Modern Order|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=lHibH8WJfuMC}}|date=November 1, 2010|publisher=Penn State Press|isbn=978-0-271-04350-0|ref=harv |oclc=49414683}}\n* {{cite book|first=Marc Allen|last=Eisner|title=Regulatory Politics in Transition|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=HAmT6fuhwQcC}}|year=2000|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-6492-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Gilbert J.|last=Gall|title=Pursuing Justice: Lee Pressman, the New Deal, and the CIO|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=xCYoLnaWXdoC}}|year=1999|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-4103-9|ref=harv |oclc=43476605}}\n* {{cite book|first=James A.|last=Gross|authorlink=James A. Gross|title=Broken Promise: The Subversion Of U.S. Labor Relations|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=yV0pX9PU1LEC}}|date=June 10, 2010|publisher=Temple University Press|isbn=978-1-4399-0370-4|ref=harv |oclc=693761467}}\n* {{cite book|first=James A.|last=Gross|authorlink=James A. Gross|title=The Making of the National Labor Relations Board: A Study in Economics, Politics, and the Law: Volume 1 (1933-1937)|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=v8-GnqDCGyAC}}|year=1974|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-87395-271-2|ref=harv |oclc=505722441}}\n* {{cite book|first=James A.|last=Gross|authorlink=James A. Gross|title=Reshaping of the National Labor Relations Board: A Study in Economics, Politics, and the Law|location=Albany, NY|publisher=[[SUNY Press]]|year=1981|ref=harv |oclc=555229476}}\n* {{cite book|first=Meg|last=Jacobs|title=Pocketbook Politics: Economic Citizenship in Twentieth-Century America|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=xWNPAQAAQBAJ}}|date=February 20, 2007|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-4378-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Adrian|last=Karatnycky|title=Freedom in the World: The Annual Survey of Political Rights and Civil Liberties, 2000-2001|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=Mz57SSzuYecC}}|year=2000|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-5008-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Josiah Bartlett|last=Lambert|title=\"If the Workers Took a Notion\": The Right to Strike and American Political Development|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=IjecnphnVZQC}}|year=2005|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-8945-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=R. Alton|last=Lee|title=Truman and Taft Hartley: A Question of Mandate|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=Xa4rAAAAYAAJ}}|year=1980|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group, Incorporated|isbn=978-0-313-22618-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Eric|editor-last=Arnesen|title=Encyclopedia of U.S. Labor and Working-class History|chapter-url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=zEWsZ81Bd3YC}}|year=2007|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-96826-3|last=Luff|first=Jennifer|authorlink1=Jennifer D. Luff|chapter=LaFollette Civil Liberties Committee |volume=1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=John William|last=Malsberger|title=From Obstruction to Moderation: The Transformation of Senate Conservatism, 1938-1952|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=xzF9F2I5nFkC}}|year=2000|publisher=Susquehanna University Press|isbn=978-1-57591-026-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Charles J.|last=Morris|authorlink=Charles Morris (legal educator)|title=The Blue Eagle at Work: Reclaiming Democratic Rights in the American Workplace|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=q2eWTzf2mH8C}}|year=2005|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-4317-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Victor|last=Rabinowitz|authorlink=Victor Rabinowitz|title=Unrepentant Leftist: A Lawyer's Memoir|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=iMaVigHoraAC}}|year=1996|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-02253-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Arthur Meier|last=Schlesinger|authorlink=Schlesinger Jr., Arthur M.|title=The Coming of the New Deal, 1933-1935|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=mj3VmJ38tHIC}}|year=2003|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=0-618-34086-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Landon R.Y.|last=Storrs|title=The Second Red Scare and the Unmaking of the New Deal Left|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=umlPTJksNdUC}}|year=2013|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-15396-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Limits on Technocratization of the Law: The Elimination of the National Labor Relations Board's Division of Economic Research|jstor=2095610|journal=American Sociological Review|date=1989-06-01|pages=341\u2013358|volume=54|issue=3|doi=10.2307/2095610|first=Robin|last=Stryker|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tomlins|first=Christopher|title=The State and the Unions: Labor Relations, Law, and the Organized Labor Movement in America, 1880-1960|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=VnZCuAAACAAJ}}|year=1985|publisher=Cambridge University|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news|title=Companies Challenge Labor Rulings|first=Melanie|last=Trottman|first2=Kris|last2=Maher|type=paper|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=March 9\u201310, 2013|pages=A1\u2013A2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Stanley|last=Vittoz|title=New Deal labor policy and the American industrial economy|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=TnGSK8IP8HUC}}|year=1987|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=978-0-8078-1729-2|ref=harv}}\n* Fischer, Fredric H.; Brent, Garren; and Truesdale, John C., eds. ''How to Take A Case Before the NLRB.'' 8th ed. Washington, D.C.: Bureau of National Affairs, 2008.\n* Gould IV, William B. ''Labored Relations: Law, Politics, and the NLRB.'' Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press, 2001.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091007175537/http://www.nlrb.gov/ National Labor Relations Board official website]\n* [https://www.federalregister.gov/agencies/national-labor-relations-board National Labor Relations Board] in the [[Federal Register]]\n\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1935]]\n[[Category:History of labor relations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Labor relations boards]]\n[[Category:National Labor Relations Board| ]]\n[[Category:New Deal agencies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name     = National Labor Relations Board\n|nativename      = NLRB\n|seal            = National Labor Relations Board logo - color.jpg\n|seal_width      = 140px\n|formed          = {{Start date and age|1935|7|5}}\n|jurisdiction    = [[Federal government of the United States]]\n|headquarters    = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|employees       = 1,628 (2008)\n|preceding1      = [[National Labor Board]]{{sfn|Morris|2005|p=25}}\n|preceding2      = \"First\" '''National Labor Relations Board'''{{sfn|Vittoz|1987|p=145}}\n|preceding3      = [[National War Labor Board (1942\u20131945)|National War Labor Board (World War II)]]\n|preceding4      = [[Council on Wage and Price Stability|Council on Wage and Price Stability (Carter-era)]]<ref name=wagecontrolenc>{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/topic/Wage_and_Price_Controls.aspx|title=Wage and Price Controls facts, information, pictures - Encyclopedia.com articles about Wage and Price Controls|website=www.encyclopedia.com}}</ref>\n|parent_agency   = [[Executive Office of the President of the United States]]\n|budget          =\n|chief1_name     = [[John F. Ring]]\n|chief1_position = [[List of Chairmen of the National Labor Relations Board|Chairman]]\n|chief2_name     = [[Peter B. Robb]]\n|chief2_position = General Counsel\n|website         = {{url|http://www.nlrb.gov|nlrb.gov}}\n}}\nThe '''National Labor Relations Board''' ('''NLRB''') is an [[Independent agencies of the United States government|independent agency]] of the [[federal government of the United States]] with responsibilities for enforcing [[United States labor law|U.S. labor law]] in relation to [[collective bargaining]] and [[unfair labor practices]]. Under the [[National Labor Relations Act of 1935]] it supervises [[election]]s for [[trade union|labor union]] representation and can investigate and remedy [[unfair labor practice]]s. Unfair labor practices may involve union-related situations or instances of [[protected concerted activity]]. The NLRB is governed by a five-person board and a [[General Counsel]], all of whom are appointed by the [[President of the United States|President]] with the [[Advice and consent|consent]] of the [[United States Senate|Senate]]. Board members are appointed to five-year terms and the General Counsel is appointed to a four-year term. The General Counsel acts as a prosecutor and the Board acts as an [[appellate]] [[quasi-judicial body]] from decisions of [[administrative law judge]]s.\n\nThe NLRB is headquartered at 1015 Half St. SE, Washington, D.C., with over 30 regional, sub-regional and residential offices throughout the United States.\n\n==History==\n\n===1933\u20131935: First collective bargaining organization 'National Labor Board'===\nThe history of the National Labor Relations Board (NLRB) can be traced to enactment of the [[National Industrial Recovery Act]] in 1933. Section 7(a) of the act protected collective bargaining rights for unions,{{sfn|Morris|2005|p=8}} but was difficult to enforce. A massive wave of union organizing was punctuated by employer and [[union violence]], [[general strike]]s, and [[recognition strike]]s.{{sfn|Dubofsky|Dulles|2004|pp=252\u201354}}{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=217\u201318}}{{sfn|Rayback|pp=328\u201329}} The National Industrial Recovery Act was administered by the [[National Recovery Administration]] (NRA). At the outset, NRA Administrator [[Hugh S. Johnson]] believed that Section 7(a) would be self-enforcing, but the tremendous labor unrest proved him wrong. On August 5, 1933, President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] announced the establishment of the [[National Labor Board]], under the auspices of the NRA, to implement the collective bargaining provisions of Section 7(a).{{sfn|Morris|2005|p=25}}\n\nThe National Labor Board (NLB) established a system of 20 regional boards to handle the immense caseload. Each regional board had a representative designated by local labor unions, local employers, and a \"public\" representative. All were unpaid. The public representative acted as the chair. The regional boards could hold hearings and propose settlements to disputes. Initially, they lacked authority to order representation elections, but this changed after Roosevelt issued additional executive orders on February 1 and February 23, 1934.\n\nThe NLB, too, proved ineffective. Congress passed Public Resolution No. 44 on June 19, 1934, which empowered the president to appoint a new labor board with authority to issue subpoenas, hold elections, and mediate labor disputes.{{sfn|Morris|2005|p=47}}{{sfn|Schlesinger|2003|p=151}} On June 29, President Roosevelt abolished the NLB and in [[Executive order (United States)|Executive Order]] 6763 established a new, three-member National Labor Relations Board.{{sfn|Vittoz|1987|p= 144}}{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=71\u201372}}\n\n[[Lloyd K. Garrison]] was the first Chairman of the National Labor Relations Board (often referred to by scholars the \"First NLRB\" or \"Old NLRB\").{{sfn|Vittoz|1987|p=145}} The \"First NLRB\" established organizational structures which continue at the NLRB in the 21st century. This includes the regional structure of the board; the use of [[administrative law judge]]s and regional hearing officers to initially rule on cases; an appeal process to the national board; and the use of expert staff, organized into various divisions, at the national level.{{sfn|Gross|1974|p=156}} Formally, Garrison established the:{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=79\u201380}}\n* Executive Office, which handled administrative activities of the national and regionalsit boards, field staff, and Legal Division. It was overseen by an Executive Secretary.\n* Examining Division, national staff which conducted field investigations and assisted the regional boards with adjudications, hearings, and representative elections.\n* Information Division, which provided the press and public with news.\n* Legal Division, which assisted the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] in seeking compliance with board decisions in the courts, or in responding to suits brought about by board decisions.<ref>The \"first NLRB\" was barred from initiating or responding to lawsuits itself. It could only ask the Department of Justice to act on its behalf.</ref>\n* Research Division, which studied decisions of the regional boards so that a comprehensive labor law might be developed, and studied the economics of each case.\n\nWithin a year, however, most of the jurisdiction of the \"First NLRB\" was stripped away. Its decisions in the automobile, newspaper, textile, and steel industries proved so volatile that Roosevelt himself often removed these cases from the board's jurisdiction. Several federal court decisions further limited the board's power. [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Robert F. Wagner]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]] \u2013 [[New York (state)|NY]]) subsequently pushed legislation through Congress to give a statutory basis to federal labor policy that survived court scrutiny. On July 5, 1935, a new law\u2014the [[National Labor Relations Act]] (NLRA, also known as the Wagner Act)\u2014superseded the NIRA and established a new, long-lasting federal labor policy.{{sfn|Schlesinger|2003|pp=400\u201306}} The NLRA designated the National Labor Relations Board as the implementing agency.\n\n===1935\u20131939: Constitutionality, communism, and organizational changes===\n[[File:Madden witt fahy.jpg|thumb|[[J. Warren Madden]] (left), [[Nathan Witt]], and [[Charles Fahy]] (right) reviewing documents before a congressional hearing on December 13, 1937.]]\nThe first Chairman of the \"new\" NLRB was [[J. Warren Madden]], professor of the [[University of Pittsburgh School of Law]].<ref>\"President Names New Labor Board.\" ''New York Times.'' August 24, 1935.</ref> Madden largely confirmed the previous structure of the \"first NLRB\" by formally establishing five divisions within the agency:\n* '''Administrative Division:'''  Oversaw all administrative activities of national and regional boards and their finances; led by Secretary\n* '''Economic Division:'''  Analyzed economic evidence in cases; made studies of economics of labor relations for use by board and  courts; supervised by Chief Industrial Economist; also known as the Technical Service Division{{sfn|Gross|1974|p=219}}\n* '''Legal Division:'''  Handled NLRB either decisions appealed to courts or cases in which NLRB sought enforcement of its decisions; overseen by General Counsel (hired by NLRB board); comprised two subdivisions: \n** Litigation Section:  Advised national and regional boards, prepared briefs, worked with Justice Department\n** Review Section:  Analyzed regional hearings and decisions; issued interpretations of law; prepared forms; drafted regulations\n* '''Publications Division:'''  Handled all press and public inquiries; published decisions of national and regional boards and their rules and regulations; overseen by Director of Publications\n* '''Trial Examining Division:'''  Held hearings before the national board; overseen by Chief Trial Examiner\nBenedict Wolf served as first Secretary of the NLRB, [[Charles H. Fahy]] the first General Counsel, and [[David J. Saposs]] the first Chief Industrial Economist.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=79, 170, 174\u201375}} Wolf resigned in mid-1937, and [[Nathan Witt]], an attorney in the Legal Division, was named Secretary in October.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=111, 143}}\n\nThe Economic Division was a critical one for the NLRB. Cause-and-effect was one of the fundamental assumptions of the National Labor Relations Act, and for the causes of labor unrest to be understood economic analysis was needed.{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=344}} From the start, the Economic Division undertook three important tasks: 1) Gather economic data in support of cases before the courts; 2) Conduct general studies of labor relations to guide the board in formulating decisions and policies; and 3) Research the history of labor relations (the history of written agreements, whether certain issues were historically part of collective bargaining, how unions functioned internally, trends in employer activities, trends in collective bargaining, whether certain employer actions led to labor disputes, etc.) so that the board could educate itself, the courts, Congress, and the public about labor relations.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=176\u201379}} The first function proved critical to the survival of the NLRB. It was the Economic Division's data and analysis, more than then NLRB's legal reasoning, which proved critical in persuading the Supreme Court to sustain the Wagner Act in ''NLRB v. Jones & Laughlin Steel''.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=176\u201379, 191}}{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=347}} The Court even cited several Economic Division studies in its decision.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=228\u201329}} In the wake of ''Jones & Laughlin Steel'', many labor relations experts outside the agency concluded that economic analysis was \"an accepted fact\" essential to the proper functioning of the agency.{{sfn|Gross|1974|p=233}} The Economic Division did, too.  It asked Madden to pair an economist with an attorney in every important case,{{sfn|Eisner|2000|p=101}} and prepared outline of the economic data needed to support each case in case it went before the courts.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=182\u201383}}\n\nDuring his time on the NLRB, Madden was often opposed by the [[American Federation of Labor]] (AFL), which believed that Madden was using the NLRA and the procedures and staff of the NLRB to favor the AFL's primary competitor, the [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] (CIO).<ref>Stark, Louis. \"Both A.F.L. and C.I.O. Hit at National Labor Board.\" ''New York Times.'' October 14, 1937.</ref>{{sfn|Gall|1999|pp=83\u201384, 97\u201398}} The NLRB and NLRA were also under intense pressure from employers, the press, congressional [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]], and conservative [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]].{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=171\u201373}}{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=2}}\n\nThe NLRB's Economic Division proved critical in pushing for a congressional investigation into employer anti-union activities, and ensuring that investigation was a success. The Economic Division was deeply aware of employer use of [[Labor spy|labor spies]], violence, and [[company union]]s to thwart union organizing, and quietly pressed for a congressional investigation into these and other tactics. Senator [[Robert M. La Follette, Jr.]] took up the suggestion, on June 6, 1936, the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Senate Committee on Education and Labor]] established a Subcommittee Investigating Violations of Free Speech and the Rights of Labor chaired by La Follette.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=214\u201323}} Better known as the \"[[La Follette Committee]]\", the subcommittee held extensive hearings for five years and published numerous reports.  The committee uncovered extensive evidence of millions of company dollars used to pay for spies and [[fifth column]]ists within unions, exposed the culpability of local law enforcement in acts of violence and murder against union supporters (particularly in the [[Harlan County War]]),{{sfn|Baker|Stack|2006|pp=56\u201357}} revealed the wide extent of illegal [[blacklisting]] of union members, and exposed the use of armed [[strikebreaker]]s and widespread stockpiling of tear gas, vomit gas, machine guns, mortars, and armor by corporations to use against [[Strike action|strikers]].{{sfn|Luff|2007|p=774}} Some of the evidence the committee used was provided by the Economic Division,{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=90}} and the investigation proved critical for a time in defending the agency from business and congressional attack.{{sfn|Gross|1974|pp=214\u201323}}\n\nThe biggest issue the NLRB faced was constitutional. The [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] and NLRB legal staff wanted the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] to rule as quickly as possible on the constitutionality of the NLRA. But the Board and Justice Department also realized that the Court's [[Lochner era|''Lochner'' era]] legal philosophy made it unlikely for the Court to uphold the Act. Subsequently, Madden strove to resolve minor cases before they could become court challenges, and worked to delay appeals as long as possible until the best possible case could be brought to the Court.{{sfn|Chasse|2011|p=57}} This legal strategy paid off. The Supreme Court upheld the NLRA in ''[[National Labor Relations Board v. Jones & Laughlin Steel Corporation]]'', 301 U.S. 1 (1937).{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=643\u201346}} Afterward, Madden continued to strategically guide the NLRB's legal efforts to strengthen the federal courts' view of the NLRA and the board's actions.{{sfn|Chasse|2011|p=57}} Because of the efforts of Madden and NLRB General Counsel Charles H. Fahy, the Supreme Court reviewed only 27 cases between August 1935 and March 1941, even though the board had processed nearly 5,000 cases since its inception. The Supreme Court enforced the NLRB's rulings in 19 cases without modifying them, enforced them with modification in six more, and denied enforcement in two cases. Additionally, the Board won all 30 [[injunction]] and all 16 representation cases before the lower courts, a rate of success unequalled by any other federal agency.{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=662\u201363}}\n\nAFL opposition to the \"Madden Board\" grew after decisions in ''Shipowners' Ass'n of the Pacific Coast'', 7 NLRB 1002 (1938), ''enf'd'' ''[[American Federation of Labor v. National Labor Relations Board]]'', 308 U.S. 401 (1940) (awarding a longshoremen's unit to the CIO rather than the AFL), and ''American Can Co.'', 13 NLRB 1252 (1939) (unit's history of collective bargaining outweighs desire of workers to form craft-only unit).<ref>{{harvnb|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=654\u201355}} The AFL held to a philosophy of [[craft unionism]], while the CIO believed in [[industrial unionism]]. According to the AFL, ''American Can'' decisively tipped NLRB policy in favor of the CIO.</ref>\n\nThe AFL began pushing for an investigation into the NLRB, and this investigation led to allegations of communist influence within the agency. In June 1938, the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (led by Chairman [[Martin Dies, Jr.]] [D-[[Texas|TX]]]) heard testimony from AFL leader [[John P. Frey]], who accused Madden of staffing the NLRB with [[Communism|communists]].<ref>\"Reds Start Count of Allies in Federal Jobs and Push Participation in C.I.O., Frey Says.\" ''New York Times.'' January 10, 1938; \"Communists Rule the C.I.O., Frey of A.F.L. Testifies.\" ''New York Times.'' August 14, 1938; \"High Federal Aides Are Linked to Reds at House Hearing.\" ''New York Times.'' August 18, 1938; \"Green Pushes Fight on 2 NLRB Members.\" ''New York Times.'' August 24, 1938; \"Council of A.F.L. Backs Dies Inquiry.\" ''New York Times.'' September 2, 1938; Stark, Louis. \"A.F.L. Report Asks NLRB Power Be Cut.\" ''New York Times.'' October 10, 1938.</ref> The allegations were true, in at least one case: [[Nathan Witt]], the NLRB's executive secretary and the man to whom Madden had delegated most administrative functions, was a member of the [[Communist Party of the United States]].{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|p=667}}{{sfn|Storrs|2013|p=65}} These allegations and discoveries significantly damaged the agency's support in Congress and with the public.\n\nA second investigation into the [[NLRB]] led to organizational changes at the board. On July 20, 1939, Republicans and conservative Democrats formed a coalition to push through the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] a resolution establishing a Special Committee to Investigate the National Labor Relations Board (the \"[[J. Warren Madden#The Smith Committee|Smith Committee]]\"), chaired by conservative, anti-labor Rep. [[Howard W. Smith]] (D-[[Virginia|VA]]).{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=151\u201354}}{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|p=668}} On March 7, 1940, the Smith Committee proposed legislation to abolish the NLRB, reconstitute it, and radically amend the NLRA.{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=194\u201399}}<ref>Among the changes proposed:  Removing of many of the guarantees of collective bargaining from the Wagner Act's preamble, denying legal protection to [[sitdown strike]]rs and agricultural workers, removing the requirement that employers must bargain with unions, making the General Counsel independent from the Board, abolishing the board's economic research unit, enhancing employer free speech rights, introducing the right of employers to seek an election among their workers, and removing the board's authority to engage in bargaining unit determination. See: {{harvnb|Bernstein|Piven|1969|p=670}}</ref><ref>\"Ramspeck Attacks NLRB to Roosevelt.\" ''New York Times.'' December 30, 1939; \"Republicans Urge Abolition of NLRB.\" ''New York Times.'' March 3, 1940; Dorris, Henry N. \"Smith Committee Asks End of NLRB, Revised Labor Law.\" ''New York Times.'' March 8, 1940; Stark, Louis. \"House Quickens Labor Act Battle.\" ''New York Times.'' March 17, 1940; \"Jackson Is Urged to Prosecute NLRB.\" ''New York Times.'' March 19, 1940.</ref> President Roosevelt opposed the bill, although he conceded that perhaps the Board's membership should be expanded to five from three.<ref>\"President Opposes Smith NLRB Changes.\" ''New York Times.'' March 13, 1940.</ref> The Smith bill won several early tests in the House, which also voted to substantially cut the NLRB's budget.<ref>\"NLRB of Five Men Again Wins in Test.\" ''New York Times.'' March 21, 1940; Dorris, Henry N. \"House Votes Rises for NYA and CCC, NLRB Cut Is Upheld.\" ''New York Times.'' March 29, 1940; Stark, Louis. \"House Unit Gets NLRB Bill Dissent.\" ''New York Times.'' April 10, 1940.</ref> Smith won a vote in the [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Rules Committee]] permitting him to bring his bill to the floor for a vote.<ref>\"Smith Moves to Get NLRB Bills to Floor.\" ''New York Times.'' April 14, 1940; \"Rival Labor Bills Put Before House.\" ''New York Times.'' April 20, 1940.</ref> In an attempt to defuse the legislative crisis, Madden fired 53 staff and forced another five to resign, and decentralized the NLRB's trial process to give regional directors and field agents more authority.<ref>\"NLRB Dismisses 53, 5 Quit, in Fund Cut.\" ''New York Times.'' May 25, 1940; \"Field Men to Rule for Labor Board.\" ''New York Times.'' May 26, 1940.</ref> But the House still passed the Smith bill by a vote of 258 to 129 on June 7, 1940.<ref>Dorris, Henry N. \"Sweeping Changes in Labor Act Voted by House, 258\u2013129.\" ''New York Times.'' June 8, 1940.</ref> To protect the NLRB, Roosevelt convinced Senator [[Elbert D. Thomas]], Chairman of the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions#Education and Labor, 1884\u20131947|Senate Committee on Education and Labor]], to hold no hearings or votes on the bill, and the legislation died.{{sfn|Bernstein|Piven|1969|pp=670\u201371}}{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=209\u201311}}\n\nThe Smith Committee investigation had a lasting effect on labor law in the U.S., and was the basis for the [[Taft-Hartley Act]] of 1947.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=225}}{{sfn|Atleson|1998|p=11}} Madden's term on the NLRB came to an end after just four years. On November 15, 1940, President Roosevelt nominated [[Harry A. Millis]] to the NLRB and named him Chairman, and nominated Madden to a seat on the U.S. Court of Claims.<ref>\"Dr. Millis Slated to Head the NLRB.\" ''New York Times.'' November 7, 1940; Hurd, Charles. \"Roosevelt Names Dr. Millis to NLRB, Replacing Madden.\" ''New York Times.'' November 16, 1940.</ref>\n\n===1940\u20131945: The Economics Division and World War II===\nAnother major structural change occurred at the same time that Madden left the NLRB. The Smith committee's anti-communist drive also targeted David J. Saposs, the NLRB Chief Industrial Economist. Saposs had been surreptitiously assessed by members of the Communist Party USA for membership, and rejected as a prospect.{{sfn|Gross|1974|p=220}} But Smith and others attacked Saposs as a communist, and Congress defunded his division and his job on October 11, 1940.{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=199, 202}}{{sfn|Jacobs|2007|pp=171\u201372}}{{sfn|Chasse|2011|p=58}} Although the Smith committee's investigation proved critical, the disestablishment of the Economic Division was due to many reasons\u2014both internal and external to the NLRB, and only some of which involved allegations of communist infiltration. As historian James A. Gross observed:.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}}\n<blockquote>The Division was eliminated for all kinds of reasons which had nothing to do with the merits and importance of its work:  political pressures and maneuverings, jealousy and empire building between and among lawyers and economists inside the Board, opposition to leftist ideologies, a personal attack on the Chief Economist, David Saposs, and a mighty hostility to the administrative process.</blockquote>\n\nThe loss of the Economic Division was a major blow to the NLRB.  It had a major tactical impact: Economic data helped the NLRB fulfill its adjudicatorial and prosecutorial work in areas such as [[unfair labor practice]]s (ULPs), representation elections, and in determining remedial actions (such as reinstatement, back pay awards, and fines).{{sfn|Stryker|1989|pp=346\u201347}} Economic data also undermined employer resistance to the agency by linking that opposition to employer ULPs.{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=349}} The loss also left the board dependent on the biased information offered by the parties in dispute before it, leading to poor decision-making and far less success in the courts.{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=266\u201367}} It also had a major strategic impact: It left the board unable to determine whether its administration of the law was effective or not.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=265}} Nor could the board determine whether labor unrest was a serious threat to the economy or not. As [[Labor history (discipline)|labor historian]] Josiah Bartlett Lambert put it: \"Without the Economic Research Division, the NLRB could not undertake empirical studies to determine the actual impact of [[Secondary action|secondary boycotts]], [[jurisdictional strike]]s, national emergency strikes, and the like.\"{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=104}} The Economic Division was critical to a long-range NLRB process to lead to the long-term evolution of industrial labor relations in the U.S., but that goal had to be abandoned.{{sfn|Eisner|2000|p=101}}{{sfn|Eisner|2010|pp=336\u201337}} Most importantly, however, the evisceration of the Economic Division struck at the fundamental purpose of federal labor law, which was to allow experts to adjudicate labor disputes rather than use a legal process. With this data and analysis, widespread skepticism about the board's expertise quickly spread through Congress and the courts.  It also left the board largely unable to engage in rule-making, forcing it to make labor law on an inefficient, time-consuming case-by-case basis.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=266}} As of 1981, NLRB was still the only federal agency forbidden to seek economic information about the impact of its activities.{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=264\u201365}}\n\nThe second Chairman of the NLRB, [[Harry A. Millis]], led the board in a much more moderate direction.{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=104}} Lacking an economic division to give it ammunition to fight with Millis deliberately made the NLRB dependent on Congress and the executive branch for its survival.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=261}} Millis made a large number of organizational changes. He stripped the office of Secretary of its power, set up an Administrative Division to supervise the 22 regional offices, initiated a study of the Board's administrative procedures, and genuinely delegated power to the regional offices.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=229}} He removed casehandling and regional office communication from the jurisdiction of the Office of the Secretary and created a Field Division.{{sfn|Tomlins|1985|p=225}}<ref>Stark, Louis. \"Methods of NLRB Indicated in Study Made By Own Men.\" New York Times. March 22, 1940.</ref> He also adopted procedures requiring the board made its decisions based solely on the trial examiner's report, authorized NLRB review attorneys to review trial examiner report, required decisions to be drafted ahead of time and distributed for review, authorized review attorneys to revise drafts before a final decision was issued, required trial examiners to emphasize findings of fact and to address points of law, and began holding board meetings when there were differences of opinion over decisions.{{sfn|Tomlins|1985|p=225}}\n\nMillis eliminated the Review Division's decisive role in cases, which had been established under Madden and Witt.{{sfn|Tomlins|1985|p=226}} Madden and Witt had adopted a highly centralized Board structure so that (generally speaking) only the cases most favorable to the board made it to the courts. The centralized structure meant that only the strongest cases made it to national board, so that the board could apply all its economic and legal powers to crafting the best decision possible. This strategy enabled the NLRB to defend itself very well before the Supreme Court. But Madden and Witt had held on to the centralized strategy too long, and made political enemies in the process. Millis substituted a decentralized process in which the board was less a decision-maker and more a provider of services to the regions.{{sfn|Tomlins|1985|p=226}} Many of the changes Millis instituted were designed to mimic requirements placed on other agencies by the [[Administrative Procedure Act (United States)|Administrative Procedure Act]].{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}}\n\nAmerican entry into World War II on December 8, 1941, significantly changed the NLRB. On January 12, 1942, President Roosevelt created the [[National War Labor Board (1942\u20131945)|National War Labor Board]] (NWLB), which displaced the NLRB as the main focus of federal labor relations for the duration of the war. The NWLB was given the authority to \"finally determine\" any labor dispute which threatened to interrupt war production, and to stabilize union wages and benefits during the war. Although Roosevelt instructed the NWLB not to intrude on jurisdiction exercised by the NLRB, the War Labor Board refused to honor this request. From 1942 to 1945, Millis tried to secure a jurisdictional agreement with NWLB Chairman George W. Taylor. But these discussions proved fruitless, and Millis broke them off in June 1945. The NWLB also heavily raided the NLRB for staff, significantly hindering NLRB operations.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=243}}\n\nAdditional changes came with the passage of the [[War Labor Disputes Act]] (WLDA) on June 25, 1943. Enacted over Roosevelt's veto after 400,000 coal miners, their wages significantly lower due to high wartime inflation, struck for a $2-a-day wage increase,{{sfn|Malsberger|2000|p=104}}{{sfn|Karatnycky|2000|p=115}} the legislation (in part) required the NLRB to issue a ballot outlining all the collective bargaining proposals and counter-proposals, wait 30 days, and then hold a strike vote.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=244}} The War Labor Disputes Act proved very burdensome.  The NLRB processed 2,000 WLDA cases from 1943 to the end of 1945, of which 500 were strike votes. The act's strike vote procedures did little to stop strikes, however, and Millis feared unions were using the referendums to whip up pro-strike feelings among their members. Millis also believed the law's strike vote process permitted more strikes to occur than the NLRB would have allowed under its old procedures. There were so many strike vote filings in the six months after the war ended that NLRB actually shut down its long distance telephone lines, cancelled all out of town travel, suspended all public hearings, and suspended all other business to accommodate the workload.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=245}} By early 1945, Millis was in ill health.<ref>\"Dr. H.A. Millis Dies.\" ''New York Times.'' June 26, 1948.</ref>  He resigned from the NLRB on June 7, 1945,<ref>\"In Administration Shake-Up\", ''Associated Press,'' June 8, 1945.</ref> and [[Paul M. Herzog]] was named his successor.\n\n===1947\u20131965: Taft-Hartley===\nA major turning point in the history of the NLRB came in 1947 with passage of the [[Taft-Hartley Act]]. Disruptions caused by strikes during World War II as well as the huge wave of strikes that followed the end of the war fueled a growing movement in 1946 and 1947 to amend the NLRA to correct what critics saw as a pro-labor tilt in federal law.<ref>Stark, Louis. \"Save Bargaining, Keep Peace In Industry, Says NLRB Head.\" ''New York Times.'' March 7, 1947.</ref>{{sfn|Gross|1981|pp=251\u201352}} Drafted by the powerful Republican Senator [[Robert A. Taft]] and the strongly anti-union Representative [[Fred A. Hartley, Jr.]], the Taft-Hartley Act banned jurisdictional strikes, [[Wildcat strike action|wildcat strikes]], political strikes, [[Secondary action|secondary boycotts]], secondary picketing, mass picketing, union campaign donations made from dues money, the [[closed shop]], and unions of supervisors. The act also enumerated new employer rights, defined union-committed ULPs, gave states the right to opt out of federal labor law through [[right-to-work law]]s, required unions to give an 80-days' strike notice in all cases, established procedures for the President to end a strike in a national emergency, and required all union officials to sign an anti-Communist oath. Organizationally, the act made the General Counsel a presidential appointee, independent of the board itself, and gave the General Counsel limited powers to seek injunctions without referring to the Justice Department. It also banned the NLRB from engaging in any mediation or conciliation, and formally enshrined in law the ban on hiring personnel to do economic data collection or analysis.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}}\n\nIn August 1947, [[Robert N. Denham]] became the NRLB's [[general counsel]]. He held \"conservative views\" and wielded \"considerable influence\" on labor-management relations and interpretations of the newly passed [[Taft-Hartley Act]]. In 1950, US President [[Harry S. Truman]] fired Denham (''New York Times'':  \"left at the behest of the President\").<ref name=DenhamPapers>\n{{cite web\n| title = Denham, Robert N. (1885-1954), Papers, 1919-1954\n| publisher = State Historical Society of Missouri\n| url = https://collections.shsmo.org/manuscripts/columbia/c0012.pdf\n| date = \n| accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=NYT-Denham>\n{{cite news\n| title = Robert N. Denham Dies; N.L.R.B. Ex-General Counsel Victim of Heart Attack\n| publisher = State Historical Society of Missouri\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1954/06/19/archives/robert-n-denham-dies-n-l-r-b-exgeneral-counsel-victim-of-heart.html\n| pages = \n| date = 19 June 1954\n| accessdate = 27 October 2019}}</ref> While NLRB general counsel, Denham received considerable news coverage as a \"quasi-Republican.\"  Nominated by US President [[Harry S. Truman]],<ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = The President's News Conference: July 17, 1947 \n| publisher = Harry S. Truman Library & Museum\n| url = https://www.trumanlibrary.gov/library/public-papers/145/presidents-news-conference-0\n| date = 17 July 1947\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref> Denham received unanimous approval by the US Senate Labor Committee. He received \"full and independent powers to investigate violations, file complaints and prosecute offenders before the board.\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Labor: Fair Target\n| publisher = TIME\n| url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,855805,00.html\n| date = 4 August 1947\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref> In August 1947, he supported an \"Anti-Red Affidavit Rule\" and so sided with US Senator [[Robert A. Taft]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = Denham Is Reported Determined To Keep Anti-Red Affidavit Rule\n| first = Louis \n| last = Starkspecial\n| work = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1947/08/30/archives/denham-is-reported-determined-to-keep-antired-affidavit-rule.html\n| page = 28\n| date = 30 August 1947\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>  In October 1947, the NRLB overruled him, which meant that top officers of the [[American Federation of Labor]] (AFL) and [[Congress of Industrial Organizations]] (CIO) would not have to sign an anti-Communist oath per the Taft-Hartley Act.<ref>\n{{cite news\n| title = National Affairs: Reversal\n| publisher = TIME\n| url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,804309,00.html\n| date = 20 October 1947\n| accessdate = 28 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHerzog publicly admitted the need for some change in the NLRA, but privately he opposed the proposed Taft-Hartley amendments. He felt the communist oath provisions were unconstitutional, that the amendments would turn the NLRA into a management weapon, that creation of an independent General Counsel would weaken the NLRB, and that the law's dismantling of the agency's economic analysis unit deprived the NLRB of essential expertise.{{sfn|Gross|2010|pp=11\u201313}} Nonetheless, Congress overrode Truman's veto of the Taft-Hartley Act on June 23, 1947, and the bill became law.{{sfn|Lee|1980|pp=101\u201303}}\n\nThe Taft-Hartley Act fundamentally changed the nature of federal labor law, but it also seriously hindered the NLRB's ability to enforce the law. The loss of the mediation function left the NLRB unable to become involved in labor disputes, a function it had engaged in since its inception as the National Labor Board in 1933. This hindered the agency's efforts to study, analyze, and create bulwarks against [[Good faith|bad-faith]] [[collective bargaining]]; reduced its ability to formulate national labor policy in this area; and left the agency making labor law on an ineffective, time-consuming case-by-case basis.{{sfn|Lambert|2005|p=104}} The separation of the General Counsel from supervision by the national board also had significant impact on the agency. This separation was enacted against the advice of the Justice Department, contradicted the policy Congress had enacted in the Administrative Procedure Act of 1946, and ignored Millis' extensive internal reforms. The change left the NLRB as the only federal agency unable to coordinate its decision-making and legal activities, and the only agency exempted in this manner under the Administrative Procedure Act. The separation of the General Counsel was not discussed by the committee or by any witnesses during the legislation's mark-up. Indeed, there was no basis for it at all in the public record.{{sfn|Gross|1981|p=264}} It was, in the words of sociologist Robin Stryker, \"little-noted\" and \"unprecedented\".{{sfn|Stryker|1989|p=344}}\n\nThe anti-communist oath provisions generated extensive public debate, and generated disputes before the Supreme Court several times. The Taft-Hartley oath first reached the court in [[American Communications Ass'n v. Douds]], {{Ussc|339|382|1950|el=no}}, in which the court held 5-to-1 that the oath did not violate the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]], was not an ''[[ex post facto]]'' law or [[bill of attainder]] in violation of [[Article One of the United States Constitution#Section 10: Limits on the States|Article One, Section 10]], and was not a \"test oath\" in violation of [[Article Six of the United States Constitution#Oaths|Article Six]]. The issue again came before the court in [[Garner v. Board of Public Works]], {{Ussc|341|716|1951|el=no}}, in which the court unanimously held that a municipal [[loyalty oath]] was not an ''ex post facto law'' or bill of attainder. It came before the court yet a third time in ''Wieman v. Updegraff'', {{Ussc|344|183|1952|el=no}}. This time, the outcome was radically different. The Supreme Court unanimously ruled that state loyalty oath legislation violated the [[due process]] clause of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]]. In 1965, the Supreme Court held 5-to-4 that the anti-communist oath was a bill of attainder in ''[[United States v. Brown (1965)|United States v. Brown]]'', {{Ussc|381|437|1965|el=no}}.<ref>\"Beyond Process: A Substantive Rationale for the Bill of Attainder Clause.\" ''Virginia Law Review.'' April 1984, p. 485.</ref> The Supreme Court essentially overturned ''Douds'', but did not formally do so.{{sfn|Rabinowitz|1996|p=56}}\n\n===1966\u20132007===\n\nThe board itself (as an adjudicating body distinct from the functions separated as a result of Taft-Harley) has a fixed seating which is assigned based on the names of<ref>[https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/members-nlrb-1935 names of the original board members] The complete personnel list of the board since its inception at nlrb.gov</ref> 5 original members.\n\n===2007\u20132013: Lack of quorum===\nFrom December 2007 until June 2010, the five-person Board had only two members, creating a legal controversy. Three members' terms expired in December 2007, leaving the NLRB with just two members\u2014Chairman [[Wilma B. Liebman]] and Member Peter Schaumber.<ref name=\"Hananel\">Hananel, Sam. [http://www.boston.com/news/nation/washington/articles/2009/09/07/on_labor_day_us_labor_board_remains_in_gridlock \"On Labor Day, Labor Board Still in Gridlock\"], ''Boston Globe'', September 7, 2009.</ref> President [[George W. Bush]] refused to make some nominations to the Board and Senate [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] refused to confirm those which he did make.<ref name=\"Hananel\"/><ref name=\"Hananel2\">Hananel, Sam. \"Justice Asks High Court to OK Labor Board Rulings\", ''Associated Press'', September 29, 2009.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name=\"Greenhouse\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/15/us/politics/15nlrb.html Greenhouse, Steven. \"Labor Panel Is Stalled by Dispute on Nominee\"], ''[[The New York Times]].'' January 14, 2010.</ref>\n\nOn December 28, 2007, just before the Board lost its quorum, the four members agreed to delegate their authority to a three-person panel per the [[National Labor Relations Act]].<ref name=\"Greenhouse\"/><ref name=\"CCHLabor\">[http://hr.cch.com/news/employment/011008a.asp \"NLRB Temporarily Delegates Litigation Authority to General Counsel\"], ''CCH/Aspen Labor & Employment Law.'' January 10, 2008.</ref> Only Liebman and Schaumber remained on the Board, but the Board concluded that the two constituted a [[quorum]] of the three-person panel and thus could make decisions on behalf of the Board.<ref name=\"Greenhouse\"/><ref name=\"CCHLabor\"/> Liebman and Schaumber informally agreed to decide only those cases which were in their view noncontroversial and on which they could agree, and issued almost 400 decisions between January 2008 and September 2009.<ref name=\"Hananel\"/><ref name=\"Hananel2\"/><ref name=\"Greenhouse\"/><ref name=\"InsideCounsel\">\"Court Invalidates Two-Member NLRB Decision\", ''Inside Counsel'', July 2009.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name=\"Pickler\">Pickler, Nedra. \"NLRB Decisions Cause Conflicting Court Opinions.\" ''Associated Press'', May 1, 2009.</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nThe U.S. Courts of Appeals for the [[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|First]], [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|Second]], and [[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|Seventh]] Circuits upheld the two-member NLRB's authority to decide cases, while the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit|D.C. Circuit Court of Appeals]] did not.<ref name=\"Hananel\"/><ref name=\"Hananel2\"/>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name=\"InsideCounsel\" />{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}<ref name=\"Pickler\"/>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}} In September 2009, the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]] asked the [[Supreme Court of the United States|U.S. Supreme Court]] to immediately hear arguments concerning the dispute, given the high stakes involved.<ref name=\"Hananel2\"/> The Supreme Court granted [[certiorari]] in October and agreed to decide the issue.<ref>\"U.S. Supreme Court to Rule on National Labor Relations Board Issue\", ''Lawyers USA'', November 2, 2009; [https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8786398 \"Court to Decide If Two-Person Labor Board Legal\"], ''Associated Press.'' November 2, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, the Supreme Court ruled in ''[[New Process Steel, L. P. v. NLRB]]'' that the two-member Board had no authority to issue decisions, invalidating all rulings made by Liebman and Schaumber.<ref>130 S. Ct. 2635, 2638 (2010).</ref>{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}} In 2013, the question of a legitimate quorum on the NLRB surfaced again, when the [[United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit]] ruled that President Obama had \"violated the Constitution when he bypassed the Senate to fill three board vacancies\".{{sfn|Trottman|Maher|2013}}{{full citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Structure==\n{{refimprove section|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:1099 14th Street \u2013 National Labor Relations Board - sign.JPG|thumb|right|Plaque on the exterior of [[1099 14th Street]] NW in Washington, D.C., the NLRB headquarters as of 2013.]]\n[[File:NLRB picketing 2007.jpg|thumb|right|Union members picketing NLRB rulings outside the agency's [[Washington, D.C.]], headquarters in November 2007.]]\nIn 1947, the [[Taft\u2013Hartley Act]] created a formal administrative distinction between the Board and the General Counsel of the NLRB. In broad terms, the General Counsel is responsible for investigating and prosecuting [[unfair labor practice]] claims and for the general supervision of the NLRB field offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/general-counsel|title=The General Counsel - NLRB|website=www.nlrb.gov}}</ref> The General Counsel is appointed by the President to a four-year term and independent from the Board; it has limited independence to argue for a change in the law in presenting cases to the Board. The General Counsel oversees four divisions: the Division of Operations Management, the Division of Administration, the Division of Advice, and the Division of Enforcement Litigation.\n\nThe Board, on the other hand, is the adjudicative body that decides the unfair labor practice cases brought to it. Once the Board has decided the issue, it is the General Counsel's responsibility to uphold the Board's decision, even if it is contrary to the position it advocated when presenting the case to the Board. The Board is also responsible for the administration of the Act's provisions governing the holding of elections and resolution of jurisdictional disputes.\n\nThe Board has more than thirty regional offices. The regional offices conduct elections, investigate unfair labor practice charges, and make the initial determination on those charges (whether to dismiss, settle, or issue complaints). The Board has jurisdiction to hold elections and prosecute violations of the Act in [[Puerto Rico]] and [[American Samoa]].\n\n===Jurisdiction===\nThe Board's [[jurisdiction]] is limited to [[private sector]] employees and the [[United States Postal Service]]; other than Postal Service employees, it has no authority over labor relations disputes involving governmental, [[railroad]] and [[airline]] employees covered by the [[Adamson Railway Labor Act]], or agricultural employees. On the other hand, in those parts of the private sector its jurisdictional standards are low enough to reach almost all employers whose business has any appreciable impact on [[interstate commerce]].\n\n===Processing of charges===\nCharges are filed by parties against unions or employers with the appropriate regional office. The regional office will investigate the complaint. If a violation is believed to exist, the region will take the case before an [[Administrative Law Judge]] who will conduct a hearing. The decision of the Administrative Law Judge may be reviewed by the five member Board. Board decisions are reviewable by [[United States Courts of Appeals]]. The Board's decisions are not self-executing: it must seek court enforcement in order to force a recalcitrant party to comply with its orders. (For greater detail on this process see the entry for [[unfair labor practice]]).\n\n==General Counsel==\n[[Lafe Solomon]] was named Acting General Counsel on June 21, 2010. His nomination was sent to the U.S. Senate on January 5, 2011. Solomon's authority came into question on August 13, 2013 when Judge [[Benjamin Settle]] for the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Washington]] denied a petition for [[Temporary restraining order#Injunctions in US labor law context|injunctive]] relief, ruling that Solomon had not been properly appointed under the [[Federal Vacancies Reform Act of 1998]] (FVRA).<ref>{{citation |last=Trottman |first=Melanie |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2013/08/22/ruling-on-top-lawyer-adds-to-nlrb-questions |title=Ruling on Top Lawyer Adds to NLRB Questions |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=August 22, 2013 |accessdate= August 22, 2013}}</ref> Although other [[United States district court|district courts]] had enforced Solomon's requests, Judge Settle's decision called into question all of Solomon's activity since June 21, 2010, focusing on subsections (a)(1) and (2) of the FVRA; some pundits claimed that Solomon's appointment was allowed under subsection (a)(3).<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.laborrelationstoday.com/2013/08/articles/presidential-appointments/another-setback-for-the-nlrb-federal-district-court-invalidates-the-acting-general-counsels-appointment |title=Another Setback for the NLRB: Federal District Court Invalidates the Acting General Counsel's Appointment |work=Labor Relations Today |date=August 22, 2013 |accessdate= August 22, 2013}}</ref> President Obama withdrew Solomon's nomination.\n\nOn July 31, 2013, President Obama nominated former NLRB nominee Richard Griffin as General Counsel\u2014\"a kind of prosecutor at the board\" and \"one of the most critical roles at the agency.\"<ref name=\"huffingtonpost_2013\">{{cite web | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/17/richard-griffin-nlrb_n_3611585.html | title=Richard Griffin, Former NLRB Nominee, To Be Offered General Counsel Slot After Filibuster Deal | publisher=Huffington Post | date=July 18, 2013 | accessdate=April 4, 2016 |first1=Dave |last1=Jamieson |first2=Ryan |last2=Grim}}</ref> Solomon's nomination was withdrawn.<ref name=vail>{{citation |url=http://inthesetimes.com/working/entry/15380/senate_approves_new_members_for_national_labor_board |last=Vail |first=Bruce |title=National Labor Board Shutdown Averted as Senate Approves New Members |work=In These Times |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}</ref> The Senate approved Griffin's nomination on October 29, 2013, by a vote of 55 to 44.<ref>{{cite news|last=Devaney|first=Tim|title=Rejected NLRB pick wins vote to serve as board counsel|work=The Washington Times|date=October 29, 2013|accessdate=April 26, 2016|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/oct/29/obama-nlrb-counsel-pick-wins-key-vote/?page=all}}</ref>\n\n==Board members==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Seat<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/members-nlrb-1935|title=Members of the NLRB since 1935|author=nlrb.gov}}</ref>\n! Member\n! Entered office\n! Term expires\n|-\n| Carmody<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 8 and 3)</div>\n| ''Vacant'' \n| \n| August 27, 2023<!--Mark Gaston Pearce (D)\n| April 7, 2010<ref>https://www.law360.com/articles/1077826/trump-taps-nlrb-s-pearce-for-3rd-term</ref>-->\n|-\n| Gray<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 9 and 4)</div>\n| ''Vacant'' \n| \n| December 16, 2024\n|-\n| Smith<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 6 and 1)</div>\n| [[William Emanuel]] (R)\n|September 28, 2017\n| August 27, 2021\n|-\n| [[Orrice Abram Murdock Jr.|Murdock]]<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 7 and 2)</div>\n| [[John F. Ring]] (R)\n| April 16, 2018\n| December 16, 2022\n|-\n| [[J. Warren Madden|Madden]]<div style=\"font-size:80%\">(Term expires in years ending 5 and 0)</div>\n| [[Marvin Kaplan (lawyer)|Marvin Kaplan]] (R) \n| August 10, 2017<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nlrb.gov/news-outreach/news-story/marvin-e-kaplan-sworn-nlrb-member |title=Marvin E. Kaplan Sworn in as NLRB Member|date=10 August 2017|accessdate=16 August 2017}}</ref>\n| August 27, 2020\n|}\n\n===2007\u20132013: Unoccupied board seats===\nIn April 2009, President Obama nominated Craig Becker (Associate General Counsel of the [[Service Employees International Union]]), Mark Gaston Pearce (a member on the Industrial Board of Appeals, an agency of the New York State Department of Labor), and Brian Hayes (Republican Labor Policy Director for the [[United States Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor, and Pensions|Senate Committee on Health, Education, Labor and Pensions]]) to fill the three empty seats on the NLRB.<ref name=\"Hananel\"/>\n\nBecker's nomination appeared to fail on February 8, 2010, after Republican Senators (led by [[John McCain]]) threatened to filibuster his nomination.<ref name=\"Greenhouse\" /><ref name=\"Failed\">[http://voices.washingtonpost.com/federal-eye/2010/02/nlrb_nominee_craig_becker_fail.html O'Keefe, Ed. \"Craig Becker, nominated for NLRB, rejected by Senate\"], ''Washington Post''. February 9, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/12/us/politics/12confirm.html \"Senate Confirms 2 Dozen Obama Nominees\"], ''New York Times.'' February 11, 2010.</ref> President Obama said he would consider making [[recess appointment]]s to the NLRB due to the Senate's failure to move on any of the three nominations.<ref name=\"Failed\"/> On March 27, 2010, Obama recess appointed Becker and Pearce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-positions|date=March 27, 2010|title=President Obama Announces Recess Appointments to Key Administration Positions|author=The White House, Office of the Press Secretary|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022015004/http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-positions|archivedate=October 22, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2010, a [[voice vote]] in the Senate confirmed Pearce to a full term, allowing him to serve until August 27, 2013. The same day, the Senate confirmed Republican nominee Brian Hayes of Massachusetts by voice vote. Hayes' term ended on December 16, 2012.<ref>Trottman, Melanie. [https://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2012/12/17/labor-relations-board-loses-voice-of-dissent \"Labor Board Loses Voice of Dissent\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', December 17, 2012; accessed 2013-01-27.</ref> Becker's term, as a recess appointee, ended on December 31, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newmediajournal.us/indx.php/item/1450|title=Media Journal coverage of the NLRB appointments|publisher=}}</ref> Effective August 28, 2011, Pearce was named Chairman to replace Democrat Wilma Liebman, whose term had expired.<ref>Geman, B.[http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/178489-labor-board-chief-departs-as-uncertainty-for-panel-looms \"NLRB chairwoman departs; political fights loom for labor panel\"], ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' Briefing Room, August 27, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2012, Obama announced [[recess appointment]]s to three seats on the board: Sharon Block, Terence F. Flynn, and Richard Griffin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2012/01/04/president-obama-announces-recess-appointments-key-administration-posts|title=President Obama Announces Recess Appointments to Key Administration Posts|author=The White House, Office of the Press Secretary|date=January 4, 2012|accessdate=January 4, 2012}}</ref> The appointments were criticized by Republicans, including the House Speaker [[John Boehner]], as unconstitutional and \"a brazen attempt to undercut the role of the Senate to advise and consent the executive branch on appointments\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Bucking Senate, Obama Appoints Consumer Chief|author=Helene Cooper|author2=Jennifer Steinhauer|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/05/us/politics/richard-cordray-named-consumer-chief-in-recess-appointment.html?pagewanted=all|work=The New York Times|date=January 4, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> Although made as recess appointments, critics questioned their legality, arguing that Congress had not officially been in recess as pro forma sessions had been held.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/01/04/obama-tempts-fight-over-recess-appointments|title=Obama tempts fight over recess appointments|author=Charlie Savage|date=January 4, 2012|work=The Caucus|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> Former U.S. attorney general [[Edwin Meese]] stated that in his opinion, since the appointments were made when the Senate was \"demonstrably not in recess\" they represented \"a constitutional abuse of a high order\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama's recess appointments are unconstitutional|author=Edwin Meese|author2=Todd Gaziano|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/obamas-recess-appointments-are-unconstitutional/2012/01/05/gIQAnWRfdP_story.html|work=The Washington Post|date=January 5, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref> On January 12, 2012 the U.S. Justice Department released a memo stating that appointments made during pro forma sessions are supported by the Constitution and precedent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama Has Recess Appointment Power, Justice Department Says|author=Seth Stern|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2012/01/12/bloomberg_articlesLXP7PE6K50XW.DTL|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=January 12, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 25, 2013, in ''Noel Canning v. NLRB'', a panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit ruled that President Obama's recess appointments were invalid as they were not made during an intersession recess of the Senate, and the President moved to fill them during the same recess.<ref>Greenhouse, Steven. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/26/us/labor-relations-board-rulings-could-be-undone.html \"More Than 300 Labor Board Decisions Could Be Nullified\"], ''New York Times'', January 25, 2013; accessed 2013-01-26.</ref> On May 16, 2013, in ''National Labor Relations Board v. New Vista Nursing and Rehabilitation'', the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit became the second federal appellate court to rule that the recess appointments to the NLRB were unconstitutional. In a split decision, it also found that the March 27, 2010 recess appointment of Craig Becker was unconstitutional.<ref>Allenson, Sheryl C. and Milam-Perez, Lisa. [http://www.employmentlawdaily.com/index.php/2013/05/16/former-board-member-craig-becker-invalidly-recess-appointed/#sthash.ScW6uRak.dpuf \"Former Board member Craig Becker invalidly recess-appointed; clause refers to 'intrasession break'\"], ''Employment Law Daily'', May 16, 2013; accessed February 1, 2014.</ref> On January 14, 2014, the U.S. Supreme Court heard the case in ''[[National Labor Relations Board v. Noel Canning]]''.<ref>Liptak, Adam. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/25/us/justices-agree-to-hear-case-on-presidents-recess-appointments.html \"Justices to Hear Case on Obama's Recess Appointments\"], ''New York Times'', June 24, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref><ref>Williams, Victor. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/victor-williams/the-supreme-court-should-_2_b_4586974.html \"The Supreme Court Should Stay Out of the Noel Canning Recess Fight\"], ''Huffington Post'', January 14, 2014; accessed February 1, 2014.</ref>\n\nBetween January 2008 and mid-July 2013 the agency never had all five members, and not once did it operate with three confirmed members.<ref>Landler, Mark and Greenhouse, Steven. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/16/us/politics/vacancies-and-partisan-fighting-put-labor-relations-agency-in-legal-limbo.html \"Vacancies and Partisan Fighting Put Labor Relations Agency in Legal Limbo\"], ''New York Times'', July 15, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref> On July 14, 2013, Senate Majority Leader [[Harry Reid]] threatened to exercise the \"[[nuclear option]]\" and allow a simple majority (rather than a [[supermajority]]) of the Senate to end a [[filibuster]]. This threat to end the filibuster's privileged position in the Senate was intended to end Republican filibustering of NLRB nominees.<ref>Weisman, Jonathan and Parker, Ashley. [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/16/us/politics/democrats-seeing-precedent-press-on-to-curb-filibuster.html \"Senate's Leader Sets Showdown Over Changes to Filibuster\"], ''New York Times'', July 15, 2013; accessed 2013-07-16.</ref> On July 16, 2013, President Obama and Senate Republicans reached an agreement to end the impasse over NLRB appointees. Obama withdrew the pending nominations of Block and Griffin, and submit two new nominees: Nancy Schiffer, associate general counsel at the AFL-CIO, and Kent Hirozawa, chief counsel to NLRB Chairman Mark Gaston Pearce. Republicans agreed not to oppose a fourth nominee, to be submitted in 2014.<ref>[http://www.politico.com/story/2013/07/white-house-consults-with-afl-cio-head-on-nlrb-picks-94280.html Everett, Burgess and Bresnahan, John. \"Obama Selects NLRB Replacement Picks\"], ''Politico'', July 16, 2013; accessed July 16, 2013.</ref>\n\nOn July 30, 2013, the Senate confirmed all five of Obama's nominees for the NLRB: Kent Hirozawa, Harry I. Johnson III, [[Philip A. Miscimarra]], Mark Gaston Pearce and Nancy Schiffer. Johnson and Miscimarra represented the Republican nominees for the board.<ref>Cox, Ramsey.[http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/314503-senate-votes-to-confirm-all-five-nlrb-members#ixzz2aemFMR3p \"Senate Confirms All Five NLRB Members\"], ''The Hill'', July 30, 2013; accessed 2013-07-31.</ref> Pearce was confirmed for a second five-year term.<ref>[http://www.chicagobusiness.com/article/20130731/NEWS04/130739947/chicago-attorney-tapped-for-national-labor-relations-board \"Chicago Attorney Tapped for National Labor Relations Board\"], ''Chicago Business Journal'', July 31, 2013; accessed July 31, 2013.</ref>  Nancy Schiffer's term ended on December 15, 2014. She was succeeded by Lauren McFerran on December 16, 2014. Harry I. Johnson III's term ended on August 27, 2015.<ref>[https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/board-members-1935 NLRB official website], nlrb.gov; accessed February 4, 2016.</ref>\n\n===2017 appointments===\nOn January 25, 2017, President [[Donald Trump]] appointed Philip Miscimarra the acting Chairman of the NLRB.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wiessner|first=Daniel|title=Trump taps Republican EEOC, NLRB members as acting chairs|work=Reuters|date=January 25, 2017|accessdate=January 26, 2017|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/trump-appointments-idUSL1N1FF20G}}</ref> Miscimarra's term expired on December 16, 2017. [[Marvin Kaplan (lawyer)|Marvin Kaplan]] succeeded him as NLRB Chairman on December 21, 2017.<ref name=nlrb_chair_confirm_vote>{{cite web|author=United States Senate|url=https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/roll_call_lists/roll_call_vote_cfm.cfm?congress=115&session=1&vote=00184|title=Confirmation Marvin Kaplan, of Kansas, to be a Member of the National Labor Relations Board|date=September 25, 2017|accessdate=December 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=trump_named_kaplan_chairman>{{cite web|author=National Labor Relations Board|url=https://www.nlrb.gov/who-we-are/board/marvin-e-kaplan|title=Marvin E. Kaplan|date=|accessdate=December 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Organized labour}}\n* [[US labor law]]\n* [[Federal Labor Relations Authority]]\n* [[Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service (United States)]]\n* [[List of Chairmen of the National Labor Relations Board]]\n* [[NLRB election procedures]]\n* [[Subpoena ad testificandum]]\n* [[Subpoena duces tecum]]\n* [[Title 29 of the Code of Federal Regulations]]\n* [[Union organizer]]\n* [[USA.gov]]\n* [[USAFacts]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|first=James B.|last=Atleson|title=Labor and the Wartime State: Labor Relations and Law During World War II|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=fZ7wf-45KPcC}}|date=January 1, 1998|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-06674-0|ref=harv |oclc=605496878}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Thomas E.|last1=Baker|authorlink1=Thomas E. Baker|first2=John F.|last2=Stack|title=At War with Civil Rights and Civil Liberties|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=svxzgTPwG1wC}}|year=2006|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers|isbn=978-0-7425-3599-2|ref=harv |oclc=646057221}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Irving|last1=Bernstein|authorlink=Irving Bernstein|first2=Frances Fox|last2=Piven|authorlink2=Frances Fox Piven|title=The Turbulent Years: A History of the American Worker, 1933-1941|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=aaHaroUImGIC}}|year=1969|publisher=Haymarket Books|isbn=978-1-60846-064-9|ref=harv |oclc=776982985}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Malcolm|editor-last1=Rutherford|title=The Institutionalist Movement in American Economics, 1918\u20131947: Science and Social Control|chapter-url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=XfX72hARkpsC|page=361}}|date=February 21, 2011|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-49756-5|last=Chasse|first=J. Dennis|chapter=John R. Commons and His Students: The View From the End of the Twentieth Century|ref=harv |oclc=474282342}}\n* {{cite book|first1=Melvyn|last1=Dubofsky|authorlink=Melvyn Dubofsky|first2=Foster Rhea|last2=Dulles|title=Labor in America: A History|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=gIZDPwAACAAJ}}|date=January 2004|publisher=Harlan Davidson|isbn=978-0-88295-998-6|ref=harv |oclc=300754496}}\n* {{cite book|first=Marc Allen|last=Eisner|title=From Warfare State to Welfare State: World War I, Compensatory State-Building, and the Limits of the Modern Order|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=lHibH8WJfuMC}}|date=November 1, 2010|publisher=Penn State Press|isbn=978-0-271-04350-0|ref=harv |oclc=49414683}}\n* {{cite book|first=Marc Allen|last=Eisner|title=Regulatory Politics in Transition|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=HAmT6fuhwQcC}}|year=2000|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-6492-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Gilbert J.|last=Gall|title=Pursuing Justice: Lee Pressman, the New Deal, and the CIO|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=xCYoLnaWXdoC}}|year=1999|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-4103-9|ref=harv |oclc=43476605}}\n* {{cite book|first=James A.|last=Gross|authorlink=James A. Gross|title=Broken Promise: The Subversion Of U.S. Labor Relations|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=yV0pX9PU1LEC}}|date=June 10, 2010|publisher=Temple University Press|isbn=978-1-4399-0370-4|ref=harv |oclc=693761467}}\n* {{cite book|first=James A.|last=Gross|authorlink=James A. Gross|title=The Making of the National Labor Relations Board: A Study in Economics, Politics, and the Law: Volume 1 (1933-1937)|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=v8-GnqDCGyAC}}|year=1974|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-87395-271-2|ref=harv |oclc=505722441}}\n* {{cite book|first=James A.|last=Gross|authorlink=James A. Gross|title=Reshaping of the National Labor Relations Board: A Study in Economics, Politics, and the Law|location=Albany, NY|publisher=[[SUNY Press]]|year=1981|ref=harv |oclc=555229476}}\n* {{cite book|first=Meg|last=Jacobs|title=Pocketbook Politics: Economic Citizenship in Twentieth-Century America|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=xWNPAQAAQBAJ}}|date=February 20, 2007|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-4378-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Adrian|last=Karatnycky|title=Freedom in the World: The Annual Survey of Political Rights and Civil Liberties, 2000-2001|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=Mz57SSzuYecC}}|year=2000|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-5008-7|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Josiah Bartlett|last=Lambert|title=\"If the Workers Took a Notion\": The Right to Strike and American Political Development|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=IjecnphnVZQC}}|year=2005|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-8945-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=R. Alton|last=Lee|title=Truman and Taft Hartley: A Question of Mandate|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=Xa4rAAAAYAAJ}}|year=1980|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group, Incorporated|isbn=978-0-313-22618-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Eric|editor-last=Arnesen|title=Encyclopedia of U.S. Labor and Working-class History|chapter-url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=zEWsZ81Bd3YC}}|year=2007|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-96826-3|last=Luff|first=Jennifer|authorlink1=Jennifer D. Luff|chapter=LaFollette Civil Liberties Committee |volume=1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=John William|last=Malsberger|title=From Obstruction to Moderation: The Transformation of Senate Conservatism, 1938-1952|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=xzF9F2I5nFkC}}|year=2000|publisher=Susquehanna University Press|isbn=978-1-57591-026-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Charles J.|last=Morris|authorlink=Charles Morris (legal educator)|title=The Blue Eagle at Work: Reclaiming Democratic Rights in the American Workplace|url={{google books |plainurl=y |id=q2eWTzf2mH8C}}|year=2005|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-4317-2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Victor|last=Rabinowitz|authorlink=Victor Rabinowitz|title=Unrepentant Leftist: A Lawyer's Memoir|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=iMaVigHoraAC}}|year=1996|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-02253-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Arthur Meier|last=Schlesinger|authorlink=Schlesinger Jr., Arthur M.|title=The Coming of the New Deal, 1933-1935|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=mj3VmJ38tHIC}}|year=2003|publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt|isbn=0-618-34086-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Landon R.Y.|last=Storrs|title=The Second Red Scare and the Unmaking of the New Deal Left|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=umlPTJksNdUC}}|year=2013|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-15396-4|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Limits on Technocratization of the Law: The Elimination of the National Labor Relations Board's Division of Economic Research|jstor=2095610|journal=American Sociological Review|date=1989-06-01|pages=341\u2013358|volume=54|issue=3|doi=10.2307/2095610|first=Robin|last=Stryker|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Tomlins|first=Christopher|title=The State and the Unions: Labor Relations, Law, and the Organized Labor Movement in America, 1880-1960|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=VnZCuAAACAAJ}}|year=1985|publisher=Cambridge University|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite news|title=Companies Challenge Labor Rulings|first=Melanie|last=Trottman|first2=Kris|last2=Maher|type=paper|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=March 9\u201310, 2013|pages=A1\u2013A2|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Stanley|last=Vittoz|title=New Deal labor policy and the American industrial economy|url={{google books|plainurl=y|id=TnGSK8IP8HUC}}|year=1987|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|isbn=978-0-8078-1729-2|ref=harv}}\n* Fischer, Fredric H.; Brent, Garren; and Truesdale, John C., eds. ''How to Take A Case Before the NLRB.'' 8th ed. Washington, D.C.: Bureau of National Affairs, 2008.\n* Gould IV, William B. ''Labored Relations: Law, Politics, and the NLRB.'' Cambridge, Mass.: MIT Press, 2001.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box}}\n\n* [http://www.nlrb.gov/ National Labor Relations Board official website]\n* [https://www.federalregister.gov/agencies/national-labor-relations-board National Labor Relations Board] in the [[Federal Register]]\n\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1935]]\n[[Category:History of labor relations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Labor relations boards]]\n[[Category:National Labor Relations Board| ]]\n[[Category:New Deal agencies]]\n", "name_user": "InternetArchiveBot", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Rescuing 1 sources and tagging 0 as dead.) #IABot (v2.0)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Labor_Relations_Board"}
{"title_page": "Aladdin Sane", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Aladdin Sane\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| cover      = DavisBowieAladdinSane.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1973|4|13|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 6 October 1972, 4\u201311 December 1972, c. 18\u201324 January 1973<ref name=\"Any Day Now\">Kevin Cann (2010). ''Any Day Now \u2013 The London Years: 1947\u20131974'': pp. 270, 277, 283</ref>\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Trident Studios|Trident]], London; RCA, New York City\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Glam rock]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[art rock]]\n}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=40|s=47}}\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Ken Scott]]\n* David Bowie\n}}\n| prev_title = [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Pin Ups]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Aladdin Sane\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[The Jean Genie]]\n | single1date = 24 November 1972\n | single2     = [[Drive-In Saturday]]\n | single2date = 6 April 1973\n | single3     = [[Time (David Bowie song)|Time]]\n | single3date = 13 April 1973\n | single4     = [[Let's Spend the Night Together#David Bowie version|Let's Spend the Night Together]]\n | single4date = July 1973\n}}\n}}\n'''''Aladdin Sane''''' is the sixth studio album by English musician [[David Bowie]], released by [[RCA Records]] on 13 April 1973. The follow-up to his breakthrough ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]'', it was the first album he wrote and released from a position of stardom.<ref name=carrmurr1>{{cite book |title=David Bowie: An Illustrated Record |last=Carr |first=Roy |authorlink=Roy Carr |author2=[[Charles Shaar Murray|Murray, Charles Shaar]] |year=1981 |publisher=Avon Books |location=New York |isbn=0-380-77966-8 |pages=52\u201356}}</ref> It was produced by Bowie and [[Ken Scott]] and features contributions from Bowie's backing band [[the Spiders from Mars]] \u2013 comprising [[Mick Ronson]], [[Trevor Bolder]] and [[Mick Woodmansey]]. It was recorded at [[Trident Studios]] in London and RCA Studios in New York City between legs of the [[Ziggy Stardust Tour]]. The album features a tougher and raunchier [[glam rock]] sound than its predecessor. The album cover, featuring a lightning bolt across Bowie's face, is regarded as one of his most iconic images.\n\nPreceded by the singles \"[[The Jean Genie]]\" and \"[[Drive-In Saturday]]\", ''Aladdin Sane'' was Bowie's most commercially successful record up to that point, peaking at No. 1 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and No. 17 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. The album also received positive reviews from music critics, although many found it to be inferior to its predecessor. It has since been regarded by Bowie biographers as one of his essential albums. In 2003, the album was ranked among six Bowie entries on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of the [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 greatest albums of all time]] (at No. 277), and No. 279 in a 2012 revised list. It was later ranked No. 77 on [[Pitchfork Media]]'s list of the top 100 albums of the 1970s. Songs from the album were performed frequently by Bowie on the Ziggy Stardust and [[Diamond Dogs Tour]]. The album has since been reissued multiple times and was remastered in 2013 for its 40th anniversary, which was included on the box set ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' in 2015.\n\n== \"Ziggy goes to America\" ==\nThe name of the album is a pun on \"A Lad Insane\". An early variation was \"Love Aladdin Vein\", which David Bowie dropped partly because of its drug connotations.<ref name=pegg2>{{cite book |title=The Complete David Bowie |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004 |origyear=2000 |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-903111-73-0 |pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Although technically a new Bowie 'character', Aladdin Sane was essentially a development of [[David Bowie#Ziggy Stardust|Ziggy Stardust]] in his appearance and persona, as evidenced on the cover by [[Brian Duffy (photographer)|Brian Duffy]] and in Bowie's live performances throughout 1973 that culminated in Ziggy's 'retirement' at the [[Hammersmith Odeon]] in July that year. Lacking the thematic flow found on its predecessor,<ref>[[Kris Needs]] (1983) ''Bowie: A Celebration'': p.29</ref> ''Aladdin Sane'' was described by Bowie himself as simply \"Ziggy goes to America\"; most of the tracks were observations he composed on the road during his [[Ziggy Stardust Tour]], which accounted for the place names following each song title on the original record labels.<ref name=carrmurr1 /> Biographer Christopher Sandford believed the album showed that Bowie \"was simultaneously appalled and fixated by America\".<ref name=\"Loving the Alien\">Christopher Sandford (1996, 1997). ''Loving the Alien'': p.109</ref>\n\nHis mixed feelings about the journey stemmed, in Bowie's words, from \"wanting to be up on the stage performing my songs, but on the other hand not really wanting to be on those buses with all those strange people&nbsp;... So ''Aladdin Sane'' was split down the middle.\"<ref name=\"pegg2806\">Pegg, Nicholas (2006). The Complete David Bowie (4th ed.). London: Reynolds & Hearn Ltd. pp. 286. {{ISBN|1-905287-15-1}}.</ref> This kind of \"[[schizophrenia]]\", as Bowie described it, was conveyed on the cover by his makeup, where a lightning bolt represents the duality of mind, although he would later tell friends that the \"lad insane\" of the album's title track was inspired by his brother Terry, who had been diagnosed as a schizophrenic.<ref name=\"pegg2806\" /><ref>Pegg, 2006, pp.19 and 286.</ref><ref>[http://www.superseventies.com/ac27aladdinsane.html Seventies' Greatest Album Covers: Aladdin Sane] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720075243/http://www.superseventies.com/ac27aladdinsane.html |date=20 July 2011 }}. Retrieved 2 July 2011.</ref> Bowie himself came up with the idea of the lightning bolt over his face, but said the teardrop was Brian Duffy's idea: \"He [Brian] put on that afterward, just popped it in there. I thought it was rather sweet.\"<ref name=RS87>{{citation | last=Loder | first=Kurt | title=Stardust Memories |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] | issue=498 | date=23 April 1987 | pages=74\u201377, 80, 82, 168, 171}}</ref> Regarded as one of the most iconic images of Bowie, it was called \"the Mona Lisa of album covers\" by Mick McCann writing for ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bowie By Duffy': Iconic Glam Photos Glitter At Foam In Amsterdam|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/21/bowie-by-duffy-glam-photos-at-foam_n_3312361.html|work=Huffington Post|date=25 March 2017|access-date=25 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326135420/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/21/bowie-by-duffy-glam-photos-at-foam_n_3312361.html|archive-date=26 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=David Bowie on the iconic lightning bolt from his Aladdin Sane cover|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/david-bowie-on-the-iconic-lightning-bolt-from-his-aladdin-sane-cover-a6808056.html|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 March 2017|access-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820001228/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/david-bowie-on-the-iconic-lightning-bolt-from-his-aladdin-sane-cover-a6808056.html|archive-date=20 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Production and style ==\nThe majority of ''Aladdin Sane'' was recorded at [[Trident Studios]] in London in January 1973, between legs of the Ziggy Stardust Tour. A desire to rush release the record was blamed for mixes on the [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]]-influenced \"[[Watch That Man]]\" and \"[[Cracked Actor (song)|Cracked Actor]]\" that buried vocals and harmonica, respectively.<ref name=carrmurr1 /><ref name=buckstrange1>{{cite book |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2000 |origyear=1999 |publisher=Virgin Books |location=London |isbn=0-7535-0457-X |pages=182\u2013189}}</ref> Bowie and producer [[Ken Scott]] later rebuffed this suggestion regarding \"Watch That Man\", claiming that a remix they produced which brought the vocals forward was considered by Mainman management and RCA Records to be inferior to the original that was eventually released.<ref name=buckstrange1 /><ref>[[David Bowie]] (2003). ''Aladdin Sane 30th Anniversary Edition'': CD liner notes</ref>\n\n''Aladdin Sane'' featured a tougher rock sound than its predecessor ''Ziggy Stardust'',<ref name=buckstrange1 /> particularly on tracks like \"[[Panic in Detroit]]\" (built around a [[Bo Diddley beat]]) and Bowie's breakneck version of the Stones' \"[[Let's Spend the Night Together]]\".<ref name=carrmurr1 /> The album  also explored unusual styles such as [[avant-garde jazz]] in the [[Aladdin Sane (song)|title track]] and [[Bertolt Brecht|Brechtian]] cabaret in \"[[Time (David Bowie song)|Time]]\". Both numbers were dominated by [[Mike Garson]]'s acclaimed piano work,<ref name=buckstrange1 /> which also featured heavily in the faux [[James Bond]] flamenco ballad \"[[Lady Grinning Soul]]\", inspired by singer [[Claudia Lennear]].<ref name=carrmurr1 />\n\n== Singles ==\nTwo hit singles that would be included on the album preceded its release, \"[[The Jean Genie]]\" and \"[[Drive-In Saturday]]\". The former (recorded at RCA's New York studios during the first leg of the Ziggy Stardust Tour in late 1972) was a heavy [[rhythm and blues|R&B]] chug with lyrics loosely based on [[Iggy Pop]],<ref name=pegg3>{{cite book |title=The Complete David Bowie |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004 |origyear=2000 |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-903111-73-0 |pages=110\u2013111}}</ref> the latter a futuristic [[doo-wop]] number describing a time when the population has to relearn sex by watching old movies.<ref name=carrmurr1 /> \"Time\" was later issued as a single in the US and Japan, and \"Let's Spend the Night Together\" in the US and Europe. In 1974, [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] released a version of \"Watch That Man\" as the B-side to her single \"[[The Man Who Sold the World]]\", produced by Bowie and [[Mick Ronson]].\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusicreview\">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=''Aladdin Sane'' \u2013 David Bowie|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/aladdin-sane-mw0000247727|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=10 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604031231/http://www.allmusic.com/album/aladdin-sane-mw0000247727|archive-date=4 June 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=blender>{{cite journal|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=3894|title=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|issue=47|date=May 2006|accessdate=14 July 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070624030927/http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=3894|archivedate=24 June 2007}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|title=Bowie's Many Faces Are Profiled On Compact Disc|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-06-10/entertainment/9002170173_1_space-oddity-scary-monsters-ziggy-stardust|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=10 June 1990|accessdate=14 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416150839/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-06-10/entertainment/9002170173_1_space-oddity-scary-monsters-ziggy-stardust|archive-date=16 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev4score = B+<ref name=christgau>{{cite book|chapter-url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=954|chapter=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane|accessdate=10 July 2008|title=Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the '70s|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|publisher=[[Ticknor and Fields]]|year=1981|isbn=0-89919-026-X|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/christgausrecord00robe_1}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|chapter=David Bowie|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th concise|year=2011|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|isbn=0-85712-595-8}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n|rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=mojo>{{cite journal|last=Buckley|first=David|title=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane (Parlophone)|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|issue=234|date=May 2013|page=102|issn=1351-0193}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n|rev7score = 9.0/10<ref name=\"Douglas Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|authorlink=Douglas Wolk|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21066-five-years-1969-1973/|title=David Bowie: Five Years 1969\u20131973|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=1 October 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206231305/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21066-five-years-1969-1973/|archive-date=6 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n|rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Q Review\">{{cite journal|last=O'Brien|first=Lucy|authorlink=Lucy O'Brien|title=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|issue=154|date=July 1999|page=132}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Walters|first=Barry|title=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=10 July 2003}}</ref>\n|rev10 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev10Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|chapter=David Bowie|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|edition=4th|year=2004|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/97 97\u201399]|isbn=0-7432-0169-8}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Aladdin Sane'' was released in the UK on 13 April 1973.<ref name=\"Any Day Now2\">Kevin Cann (2010). ''Any Day Now \u2013 The London Years: 1947\u20131974'': p. 291</ref> {{refn|group=nb|There is some debate about the release date. In 2018, the David Bowie official website stated that new evidence had come to light proving that the official release date was 20 April 1973, but because this was Good Friday (a public holiday in the UK), the album\nwas made available on 19 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/aladdin-sane-45th-anniversary-silver-vinyl-due-57611|title=Aladdin Sane 45th anniversary silver vinyl due|accessdate=15 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216084544/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/aladdin-sane-45th-anniversary-silver-vinyl-due-57611|archive-date=16 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} With a purported 100,000 copies ordered in advance,<ref name=buckstrange1 /> the album debuted at the top of the UK charts and reached No. 17 in America, making it Bowie's most successful album commercially in both countries to that date. The album is estimated to have sold 4.6 million copies worldwide, making it one of Bowie's highest-selling LPs.<ref name=sales>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/graphic/2012/jan/07/infomania-david-bowie|title=David Bowie: Infomania|last=Dee|first=Johnny|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 January 2012|accessdate=14 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108173839/http://www.theguardian.com/culture/graphic/2012/jan/07/infomania-david-bowie|archive-date=8 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[British Hit Singles & Albums|The Guinness Book of British Hit Albums]]'' notes that Bowie \"ruled the ''(British)'' album chart, accumulating an unprecedented 182 weeks on the list in 1973 with six different titles.\"<ref>*Roberts, David (editor). ''[[British Hit Singles & Albums|The Guinness Book of British Hit Albums]]'', p16. Guinness Publishing Ltd. 7th edition (1996). {{ISBN|0-85112-619-7}}</ref>\n\nCritical reaction was generally laudatory, if more enthusiastic in the US than in the UK.<ref name=pegg3 /> ''Rolling Stone'' remarked on \"Bowie's provocative melodies, audacious lyrics, masterful arrangements (with Mick Ronson) and production (with Ken Scott)\",<ref name=\"RS Gerson\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/aladdin-sane-19730719 |title=Aladdin Sane |date=19 July 1973 |author=Gerson, Ben |accessdate=21 March 2011 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BfjDZjSD?url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/aladdin-sane-19730719 |archive-date=25 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> while ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' called it a combination of \"raw energy with explosive rock\". In the British music press, however, letters columns accused Bowie of 'selling out' and ''Let it Rock'' magazine found the album to be more style than substance, considering that he had \"nothing to say and everything to say it with\".<ref name=pegg3 /> ''[[Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]] wrote a few years later that his favorite Bowie album had been ''Aladdin Sane'', \"the fragmented, rather second-hand collection of elegant hard rock songs (plus one [[Jacques Brel]]-style clinker) that fell between the ''Ziggy Stardust'' and ''Diamond Dogs'' concepts. That Bowie improved his music by imitating the Rolling Stones rather than by expressing himself is obviously a tribute to the Stones, but it also underlines how expedient Bowie's relationship to rock and roll has always been.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=5 April 1976|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/rock/bowie-76.php|title=David Bowie Discovers Rock and Roll|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=5 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821015701/http://robertchristgau.com/xg/rock/bowie-76.php|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] believed that ''Aladdin Sane'' followed the same pattern as its predecessor, but for \"both better and worse.\"<ref name=\"allmusicreview\" /> While he praised the different genres the album presented and being lyrically different, he criticised Bowie's cover of [[the Rolling Stones]]' \"[[Let's Spend the Night Together]]\", calling it \"oddly clueless\", he found that \"there's no distinctive sound or theme to make the album cohesive; it's Bowie riding the wake of Ziggy Stardust, which means there's a wealth of classic material here, but not enough focus to make the album itself a classic.\"<ref name=\"allmusicreview\" /> Douglas Wolk of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' also found the album similar to its predecessor, calling it \"effectively ''Ziggy Stardust II'', a harder-rocking if less original variation on the hit album.\"<ref name=\"Douglas Pitchfork\" /> He writes that while ''Ziggy Stardust'' ended with a \"vision of outreach to the front row\" in the lyrics of \"[[Rock 'n' Roll Suicide]]\", he describes ''Aladdin Sane'' as \"all alienation and self-conscious artifice, parodic gestures of intimacy directed to the theater balcony.\"<ref name=\"Douglas Pitchfork\" /> ''[[NME]]'' editors [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]] called the album \"oddly unsatisfying, considerably less than the sum of the parts\",<ref name=\"carrmurr1\" /> while Bowie encyclopedist [[Nicholas Pegg]] describes it as \"one of the most urgent, compelling and essential\" of his releases.<ref name=\"pegg1\">{{cite book|title=The Complete David Bowie|last=Pegg|first=Nicholas|publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd|year=2004|isbn=1-903111-73-0|location=London|pages=281\u2013283|authorlink=Nicholas Pegg|origyear=2000}}</ref> The ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' review by Ben Gerson pronounced it \"less manic than ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold The World]]'', and less intimate than ''[[Hunky Dory]]'', with none of its attacks of self-doubt.\"<ref name=\"RS Gerson\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n\nBowie performed all the tracks, except \"Lady Grinning Soul\", on his [[Ziggy Stardust Tour]], and many of them on the [[Diamond Dogs Tour]]. Live versions of all but \"The Prettiest Star\" and \"Lady Grinning Soul\" have been released on various discs including ''[[Ziggy Stardust: The Motion Picture]]'', ''[[David Live]]'' and ''Aladdin Sane \u2013 30th Anniversary''. \"The Jean Genie\" is the only song on the album that Bowie played in concert throughout his career. However \"Panic in Detroit\" also appeared regularly in Bowie's later years, a remake of which was cut in 1979 but not released until added as a bonus track to the Rykodisc CD of ''[[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]''.\n\nBelgian amateur astronomers at the MIRA Public Observatory in conjunction with [[Studio Brussel]] created a \"Bowie [[Asterism (astronomy)|asterism]]\" in homage to David Bowie in January 2016; it depicts the iconic lightning bolt of Aladdin Sane using the stars [[Sigma Librae]], [[Spica]], [[Zeta Centauri]], SAO&nbsp;204132, [[Sigma Octantis]],<ref>Internet images of the \"Bowie asterism\" actually indicate [[Delta Octantis]].</ref> [[HD 125288|SAO&nbsp;241641]] and [[Beta Trianguli Australis]] which were near Mars at the time of Bowie's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mira.be/nl/node/2371|title=StardustForBowie, Mira in the eye of a Cyclone&nbsp;... - MIRA|access-date=19 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123022701/http://www.mira.be/nl/node/2371|archive-date=23 January 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ddbbrussels.prezly.com/belgians-give-starman-bowie-own-constellation/conversations|title=Belgians give 'Starman' Bowie own constellation|publisher=ddbbrussels.prezly.com|access-date=18 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119004314/http://ddbbrussels.prezly.com/belgians-give-starman-bowie-own-constellation/conversations|archive-date=19 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/18/david-bowie-astronomers-give-the-starman-his-own-constellation|title=David Bowie: astronomers give the Starman his own constellation|first=Bonnie|last=Malkin|date=17 January 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223064913/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/18/david-bowie-astronomers-give-the-starman-his-own-constellation|archive-date=23 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/belgian-astronomers-pay-tribute-to-david-bowie-with-new-constellation-20160116|title=Astronomers Pay Tribute to Bowie With New Constellation|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111052824/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/belgian-astronomers-pay-tribute-to-david-bowie-with-new-constellation-20160116|archive-date=11 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe album was included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=7 February 2006|publisher=Universe|isbn=0-7893-1371-5}}</ref> In 2003, the album was ranked among six Bowie entries on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of the [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 greatest albums of all time]] (at No. 277), and No. 279 in a 2012 revised list.<ref name=\"RS 500 greatest\">{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/david-bowie-aladdin-sane-173418/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate=September 10, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830121218/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/david-bowie-aladdin-sane-173418/| archive-date=30 August 2019| url-status=live}}</ref> It was later ranked No. 77 on [[Pitchfork Media]]'s list of the top 100 albums of the 1970s.<ref name=\"p4k\">{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5932-top-100-albums-of-the-1970s/3/ |title=Staff Lists: Top 100 Album of the 1970s |date=23 June 2004 |accessdate=17 April 2013 |work=[[Pitchfork Media]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411011310/http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5932-top-100-albums-of-the-1970s/3/ |archive-date=11 April 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nTwo songs from the album, \"Cracked Actor\" and \"Time\" were included in the 2017 feature-length biographical documentary, and compilation Soundtrack, entitled ''[[Mick Ronson#In popular culture|Beside Bowie: The Mick Ronson Story]]''.\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks written by [[David Bowie]], except where noted.\n\n;Side one\n# \"[[Watch That Man]]\" \u2013 4:30\n# \"[[Aladdin Sane (song)|Aladdin Sane (1913-1938-197?)]]\" \u2013 5:06\n# \"[[Drive-In Saturday]]\" \u2013 4:33\n# \"[[Panic in Detroit]]\" \u2013 4:25\n# \"[[Cracked Actor (song)|Cracked Actor]]\" \u2013 3:01\n\n;Side two\n# \"[[Time (David Bowie song)|Time]]\" \u2013 5:15\n# \"[[The Prettiest Star]]\" \u2013 3:31\n# \"[[Let's Spend the Night Together#David Bowie version|Let's Spend the Night Together]]\" ([[Mick Jagger]], [[Keith Richards]]) \u2013 3:10\n# \"[[The Jean Genie]]\" \u2013 4:07\n# \"[[Lady Grinning Soul]]\" \u2013 3:54\n\n== Personnel ==\nAlbum credits per [[Nicholas Pegg]].{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=1,128}}\n*[[David Bowie]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, guitar, [[harmonica]], [[saxophone]], synthesizer, mellotron\n*[[Mick Ronson]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, piano, vocals\n*[[Trevor Bolder]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Mick Woodmansey|Mick \"Woody\" Woodmansey]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n\n=== Additional personnel ===\n*[[Mike Garson]]&nbsp;\u2013 piano\n*Ken Fordham&nbsp;\u2013 saxophone\n*Brian \"Bux\" Wilshaw&nbsp;\u2013 saxophone, [[flute]]s\n*Juanita \"Honey\" Franklin&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*[[Linda Lewis]]&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*[[Warren Peace|G.A. MacCormack]]&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n\n=== Production personnel ===\n*David Bowie&nbsp;\u2013 producer, [[arrangement]]s\n*Ken Scott&nbsp;\u2013 producer, [[recording engineer|engineer]]\n*Mick Moran&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n*Mick Ronson&nbsp;\u2013 arrangements\n\n== CD releases ==\n''Aladdin Sane'' was first released on CD in 1984 by RCA.\n\n=== 1990 Rykodisc/EMI ===\nDr. Toby Mountain at Northeastern Digital, [[Southborough, Massachusetts]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeasterndigital.com/audio/bios.htm |title=Northeastern Digital home page |accessdate=26 May 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071208131731/http://www.northeasterndigital.com/audio/bios.htm |archivedate=8 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> remastered ''Aladdin Sane'' from the original master tapes for [[Rykodisc]], which released it with no bonus tracks.\n\n=== 1999 EMI/Virgin ===\nThe album was remastered by [[Peter Mew]] at [[Abbey Road Studios]], and again released with no bonus tracks.\n\n=== 2003 EMI/Virgin ===\nIn 2003, a 2-disc version was released by EMI/Virgin. The second in a series of ''30th Anniversary 2CD Edition'' sets (along with ''Ziggy Stardust'' and ''Diamond Dogs''), this release includes a remastered version of the first disc. The second disc contains ten tracks, a few of which had been previously released on the 1989 collection [[Sound + Vision (box set)|''Sound + Vision'']].\n\n=== Bonus CD (2003 EMI/Virgin) ===\n#\"[[John, I'm Only Dancing]]\" ('Sax' version)&nbsp;\u2013 2:45\n#\"The Jean Genie\" (Single [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]] for single [[A-side and B-side|A-side]], 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 4:07\n#\"Time\" (Edit for single A-Side, 1973)&nbsp;\u2013 3:43\n#\"[[All the Young Dudes (song)|All the Young Dudes]]\" (Mono mix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:12\n#\"[[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\" (Live at [[Boston]] [[Wang Center for the Performing Arts|Music Hall]], 1 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 3:20 (From [[Sound + Vision (box set)|''Sound + Vision'']] [[CD-Video]])\n#\"[[The Supermen]]\" (Live at Boston Music Hall, 1 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 2:42 (From ''Sound + Vision'' CD-Video)\n#\"[[Life on Mars?]]\" (Live at Boston Music Hall, 1 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 3:25 (Previously unreleased)\n#\"John, I'm Only Dancing\" (Live at Boston Music Hall, 1 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 2:40 (From ''Sound + Vision'' CD-Video)\n#\"The Jean Genie\" (Live at [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]] [[Santa Monica Civic Auditorium|Civic Auditorium]], 20 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 4:10 (From ''[[Santa Monica '72]]'')\n#\"Drive-In Saturday\" (Live at [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]] [[Cleveland Public Auditorium|Public Auditorium]], 25 November 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 4:53 (Previously unreleased)\n\n=== 2013 Parlophone/AIR ===\nA 40th anniversary edition, remastered by Ray Staff at London's AIR Studios, was released in CD and digital download formats in April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/40th-anniversary-remaster-aladdin-sane-due-april-48686|title=40th anniversary remaster of Aladdin Sane due in April|work=David Bowie Official Website|access-date=11 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113220137/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/40th-anniversary-remaster-aladdin-sane-due-april-48686|archive-date=13 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThis 2013 remaster of the album was included in the 2015 [[box set]] ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)|Five Years 1969\u20131973]]'' and rereleased separately, in 2015\u20132016, in CD, vinyl and digital formats.<ref>[http://www.davidbowie.com/news/five-years-1969-1973-box-set-due-september-54571 FIVE YEARS 1969 \u2013 1973 box set due September] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218235114/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/five-years-1969-1973-box-set-due-september-54571 |date=18 February 2016 }} at davidbowie.com</ref><ref>[http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/how-to-buy-the-new-david-bowie-2015-remasters-individually How to buy the new David Bowie 2015 remasters individually] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303064623/http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/how-to-buy-the-new-david-bowie-2015-remasters-individually/ |date=3 March 2016 }} at superdeluxeedition.com</ref><ref>[http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/david-bowie-five-years-vinyl-available-separately-next-month David Bowie / 'Five Years' vinyl available separately next month] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216222656/http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/david-bowie-five-years-vinyl-available-separately-next-month |date=16 February 2016 }} at superdeluxeedition.com</ref>  A 12\" limited edition of the 2013 remaster, pressed in silver vinyl, was released in 2018 to mark the 45th anniversary of the album.<ref>[https://www.davidbowie.com/blog/2018/2/14/aladdin-sane-45th-anniversary-silver-vinyl-due Aladdin Sane 45th anniversary silver vinyl due] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709011059/https://www.davidbowie.com/blog/2018/2/14/aladdin-sane-45th-anniversary-silver-vinyl-due |date=9 July 2018 }} at davidbowie.com</ref>\n\n== Release history (selected) ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Region\n!Date\n!Label\n!Format\n!Catalog\n|-\n|United Kingdom (UK)\n|{{start date|1973|4|13|df=yes}}\n|RCA\n|LP\n|RS 1001<ref name=pegg4>{{cite book |title=The Complete David Bowie |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |year=2006 |edition=4th |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-905287-15-1 |page=284}}</ref>\n|-\n|United States (US)\n|{{start date|1973|4|13|df=yes}}\n|RCA\n|LP\n|AFL1 4852<ref name=ZSCAS>{{cite web |url=http://www.5years.com/aladdin.htm |title=Aladdin Sane (1973) |work=The Ziggy Stardust Companion |accessdate=10 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724090611/http://5years.com/aladdin.htm |archive-date=24 July 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|Worldwide\n|1985\n|RCA\n|CD\n|PD-83890/PCD1-4852<ref name=pegg4 /><ref name=iddb>{{cite web |author=Ruud Altenburg |url=http://www.illustrated-db-discography.nl/Album2.htm |title=Albums (1973\u20131977) |work=Illustrated db Discography |accessdate=10 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914181221/http://www.illustrated-db-discography.nl/Album2.htm |archive-date=14 September 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|US\n|{{start date|1990|7|13|df=yes}}\n|[[Rykodisc]]\n|CD\n|RCD-10135\n|-\n|Worldwide (except US)\n|{{start date|df=yes|1990|7}}\n|[[EMI]]\n|CD\n|EMC-3579/CDP 79 468 2<ref name=pegg4 />\n|-\n|Worldwide\n|{{start date|1999|9|28|df=yes}}\n|EMI/[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n|CD\n|7243 521902 0 1\n|-\n|Worldwide\n|{{start date|2003|5|26|df=yes}} (UK)<ref name=popmatrev>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/b/bowiedavid-aladdinsane.shtml |title=Aladdin Sane 30th Anniversary 2CD Edition |date=22 August 2003 |author=Davidson, John |accessdate=10 July 2008 |work=[[PopMatters]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119111442/http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/b/bowiedavid-aladdinsane.shtml |archive-date=19 November 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref><br />{{start date|2003|6|24|df=yes}}\n|EMI/Virgin\n|2 CD 30th Anniversary Edition\n|72435 83012 2\n|-\n|Worldwide\n|{{start date|2013|4|15|df=yes}}\n|EMI/Universal\n|CD 40th Anniversary Edition\n|5099993447423\n|-\n|}\n\n== Charts ==\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (1973)\n!Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Kent Music Report|Australian Kent Music Report Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"auchart\">{{cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]]|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book|location=St Ives, NSW|year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|7\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[RPM (magazine)|Canadian RPM Albums Chart]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.4852&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=ccntousk30frf6h4jsn237nm12|title=Top Albums/CDs \u2013 Volume 19, No. 20|work=[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]|format=PHP|date=30 June 1973|accessdate=31 January 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224000515/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?brws_s=1&file_num=nlc008388.4852&type=1&interval=24&PHPSESSID=ccntousk30frf6h4jsn237nm12|archive-date=24 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|20\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[MegaCharts|Dutch Mega Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"nlchart\">{{cite web|title=dutchcharts.nl David Bowie \u2013 ''Aladdin Sane'' |work=dutchcharts.nl |publisher=[[MegaCharts]] |url=http://dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Aladdin+Sane&cat=a |format=ASP |accessdate=31 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128010718/http://www.dutchcharts.nl/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Aladdin+Sane&cat=a |archivedate=28 January 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|4\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[SNEP|French SNEP Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"frchart\">{{cite web|url=http://infodisc.fr/Album_B.php |title=InfoDisc : Tous les Albums class\u00e9s par Artiste > Choisir Un Artiste Dans la Liste |publisher=infodisc.fr |format=PHP |accessdate=31 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111107224423/http://infodisc.fr/Album_B.php |archivedate=7 November 2011 |df=dmy }} ''Note: user must select 'David BOWIE' from drop-down.''</ref>\n|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Italian Albums Chart<ref name=\"itayearend\">{{cite web | url = http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/hp_yenda/lpe1973.htm | title = Hit Parade Italia \u2013 Gli album pi\u00f9 venduti del 1973 | language = Italian | publisher = hitparadeitalia.it | accessdate = 31 January 2014 | archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6Ctvt6mGd?url=http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/hp_yenda/lpe1973.htm | archive-date = 14 December 2012 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n|8\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Oricon|Japanese Oricon LP Chart]]<ref name=\"Jachart\">{{cite book|title=Oricon Album Chart Book: Complete Edition 1970\u20132005|publisher=Oricon Entertainment|location=Roppongi, Tokyo|year=2006|isbn=4-87131-077-9}}</ref>\n|41\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[Norwegian Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"norcharts\">{{cite web|title=norwegiancharts.com David Bowie \u2013 ''Aladdin Sane'' |url=http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Aladdin+Sane&cat=a |format=ASP |accessdate=31 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016202752/http://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Bowie&titel=Aladdin+Sane&cat=a |archivedate=16 October 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|11\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Swedish [[Sverigetopplistan|Kv\u00e4llstoppen Chart]]<ref name=\"swechart\">{{cite web|title=Swedish Charts 1972\u20131975/Kv\u00e4llstoppen \u2013 Listresultaten vecka f\u00f6r vecka > Maj 1973 > 15 Maj |url=http://www.hitsallertijden.nl/charts/swedish%20charts/SwedishCharts%200872-0875.pdf |work=hitsallertijden.nl |language=Swedish |accessdate=31 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529134518/http://www.hitsallertijden.nl/charts/swedish%20charts/SwedishCharts%200872-0875.pdf |archivedate=29 May 2017 }}''Note: [[Sverigetopplistan|Kv\u00e4llstoppen]] combined sales for albums and singles in the one chart; ''Aladdin Sane'' peaked at the number-nine on the list in the 2nd week of May 1973.''</ref>\n|5\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"UKchart\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/David%20Bowie/ |title=David Bowie > Artists > Official Charts |publisher=[[UK Albums Chart]] |accessdate=31 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103181930/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/david%20bowie/ |archivedate=3 November 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"USchart\">{{cite web|title=allmusic ((( ''Aladdin Sane'' > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums )))|website=AllMusic|url={{AllMusic|class=album|id=r2482/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}}|accessdate=31 August 2011}}</ref>\n|17\n|}\n\n=== Year-end charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n!Chart (1973)\n!Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|French Albums Chart<ref name=\"frayearend\">{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/B-CD_1973.php |title=Les Albums (CD) de 1973 par InfoDisc |language=French |format=PHP |publisher=infodisc.fr |accessdate=31 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027132903/http://www.infodisc.fr/B-CD_1973.php |archivedate=27 October 2012 }}</ref>\n|39\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Italian Albums Chart<ref name=\"itayearend\" />\n|32\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Albums Chart]]<ref name=\"UKYearend\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071217020442/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/album_chart_history_1973.php|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/album_chart_history_1973.php|title=The Official UK Charts Company : ALBUM CHART HISTORY|archivedate=17 December 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2007}}</ref>\n|2\n|}\n\n== Certifications ==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|artist=David Bowie|title=Aladdin Sane|type=album|award=Gold|relyear=1973|certyear=1981|certref=<ref>{{cite web|title=Les Certifications depuis 1973: Albums|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Album_Certifications.php|publisher=Infodisc.fr|accessdate=3 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019163029/https://www.infodisc.fr/Album_Certifications.php|archive-date=19 October 2017|url-status=live}} (select \"David Bowie\" from drop-down list)</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=album|title=Aladdin Sane|artist=David Bowie|award=Platinum|relyear=1973|certyear=2019|access-date=3 January 2019}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=album|title=Aladdin Sane|artist=David Bowie|award=Gold|relyear=1973|access-date=31 January 2014}}\n{{certification Table Bottom}}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n;Sources\n*{{cite book |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |title=The Complete David Bowie |year=2011 |publisher=Titan Books |location=London |isbn=978-0-85768-290-1 |edition=6th|authorlink=Nicholas Pegg|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last=Weisbard |first=Eric |author2=Craig Marks |title=Spin Alternative Record Guide |publisher=Vintage Books |year=1995 |isbn=0-679-75574-8}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite book |last=Goddard |first=Simon  |title=Ziggyology: A Brief History of Ziggy Stardust |publisher=Ebury |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-09-194888-7}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130724090611/http://5years.com/aladdin.htm ''Aladdin Sane'' at The Ziggy Stardust Companion]\n{{David Bowie}}\n\n[[Category:David Bowie albums]]\n[[Category:1973 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Ken Scott]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Trident Studios]]\n[[Category:EMI Records albums]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n[[Category:Rykodisc albums]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records albums]]\n[[Category:Parlophone albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Aladdin Sane\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| cover      = DavisBowieAladdinSane.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1973|4|13|df=y}}\n| recorded   = 6 October 1972, 4\u201311 December 1972, c. 18\u201324 January 1973<ref name=\"Any Day Now\">Kevin Cann (2010). ''Any Day Now \u2013 The London Years: 1947\u20131974'': pp. 270, 277, 283</ref>\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Trident Studios|Trident]], London; RCA, New York City\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Glam rock]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[art rock]]\n}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=40|s=47}}\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Ken Scott]]\n* David Bowie\n}}\n| prev_title = [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Pin Ups]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Aladdin Sane\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[The Jean Genie]]\n | single1date = 24 November 1972\n | single2     = [[Drive-In Saturday]]\n | single2date = 6 April 1973\n | single3     = [[Time (David Bowie song)|Time]]\n | single3date = 13 April 1973\n | single4     = [[Let's Spend the Night Together#David Bowie version|Let's Spend the Night Together]]\n | single4date = July 1973\n}}\n}}\n'''''Aladdin Sane''''' is the sixth studio album by English musician [[David Bowie]], released by [[RCA Records]] on 13 April 1973. The follow-up to his breakthrough ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]]'', it was the first album he wrote and released from a position of stardom.<ref name=carrmurr1>{{cite book |title=David Bowie: An Illustrated Record |last=Carr |first=Roy |authorlink=Roy Carr |author2=[[Charles Shaar Murray|Murray, Charles Shaar]] |year=1981 |publisher=Avon Books |location=New York |isbn=0-380-77966-8 |pages=52\u201356}}</ref> It was produced by Bowie and [[Ken Scott]] and features contributions from Bowie's backing band [[the Spiders from Mars]] \u2013 comprising [[Mick Ronson]], [[Trevor Bolder]] and [[Mick Woodmansey]]. It was recorded at [[Trident Studios]] in London and RCA Studios in New York City between legs of the [[Ziggy Stardust Tour]]. The album features a tougher and raunchier [[glam rock]] sound than its predecessor. The album cover featuring a lightning bolt across Bowie's face is regarded as one of his most iconic images.\n\nPreceded by the lead single \"[[The Jean Genie]]\", ''Aladdin Sane'' was Bowie's most commercially successful record up to that point, peaking at No. 1 on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and No. 17 on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. The album also received positive reviews from music critics, although many found it to be inferior to its predecessor. It has since been regarded by Bowie biographers as one of his essential albums. In 2003, the album was ranked among six Bowie entries on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of the [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 greatest albums of all time]] (at No. 277), and No. 279 in a 2012 revised list. It was later ranked No. 77 on [[Pitchfork Media]]'s list of the top 100 albums of the 1970s. Songs from the album were performed frequently by Bowie on the Ziggy Stardust and [[Diamond Dogs Tour]]. The album has since been reissued multiple times and was remastered in 2013 for its 40th anniversary, which was included on the box set ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)]]'' in 2015.\n\n== \"Ziggy goes to America\" ==\nThe name of the album is a pun on \"A Lad Insane\". An early variation was \"Love Aladdin Vein\", which David Bowie dropped partly because of its drug connotations.<ref name=pegg2>{{cite book |title=The Complete David Bowie |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004 |origyear=2000 |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-903111-73-0 |pages=20\u201321}}</ref> Although technically a new Bowie 'character', Aladdin Sane was essentially a development of [[David Bowie#Ziggy Stardust|Ziggy Stardust]] in his appearance and persona, as evidenced on the cover by [[Brian Duffy (photographer)|Brian Duffy]] and in Bowie's live performances throughout 1973 that culminated in Ziggy's 'retirement' at the [[Hammersmith Odeon]] in July that year. Lacking the thematic flow found on its predecessor,<ref>[[Kris Needs]] (1983) ''Bowie: A Celebration'': p.29</ref> ''Aladdin Sane'' was described by Bowie himself as simply \"Ziggy goes to America\"; most of the tracks were observations he composed on the road during his [[Ziggy Stardust Tour]], which accounted for the place names following each song title on the original record labels.<ref name=carrmurr1 /> Biographer Christopher Sandford believed the album showed that Bowie \"was simultaneously appalled and fixated by America\".<ref name=\"Loving the Alien\">Christopher Sandford (1996, 1997). ''Loving the Alien'': p.109</ref>\n\nHis mixed feelings about the journey stemmed, in Bowie's words, from \"wanting to be up on the stage performing my songs, but on the other hand not really wanting to be on those buses with all those strange people&nbsp;... So ''Aladdin Sane'' was split down the middle.\"<ref name=\"pegg2806\">Pegg, Nicholas (2006). The Complete David Bowie (4th ed.). London: Reynolds & Hearn Ltd. pp. 286. {{ISBN|1-905287-15-1}}.</ref> This kind of \"[[schizophrenia]]\", as Bowie described it, was conveyed on the cover by his makeup, where a lightning bolt represents the duality of mind, although he would later tell friends that the \"lad insane\" of the album's title track was inspired by his brother Terry, who had been diagnosed as a schizophrenic.<ref name=\"pegg2806\" /><ref>Pegg, 2006, pp.19 and 286.</ref><ref>[http://www.superseventies.com/ac27aladdinsane.html Seventies' Greatest Album Covers: Aladdin Sane] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720075243/http://www.superseventies.com/ac27aladdinsane.html |date=20 July 2011 }}. Retrieved 2 July 2011.</ref> Bowie himself came up with the idea of the lightning bolt over his face, but said the teardrop was Brian Duffy's idea: \"He [Brian] put on that afterward, just popped it in there. I thought it was rather sweet.\"<ref name=RS87>{{citation | last=Loder | first=Kurt | title=Stardust Memories |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] | issue=498 | date=23 April 1987 | pages=74\u201377, 80, 82, 168, 171}}</ref> Regarded as one of the most iconic images of Bowie, it was called \"the Mona Lisa of album covers\" by Mick McCann writing for ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bowie By Duffy': Iconic Glam Photos Glitter At Foam In Amsterdam|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/21/bowie-by-duffy-glam-photos-at-foam_n_3312361.html|work=Huffington Post|date=25 March 2017|access-date=25 March 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326135420/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/21/bowie-by-duffy-glam-photos-at-foam_n_3312361.html|archive-date=26 March 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=David Bowie on the iconic lightning bolt from his Aladdin Sane cover|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/david-bowie-on-the-iconic-lightning-bolt-from-his-aladdin-sane-cover-a6808056.html|newspaper=The Independent|date=25 March 2017|access-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170820001228/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/david-bowie-on-the-iconic-lightning-bolt-from-his-aladdin-sane-cover-a6808056.html|archive-date=20 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Production and style ==\nThe majority of ''Aladdin Sane'' was recorded at [[Trident Studios]] in London in January 1973, between legs of the Ziggy Stardust Tour. A desire to rush release the record was blamed for mixes on the [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]]-influenced \"[[Watch That Man]]\" and \"[[Cracked Actor (song)|Cracked Actor]]\" that buried vocals and harmonica, respectively.<ref name=carrmurr1 /><ref name=buckstrange1>{{cite book |title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story |last=Buckley |first=David |year=2000 |origyear=1999 |publisher=Virgin Books |location=London |isbn=0-7535-0457-X |pages=182\u2013189}}</ref> Bowie and producer [[Ken Scott]] later rebuffed this suggestion regarding \"Watch That Man\", claiming that a remix they produced which brought the vocals forward was considered by Mainman management and RCA Records to be inferior to the original that was eventually released.<ref name=buckstrange1 /><ref>[[David Bowie]] (2003). ''Aladdin Sane 30th Anniversary Edition'': CD liner notes</ref>\n\n''Aladdin Sane'' featured a tougher rock sound than its predecessor ''Ziggy Stardust'',<ref name=buckstrange1 /> particularly on tracks like \"[[Panic in Detroit]]\" (built around a [[Bo Diddley beat]]) and Bowie's breakneck version of the Stones' \"[[Let's Spend the Night Together]]\".<ref name=carrmurr1 /> The album  also explored unusual styles such as [[avant-garde jazz]] in the [[Aladdin Sane (song)|title track]] and [[Bertolt Brecht|Brechtian]] cabaret in \"[[Time (David Bowie song)|Time]]\". Both numbers were dominated by [[Mike Garson]]'s acclaimed piano work,<ref name=buckstrange1 /> which also featured heavily in the faux [[James Bond]] flamenco ballad \"[[Lady Grinning Soul]]\", inspired by singer [[Claudia Lennear]].<ref name=carrmurr1 />\n\n== Singles ==\nTwo hit singles that would be included on the album preceded its release, \"[[The Jean Genie]]\" and \"[[Drive-In Saturday]]\". The former (recorded at RCA's New York studios during the first leg of the Ziggy Stardust Tour in late 1972) was a heavy [[rhythm and blues|R&B]] chug with lyrics loosely based on [[Iggy Pop]],<ref name=pegg3>{{cite book |title=The Complete David Bowie |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |authorlink=Nicholas Pegg |year=2004 |origyear=2000 |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-903111-73-0 |pages=110\u2013111}}</ref> the latter a futuristic [[doo-wop]] number describing a time when the population has to relearn sex by watching old movies.<ref name=carrmurr1 /> \"Time\" was later issued as a single in the US and Japan, and \"Let's Spend the Night Together\" in the US and Europe. In 1974, [[Lulu (singer)|Lulu]] released a version of \"Watch That Man\" as the B-side to her single \"[[The Man Who Sold the World]]\", produced by Bowie and [[Mick Ronson]].\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusicreview\">{{cite web|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|title=''Aladdin Sane'' \u2013 David Bowie|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/aladdin-sane-mw0000247727|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=10 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604031231/http://www.allmusic.com/album/aladdin-sane-mw0000247727|archive-date=4 June 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=blender>{{cite journal|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=3894|title=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|issue=47|date=May 2006|accessdate=14 July 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070624030927/http://www.blender.com/guide/reviews.aspx?id=3894|archivedate=24 June 2007}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|4|4}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|title=Bowie's Many Faces Are Profiled On Compact Disc|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-06-10/entertainment/9002170173_1_space-oddity-scary-monsters-ziggy-stardust|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=10 June 1990|accessdate=14 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416150839/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-06-10/entertainment/9002170173_1_space-oddity-scary-monsters-ziggy-stardust|archive-date=16 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the Seventies|Christgau's Record Guide]]''\n|rev4score = B+<ref name=christgau>{{cite book|chapter-url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=954|chapter=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane|accessdate=10 July 2008|title=Christgau's Record Guide: Rock Albums of the '70s|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|publisher=[[Ticknor and Fields]]|year=1981|isbn=0-89919-026-X|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/christgausrecord00robe_1}}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n|rev5Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|chapter=David Bowie|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th concise|year=2011|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|isbn=0-85712-595-8}}</ref>\n|rev6 = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n|rev6score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=mojo>{{cite journal|last=Buckley|first=David|title=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane (Parlophone)|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|issue=234|date=May 2013|page=102|issn=1351-0193}}</ref>\n|rev7 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n|rev7score = 9.0/10<ref name=\"Douglas Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last=Wolk|first=Douglas|authorlink=Douglas Wolk|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21066-five-years-1969-1973/|title=David Bowie: Five Years 1969\u20131973|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=1 October 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160206231305/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/21066-five-years-1969-1973/|archive-date=6 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n|rev8score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Q Review\">{{cite journal|last=O'Brien|first=Lucy|authorlink=Lucy O'Brien|title=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|issue=154|date=July 1999|page=132}}</ref>\n|rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev9score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Walters|first=Barry|title=David Bowie: Aladdin Sane|journal=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=10 July 2003}}</ref>\n|rev10 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n|rev10Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|chapter=David Bowie|title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|edition=4th|year=2004|pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/97 97\u201399]|isbn=0-7432-0169-8}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Aladdin Sane'' was released in the UK on 13 April 1973.<ref name=\"Any Day Now2\">Kevin Cann (2010). ''Any Day Now \u2013 The London Years: 1947\u20131974'': p. 291</ref> {{refn|group=nb|There is some debate about the release date. In 2018, the David Bowie official website stated that new evidence had come to light proving that the official release date was 20 April 1973, but because this was Good Friday (a public holiday in the UK), the album\nwas made available on 19 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/aladdin-sane-45th-anniversary-silver-vinyl-due-57611|title=Aladdin Sane 45th anniversary silver vinyl due|accessdate=15 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216084544/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/aladdin-sane-45th-anniversary-silver-vinyl-due-57611|archive-date=16 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} With a purported 100,000 copies ordered in advance,<ref name=buckstrange1 /> the album debuted at the top of the UK charts and reached No. 17 in America, making it Bowie's most successful album commercially in both countries to that date. The album is estimated to have sold 4.6 million copies worldwide, making it one of Bowie's highest-selling LPs.<ref name=sales>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/graphic/2012/jan/07/infomania-david-bowie|title=David Bowie: Infomania|last=Dee|first=Johnny|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 January 2012|accessdate=14 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108173839/http://www.theguardian.com/culture/graphic/2012/jan/07/infomania-david-bowie|archive-date=8 January 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[British Hit Singles & Albums|The Guinness Book of British Hit Albums]]'' notes that Bowie \"ruled the ''(British)'' album chart, accumulating an unprecedented 182 weeks on the list in 1973 with six different titles.\"<ref>*Roberts, David (editor). ''[[British Hit Singles & Albums|The Guinness Book of British Hit Albums]]'', p16. Guinness Publishing Ltd. 7th edition (1996). {{ISBN|0-85112-619-7}}</ref>\n\nCritical reaction was generally laudatory, if more enthusiastic in the US than in the UK.<ref name=pegg3 /> ''Rolling Stone'' remarked on \"Bowie's provocative melodies, audacious lyrics, masterful arrangements (with Mick Ronson) and production (with Ken Scott)\",<ref name=\"RS Gerson\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/aladdin-sane-19730719 |title=Aladdin Sane |date=19 July 1973 |author=Gerson, Ben |accessdate=21 March 2011 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6BfjDZjSD?url=http://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/aladdin-sane-19730719 |archive-date=25 October 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> while ''[[Billboard magazine|Billboard]]'' called it a combination of \"raw energy with explosive rock\". In the British music press, however, letters columns accused Bowie of 'selling out' and ''Let it Rock'' magazine found the album to be more style than substance, considering that he had \"nothing to say and everything to say it with\".<ref name=pegg3 /> ''[[Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]] wrote a few years later that his favorite Bowie album had been ''Aladdin Sane'', \"the fragmented, rather second-hand collection of elegant hard rock songs (plus one [[Jacques Brel]]-style clinker) that fell between the ''Ziggy Stardust'' and ''Diamond Dogs'' concepts. That Bowie improved his music by imitating the Rolling Stones rather than by expressing himself is obviously a tribute to the Stones, but it also underlines how expedient Bowie's relationship to rock and roll has always been.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=5 April 1976|url=https://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/rock/bowie-76.php|title=David Bowie Discovers Rock and Roll|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=5 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170821015701/http://robertchristgau.com/xg/rock/bowie-76.php|archive-date=21 August 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] of [[AllMusic]] believed that ''Aladdin Sane'' followed the same pattern as its predecessor, but for \"both better and worse.\"<ref name=\"allmusicreview\" /> While he praised the different genres the album presented and being lyrically different, he criticised Bowie's cover of [[the Rolling Stones]]' \"[[Let's Spend the Night Together]]\", calling it \"oddly clueless\", he found that \"there's no distinctive sound or theme to make the album cohesive; it's Bowie riding the wake of Ziggy Stardust, which means there's a wealth of classic material here, but not enough focus to make the album itself a classic.\"<ref name=\"allmusicreview\" /> Douglas Wolk of ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' also found the album similar to its predecessor, calling it \"effectively ''Ziggy Stardust II'', a harder-rocking if less original variation on the hit album.\"<ref name=\"Douglas Pitchfork\" /> He writes that while ''Ziggy Stardust'' ended with a \"vision of outreach to the front row\" in the lyrics of \"[[Rock 'n' Roll Suicide]]\", he describes ''Aladdin Sane'' as \"all alienation and self-conscious artifice, parodic gestures of intimacy directed to the theater balcony.\"<ref name=\"Douglas Pitchfork\" /> ''[[NME]]'' editors [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]] called the album \"oddly unsatisfying, considerably less than the sum of the parts\",<ref name=\"carrmurr1\" /> while Bowie encyclopedist [[Nicholas Pegg]] describes it as \"one of the most urgent, compelling and essential\" of his releases.<ref name=\"pegg1\">{{cite book|title=The Complete David Bowie|last=Pegg|first=Nicholas|publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd|year=2004|isbn=1-903111-73-0|location=London|pages=281\u2013283|authorlink=Nicholas Pegg|origyear=2000}}</ref> The ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' review by Ben Gerson pronounced it \"less manic than ''[[The Man Who Sold the World (album)|The Man Who Sold The World]]'', and less intimate than ''[[Hunky Dory]]'', with none of its attacks of self-doubt.\"<ref name=\"RS Gerson\" />\n\n==Legacy==\n\nBowie performed all the tracks, except \"Lady Grinning Soul\", on his [[Ziggy Stardust Tour]], and many of them on the [[Diamond Dogs Tour]]. Live versions of all but \"The Prettiest Star\" and \"Lady Grinning Soul\" have been released on various discs including ''[[Ziggy Stardust: The Motion Picture]]'', ''[[David Live]]'' and ''Aladdin Sane \u2013 30th Anniversary''. \"The Jean Genie\" is the only song on the album that Bowie played in concert throughout his career. However \"Panic in Detroit\" also appeared regularly in Bowie's later years, a remake of which was cut in 1979 but not released until added as a bonus track to the Rykodisc CD of ''[[Scary Monsters (And Super Creeps)]]''.\n\nBelgian amateur astronomers at the MIRA Public Observatory in conjunction with [[Studio Brussel]] created a \"Bowie [[Asterism (astronomy)|asterism]]\" in homage to David Bowie in January 2016; it depicts the iconic lightning bolt of Aladdin Sane using the stars [[Sigma Librae]], [[Spica]], [[Zeta Centauri]], SAO&nbsp;204132, [[Sigma Octantis]],<ref>Internet images of the \"Bowie asterism\" actually indicate [[Delta Octantis]].</ref> [[HD 125288|SAO&nbsp;241641]] and [[Beta Trianguli Australis]] which were near Mars at the time of Bowie's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mira.be/nl/node/2371|title=StardustForBowie, Mira in the eye of a Cyclone&nbsp;... - MIRA|access-date=19 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160123022701/http://www.mira.be/nl/node/2371|archive-date=23 January 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ddbbrussels.prezly.com/belgians-give-starman-bowie-own-constellation/conversations|title=Belgians give 'Starman' Bowie own constellation|publisher=ddbbrussels.prezly.com|access-date=18 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160119004314/http://ddbbrussels.prezly.com/belgians-give-starman-bowie-own-constellation/conversations|archive-date=19 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/18/david-bowie-astronomers-give-the-starman-his-own-constellation|title=David Bowie: astronomers give the Starman his own constellation|first=Bonnie|last=Malkin|date=17 January 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=10 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223064913/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jan/18/david-bowie-astronomers-give-the-starman-his-own-constellation|archive-date=23 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/belgian-astronomers-pay-tribute-to-david-bowie-with-new-constellation-20160116|title=Astronomers Pay Tribute to Bowie With New Constellation|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111052824/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/belgian-astronomers-pay-tribute-to-david-bowie-with-new-constellation-20160116|archive-date=11 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe album was included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=7 February 2006|publisher=Universe|isbn=0-7893-1371-5}}</ref> In 2003, the album was ranked among six Bowie entries on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of the [[The 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 greatest albums of all time]] (at No. 277), and No. 279 in a 2012 revised list.<ref name=\"RS 500 greatest\">{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/david-bowie-aladdin-sane-173418/| year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time Rolling Stone\u2019s definitive list of the 500 greatest albums of all time| publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]| accessdate=September 10, 2019| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190830121218/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/david-bowie-aladdin-sane-173418/| archive-date=30 August 2019| url-status=live}}</ref> It was later ranked No. 77 on [[Pitchfork Media]]'s list of the top 100 albums of the 1970s.<ref name=\"p4k\">{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5932-top-100-albums-of-the-1970s/3/ |title=Staff Lists: Top 100 Album of the 1970s |date=23 June 2004 |accessdate=17 April 2013 |work=[[Pitchfork Media]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130411011310/http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5932-top-100-albums-of-the-1970s/3/ |archive-date=11 April 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nTwo songs from the album, \"Cracked Actor\" and \"Time\" were included in the 2017 feature-length biographical documentary, and compilation Soundtrack, entitled ''[[Mick Ronson#In popular culture|Beside Bowie: The Mick Ronson Story]]''.\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll tracks written by [[David Bowie]], except where noted.\n\n;Side one\n# \"[[Watch That Man]]\" \u2013 4:30\n# \"[[Aladdin Sane (song)|Aladdin Sane (1913-1938-197?)]]\" \u2013 5:06\n# \"[[Drive-In Saturday]]\" \u2013 4:33\n# \"[[Panic in Detroit]]\" \u2013 4:25\n# \"[[Cracked Actor (song)|Cracked Actor]]\" \u2013 3:01\n\n;Side two\n# \"[[Time (David Bowie song)|Time]]\" \u2013 5:15\n# \"[[The Prettiest Star]]\" \u2013 3:31\n# \"[[Let's Spend the Night Together#David Bowie version|Let's Spend the Night Together]]\" ([[Mick Jagger]], [[Keith Richards]]) \u2013 3:10\n# \"[[The Jean Genie]]\" \u2013 4:07\n# \"[[Lady Grinning Soul]]\" \u2013 3:54\n\n== Personnel ==\nAlbum credits per [[Nicholas Pegg]].{{sfn|Pegg|2011|p=1,128}}\n*[[David Bowie]]&nbsp;\u2013 vocals, guitar, [[harmonica]], [[saxophone]], synthesizer, mellotron\n*[[Mick Ronson]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, piano, vocals\n*[[Trevor Bolder]]&nbsp;\u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Mick Woodmansey|Mick \"Woody\" Woodmansey]]&nbsp;\u2013 drums\n\n=== Additional personnel ===\n*[[Mike Garson]]&nbsp;\u2013 piano\n*Ken Fordham&nbsp;\u2013 saxophone\n*Brian \"Bux\" Wilshaw&nbsp;\u2013 saxophone, [[flute]]s\n*Juanita \"Honey\" Franklin&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*[[Linda Lewis]]&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*[[Warren Peace|G.A. MacCormack]]&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n\n=== Production personnel ===\n*David Bowie&nbsp;\u2013 producer, [[arrangement]]s\n*Ken Scott&nbsp;\u2013 producer, [[recording engineer|engineer]]\n*Mick Moran&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n*Mick Ronson&nbsp;\u2013 arrangements\n\n== CD releases ==\n''Aladdin Sane'' was first released on CD in 1984 by RCA.\n\n=== 1990 Rykodisc/EMI ===\nDr. Toby Mountain at Northeastern Digital, [[Southborough, Massachusetts]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northeasterndigital.com/audio/bios.htm |title=Northeastern Digital home page |accessdate=26 May 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071208131731/http://www.northeasterndigital.com/audio/bios.htm |archivedate=8 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> remastered ''Aladdin Sane'' from the original master tapes for [[Rykodisc]], which released it with no bonus tracks.\n\n=== 1999 EMI/Virgin ===\nThe album was remastered by [[Peter Mew]] at [[Abbey Road Studios]], and again released with no bonus tracks.\n\n=== 2003 EMI/Virgin ===\nIn 2003, a 2-disc version was released by EMI/Virgin. The second in a series of ''30th Anniversary 2CD Edition'' sets (along with ''Ziggy Stardust'' and ''Diamond Dogs''), this release includes a remastered version of the first disc. The second disc contains ten tracks, a few of which had been previously released on the 1989 collection [[Sound + Vision (box set)|''Sound + Vision'']].\n\n=== Bonus CD (2003 EMI/Virgin) ===\n#\"[[John, I'm Only Dancing]]\" ('Sax' version)&nbsp;\u2013 2:45\n#\"The Jean Genie\" (Single [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]] for single [[A-side and B-side|A-side]], 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 4:07\n#\"Time\" (Edit for single A-Side, 1973)&nbsp;\u2013 3:43\n#\"[[All the Young Dudes (song)|All the Young Dudes]]\" (Mono mix)&nbsp;\u2013 4:12\n#\"[[Changes (David Bowie song)|Changes]]\" (Live at [[Boston]] [[Wang Center for the Performing Arts|Music Hall]], 1 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 3:20 (From [[Sound + Vision (box set)|''Sound + Vision'']] [[CD-Video]])\n#\"[[The Supermen]]\" (Live at Boston Music Hall, 1 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 2:42 (From ''Sound + Vision'' CD-Video)\n#\"[[Life on Mars?]]\" (Live at Boston Music Hall, 1 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 3:25 (Previously unreleased)\n#\"John, I'm Only Dancing\" (Live at Boston Music Hall, 1 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 2:40 (From ''Sound + Vision'' CD-Video)\n#\"The Jean Genie\" (Live at [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]] [[Santa Monica Civic Auditorium|Civic Auditorium]], 20 October 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 4:10 (From ''[[Santa Monica '72]]'')\n#\"Drive-In Saturday\" (Live at [[Cleveland, Ohio|Cleveland]] [[Cleveland Public Auditorium|Public Auditorium]], 25 November 1972)&nbsp;\u2013 4:53 (Previously unreleased)\n\n=== 2013 Parlophone/AIR ===\nA 40th anniversary edition, remastered by Ray Staff at London's AIR Studios, was released in CD and digital download formats in April 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/40th-anniversary-remaster-aladdin-sane-due-april-48686|title=40th anniversary remaster of Aladdin Sane due in April|work=David Bowie Official Website|access-date=11 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113220137/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/40th-anniversary-remaster-aladdin-sane-due-april-48686|archive-date=13 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThis 2013 remaster of the album was included in the 2015 [[box set]] ''[[Five Years (1969\u20131973)|Five Years 1969\u20131973]]'' and rereleased separately, in 2015\u20132016, in CD, vinyl and digital formats.<ref>[http://www.davidbowie.com/news/five-years-1969-1973-box-set-due-september-54571 FIVE YEARS 1969 \u2013 1973 box set due September] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218235114/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/five-years-1969-1973-box-set-due-september-54571 |date=18 February 2016 }} at davidbowie.com</ref><ref>[http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/how-to-buy-the-new-david-bowie-2015-remasters-individually How to buy the new David Bowie 2015 remasters individually] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303064623/http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/how-to-buy-the-new-david-bowie-2015-remasters-individually/ |date=3 March 2016 }} at superdeluxeedition.com</ref><ref>[http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/david-bowie-five-years-vinyl-available-separately-next-month David Bowie / 'Five Years' vinyl available separately next month] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216222656/http://www.superdeluxeedition.com/news/david-bowie-five-years-vinyl-available-separately-next-month |date=16 February 2016 }} at superdeluxeedition.com</ref>  A 12\" limited edition of the 2013 remaster, pressed in silver vinyl, was released in 2018 to mark the 45th anniversary of the album.<ref>[https://www.davidbowie.com/blog/2018/2/14/aladdin-sane-45th-anniversary-silver-vinyl-due Aladdin Sane 45th anniversary silver vinyl due] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180709011059/https://www.davidbowie.com/blog/2018/2/14/aladdin-sane-45th-anniversary-silver-vinyl-due |date=9 July 2018 }} at davidbowie.com</ref>\n\n== Release history (selected) ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Region\n!Date\n!Label\n!Format\n!Catalog\n|-\n|United Kingdom (UK)\n|{{start date|1973|4|13|df=yes}}\n|RCA\n|LP\n|RS 1001<ref name=pegg4>{{cite book |title=The Complete David Bowie |last=Pegg |first=Nicholas |year=2006 |edition=4th |publisher=Reynolds & Hearn Ltd |location=London |isbn=1-905287-15-1 |page=284}}</ref>\n|-\n|United States (US)\n|{{start date|1973|4|13|df=yes}}\n|RCA\n|LP\n|AFL1 4852<ref name=ZSCAS>{{cite web |url=http://www.5years.com/aladdin.htm |title=Aladdin Sane (1973) |work=The Ziggy Stardust Companion |accessdate=10 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724090611/http://5years.com/aladdin.htm |archive-date=24 July 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|Worldwide\n|1985\n|RCA\n|CD\n|PD-83890/PCD1-4852<ref name=pegg4 /><ref name=iddb>{{cite web |author=Ruud Altenburg |url=http://www.illustrated-db-discography.nl/Album2.htm |title=Albums (1973\u20131977) |work=Illustrated db Discography |accessdate=10 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914181221/http://www.illustrated-db-discography.nl/Album2.htm |archive-date=14 September 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|US\n|{{start date|1990|7|13|df=yes}}\n|[[Rykodisc]]\n|CD\n|RCD-10135\n|-\n|Worldwide (except US)\n|{{start date|df=yes|1990|7}}\n|[[EMI]]\n|CD\n|EMC-3579/CDP 79 468 2<ref name=pegg4 />\n|-\n|Worldwide\n|{{start date|1999|9|28|df=yes}}\n|EMI/[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n|CD\n|7243 521902 0 1\n|-\n|Worldwide\n|{{start date|2003|5|26|df=yes}} (UK)<ref name=popmatrev>{{cite web |url=http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/b/bowiedavid-aladdinsane.shtml |title=Aladdin Sane 30th Anniversary 2CD Edition |date=22 August 2003 |author=Davidson, John |accessdate=10 July 2008 |work=[[PopMatters]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119111442/http://www.popmatters.com/music/reviews/b/bowiedavid-aladdinsane.shtml |archive-date=19 November 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref><br />{{start date|2003|6|24|df=yes}}\n|EMI/Virgin\n|2 CD 30th Anniversary Edition\n|72435 83012 2\n|-\n|Worldwide\n|{{start date|2013|4|15|df=yes}}\n|EMI/Universal\n|CD 40th Anniversary Edition\n|5099993447423\n|-\n|}\n\n== Charts ==\n\n=== Weekly charts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!Chart (1973)\n!Position\n